        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What you are describing sounds more like recoil control.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That isn't the point of burst fire mode selectors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>5.56x45mm platforms like the M16 and M4 are already quite manageable in terms of recoil, especially when compared to the 7.62x51mm battle rifles (e.g. the M14) that they replaced.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Rather, the key here is trigger discipline in stressful situations, which is **not** an easy skill to master.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Based on the sources I've read, there were two main ideas behind implementing burst-fire mode options, and none had to do with recoil control: \- Reducing ammo expenditure by preventing jittery soldiers from mag-dumping at the first sign of enemy contact... and \- Increasing hit probability when compared to single shots If burst fire modes were about recoil control, then why did the U.S. not simply retrofit the M14 with a safe-semi-3 round burst fire control group instead of adopting a completely new rifle and cartridge for general issue *in the middle of a war?*</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What burst fire modes do is handle the trigger discipline for the shooter.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When shooting a weapon in full auto, you should be firing short, controlled bursts of 3\~5 rounds anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This takes considerable practice and training to do with platforms that have a high cyclic rate of fire, and it takes even more practice and training to be able to successfully do this in a stressful situation, i.e. several unfriendly locals have just come out of nowhere and are trying their damndest to kill you and your buddies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In an ideal world, we'd be able to train every soldier to the point that he can fire single shots from a MAC-11 with its fire selector on full auto.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But we don't live in an ideal world, so some folks several decades ago thought that having a safe-semi-3 round burst fire control group was a convenient workaround to the costly, time-consuming alternative of training millions of men--many of whom had never even held a firearm before entering the armed forces--to such an exacting level of skill.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_0_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And in a lot of ways, it made sense, because weapons handling and marksmanship are just two of the many, many skills that a modern soldier needs to be proficient in, and depending on his MOS, he may never even fire his service rifle in anger anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few things.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, using a hardened steel or tungsten core instead of lead (which is relatively soft) and often loading the cartridges hotter (adding more propellant or using propellant mixes that provide higher muzzle velocities) gives better armour penetrating performance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whereas a lead core bullet will just flatten or deform upon impact with ballistic armour, an armour-penetrating bullet will strike that armour with little deformation and is more likely to punch a hole through it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This does often come at the expense of poorer performance against unarmoured targets, since the hard, fast AP round will just make a bullet sized hole straight through the target rather than tumbling, fragmenting, or doing other nasty things to maximise tissue damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If that projectile doesn't strike a vital organ, shatter a bone, or sever critical arteries, the target may still be able to continue fighting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>FMJ has poor penetration stats in Tarkov because most ballistic armour is designed to defeat FMJ projectiles (and some AP loads) of a given calibre as a baseline.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, and game balance, I guess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If 95% of threats you face are going to be shooting at you with 7.62x39mm FMJ, it makes sense to design your armour to defeat at least a couple hits from that as opposed to trying to design armour to resist that ultra-rare custom-tooled tungsten core 7.62x39mm special which never saw much daylight outside of a government R amp;D lab.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the way, the Geneva Convention has never banned hollowpoint bullets, flamethrowers, or poison gas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The use of bullets that expand on impact is proscribed by the St. Petersburg Declaration to the Hague Convention around the turn of the 20th century, well before the Geneva Convention even existed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Flamethrowers were never banned by any international treaty although the use of incendiary weapons in civilian areas is proscribed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I mention all this because you'll see a lot of people claim that hollowpoint ammo, flamethrowers, poison gas, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_1_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>are "banned by the Geneva Convention."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_2_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If they are rejuvenation potions (purple ones), keep them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_2_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In Act II, you can get a Horadric Cube that will allow you to combine 3 rejuvs into a Full Rejuvenation Potion that will instantly restore 100% of your health *and* mana upon using.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_2_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Full Rejuvs are good for those "oh shit" moments... like when you face the Act II boss ;).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_2_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If these are normal health and mana potions (red and blue), why the heck are you keeping those in your stash?!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_2_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You do know that the vendors sell those in unlimited quantity, right?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_2_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>:D The only potions really worth buying from vendors are mana potions, since normal enemies will drop more than enough health potions to fill up your entire inventory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_3_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Strength requirement shouldn't change, since Treachery runeword (Shael Thul Lem) doesn't modify item equip requirements, last time I checked.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_3_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You should need only 30 strength for that breastplate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Natalya and the Assassin character were originally goth-pale white lasses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They changed them to rather unprepossessing Asian women for reasons that are anyone's guess (although Natalya didn't get beaten with the ugly stick quite as hard as the player character).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's also noticeable that now Natalya looks *completely* different from the player character, with armour that actually looks much better than anything the playable Assassin can obtain.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One other small, but interesting change is that her comment after you complete Blade of the Old Religion was truncated... or censored.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In the original game, she'd remark, "Few things could tempt me to go up against the Children of Zakarum, and their midget minions."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In D2R, the reference to "midget minions" was removed altogether, which makes zero sense, since the Flayers are not "Children of Zakarum" (you meet the actual Zakarumites later in Kurast proper, near Travincal).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't want to speculate about why these changes were made, but the uglification of both Assassins, the "censoring" of her starting armour, and the censoring of Natalya's dialogue (because "midget" is apparently an offensive term even when applied to man-eating demons) does make me wonder a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_4_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, it's nothing I will lose sleep over, and it doesn't stop me from enjoying the game, though I do hope that modders can restore the original appearance of these characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm going to venture an unpopular opinion to say that I mostly agree with this reviewer about the character models.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For all of you mocking that individual, I'll give him the benefit of the doubt and assume that English is not his first language, hence some of the more... colourful phrases.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With the exception of the Necromancer and Druid, they all look pretty bad.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do, however, think that the new Necro and Druid look significantly better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Necromancer looks the part for a mage who spends most of his time hanging out in dank crypts and mausoleums.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And the Druid looks like someone who genuinely has lycanthropy--he looks more barbaric and intimidating than the Barbarian.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the rest... the Paladin was always black in the original.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I don't see why they gave him a peasant face and bad hair.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They could have just given him a priestly tonsure, as he is a warrior monk.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Barbarian just looks sad--like Geglash's drinking buddy after a three-day bender rather than a fearsome berserker who doesn't need armour, because armour is for cowards, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the Sorc, Amazon, and Assassin... I actually think the Amazon looks the best of those three.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Assassin was ruined, full stop.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A homely, beady-eyed\* Asian woman in a burlap jumpsuit isn't what I envision when I think of the LoD Assassin or hear her voice acting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Sorceress as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just give the Amazon back her old armour, and she would look pretty damn close to the original (they fixed the Willem Dafoe face a long time ago).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What I don't get is that the Rogues in Act I still look great, and even Natalya in Act III looks decent enough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why couldn't they use Natalya's model (minus the red cape) for the Assassin player character?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, these unwelcome changes don't stop me from enjoying the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I may find the Assassin a bit too hideous to play as, but then again, I never played the Assassin much in the original LoD. And I probably will roll an Assassin at some point to learn this class, especially with respecs making the learning process a bit less painful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm having fun with my Paladin and Necromancer (the classes I tended to play most frequently in original D2 and LoD), and I'll probably roll an Amazon and a Sorceress pretty soon as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have hope for modders to fix these questionable art choices, but until then, I'm still having a blast with this game, and not getting anywhere as much work, PT, or house cleaning done as I should be, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\*Before some of you more sensitive lot downvote me to hell for this particular remark, I am not suggesting that Asians in general are ugly or beady-eyed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_5_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just some of them are, as is the case with every other ethnicity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to resistances, I'd strongly suggest prioritising lightning resistances first--lightning damage is very common, what with Lightning Enchanted unique monsters and those damned beetles in Act II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you don't have any lightning resists when fighting those, you'll be in for a very bad time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After lightning, I'd suggest priotising fire resistance, since fire damage is very common, especially in Act IV.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can deal with poison with antidote potions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cold damage isn't very common before Act V, and again, you can boost it temporarily with thawing potions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's no reason for you not to have any resistances by Act II, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you checking the vendors every time you return to town?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Picking up and identifying +resist charms?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Equipping rings and ammys that give elemental resists?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One reason why elemental resistances in D2 are so important is that magic attacks have no attack rating--they will **always** hit you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As you may know, there are are [several](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) Cube recipes that are guaranteed to give you amulets or rings with elemental resists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_6_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Good luck and happy demon hunting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_7_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even as someone who mostly enjoyed D2 as a singleplayer experience, I agree with you wholeheartedly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_7_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The whole point of immunities is to encourage party synergy and cooperation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_7_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are playing solo, then you need to plan out your build carefully to take immune monsters into account.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_7_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, immunities only are an issue on Hell difficulty, and I doubt that everyone plays every character until Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_7_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The immunes that I hate the most are physical immunes, however... those things can go to hell (though I think it would be a holiday for them there).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_8_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, don't go spend it all at once at Gheed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_8_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I don't recommend gambling at all in Normal difficulty, unless you really have a lot of gold burning a hole in your pocket and you are looking for an item ahead of where it would normally be available.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_8_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, gambling a crystal sword, morning star, or broadsword in Act I--normally you'd only find those weapons in Act II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_8_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I'd argue that this is really a waste of money, as your Act I kit is going to be replaced pretty fast anyway, and whatever you could gamble from Gheed won't last you that long until you find something better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_8_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You technically *can* gamble set and unique items, but the chances are so low that it's not worth banking on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_9_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By "magic" if you mean blue staves and wands, the sockets on those aren't useless at all, although I wouldn't waste a quest reward on a blue item!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_9_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sure, you cannot turn blue items into runewords, but you can fill those sockets with jewels or runes that can add desirable mods.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_9_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, if you put a Tir rune in that socket, you'd get 2 mana back after every kill.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_9_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+elemental damage mods from gems and runes (e.g. +1-20 lightning damage) only apply to physical attacks made with the weapon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_9_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It doesn't apply to spells which have no attack rating.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_10_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I can recall, the set bonuses would only appear when you have the items equipped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_10_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This was the case in original D2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_10_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The bonuses wouldn't show up when you have them just sitting in your inventory/stash--you actually need to have them equipped on yourself or your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_11_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sell it to Charsi in Act I. It's an old trope in D2 to refer to undesirable/less than BiS (best in slot) items as "Charsi food"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_12_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's the durability on those Draculs?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_12_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may be able to use it for a while, since durability on gloves/armours tends to decrease much slower than that on weapons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_13_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep cubing those flawed and standard gems to upgrade them into perfect gems.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_13_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, even finding a few +resists is crucial on a melee character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_13_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Casters or ranged characters can get by with less than optimal resists for a while, but you will need to play very carefully.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_14_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also applies only to physical attacks made directly with the weapon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_14_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't going to get +15 poison damage added to your Sorc's fireball spell just because you have a Grand Charm of Venom in your inventory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_14_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will get that added poison damage if your Sorc starts whacking things with her staff, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_14_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I recall correctly, however, that added damage from charms do apply to Assassin kick attacks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_14_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It doesn't add onto Paladin smite attacks, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_14_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, remember that life and mana leech **only** apply to physical attacks, not spells.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_15_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree with you *almost* 100%.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_15_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The art direction is nearly impeccable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_15_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't like what they did with some of the character designs (Assassin, Amazon, Sorceress, and Barbarian mostly; the Paladin looks ok, and I love the new Necro and Druid looks).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_15_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However that's honestly a minor point since the game is played from an isometric perspective anyway, and I am mostly more focused on what's going on around me than how aesthetically pleasing my character looks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_15_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo 2 Resurrected is what Diablo 3 **should have been** in terms of art direction and overall tone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_16_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I noticed that as well, and it thought was a bit odd.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_16_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I think you'd need to go AFK for *days* on end for that to actually threaten your character, as I've never noticed it take off more than one point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_17_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Check Ormus' shop in Act III normal for a Gnarled Staff of Teleportation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_17_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may need to reset his inventory several times (exit and re-enter town), but eventually you'll find one for sale.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_18_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What changed with Lower Resist curse in the Chaos Sanctuary?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_18_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I can recall, the Oblivion Knights **always** had access to Lower Resist since the pre-expansion days of Diablo II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_18_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What was *really* horrible was when they used to be able to cast Iron Maiden 0\_0 in pre-expansion Diablo II and before 1.10 in LoD. If VV were truly evil, they'd add that back in...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep in mind that if you use the Horadric Cube recipe to upgrade (or "up") a unique item, this will **not** turn it into the equivalent exceptional unique.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In other words, upgrading a Peasant Crown (unique War Hat, exceptional version of the standard cap) will **not** turn it into a Harlequin Crest (commonly referred to as just "Shako").</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Upping a unique will also increase its level requirement (in addition to the strength/dex requirements to equip it).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can upgrade uniques in normal if you can find the runes to do so.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't really bother doing so as it would probably be a waste of runes you can use for runewords later down the line.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few other random tips: \- Chipped gems still have uses even into the lategame.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You need them for upgrading runes past Thul. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All belts from Plated Belt onward will have 16 slots.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Exceptional versions of early game belts (e.g. Demonhide Sash, Sharkskin Belt) have lower strength requirements than the Plated Belt \- There are no locked chests in Act IV, so you can save an inventory space and ditch your keys during this Act, as you won't miss out on being able to open any chests just because you don't have keys in your inventory. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Assassins don't need keys to open locked chests. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Prioritise lightning and fire resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These are the most common forms of elemental damage throughout the game. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runewords can only be made in non-magic (i.e. not blue, yellow, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Check the runeword formulae **carefully**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sceptres do *not* count as maces for runewords that state "mace."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_19_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And spears are *not* considered polearms in this game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_20_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, most of the quests and areas in Act I are really quite straightforward--there aren't any side areas that can lead you off the beaten path.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_20_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only potentially missable quest is The Forgotten Tower.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_20_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What really confounds new players in Diablo II is character builds and the like.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_20_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, and some of the areas in Act III (e.g. Arachnid Lair vs. Spider Cavern, or Flayer Jungle vs. Great Marsh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_20_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Great Marsh is usually a pointless zone, although it can link the Spider Forest and Flayer Jungle).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_21_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are right, it doesn't have to be gnarled.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_21_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've also found a Battle Staff of Teleport (with Teleport Charges).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_21_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Checking all of the staves in Ormus' inventory each time you return to town is a good idea.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_21_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only ones I wouldn't look at are the War Staves--not because they cannot spawn with that mod, but largely because they take up too much damn space in the stash, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_21_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that recharging the staff at the blacksmiths in each town can be a bit pricey, especially when the charges are nearly depleted.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_21_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can recharge the staff yourself with an Ort rune + chipped gem if you want to save the gold or cannot afford it at the current moment.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_22_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The issue I can see with this idea is that mercenaries follow you from Act to Act.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_22_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If these blessings aren't *too* competitive, then they'll fall in the same category as the Act I, III, and V mercs--not worth using over the Act II mercs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_22_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, I'm not sure of why you hate the hirelings--they work great as meatshields or aura bots, and with decent equipment, they can really help a lot as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_22_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having access to teleport (innate skill, from Enigma, or just an item with teleport charges) solves 99% of merc management issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_22_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>More important, your hireling can be very helpful for dealing with immune monsters as well, and getting that first kill as a summon necro.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_22_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only way I can see these blessings being a viable alternative to hirelings is if they worked similar to Paladin auras, and that would make certain runewords almost useless if you could just pay Tyrael some coin to get those same bonuses!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, I don't recall Lower Resist ever being removed from Oblivion Knights, but then again, it's been a while since I played the OG D2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So I'll take your word for it, even though the Arreat Summit, the Diablo Wiki, and pretty much every source I've seen never stated that Lower Resist was ever removed from them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just Iron Maiden in 1.11 (not 1.10).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Regardless my favorite build was usually a Paladin Zealot, as you can imagine the Iron Maiden curse those things used to have scared me a heck of a lot more than Lower Resist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Getting cursed with Iron Maiden mid-zeal was usually a death sentence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, since I was fighting them up close and personal, they'd always hit me with Decrepify and shuffle off if I got within melee range of them and didn't kill them quickly enough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If hit with Lower Resist from a distance, I'd usually just turn on Cleansing and back off.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For ranged builds, if the Lower Resist was really nasty (lowering my resistances into the negative), I'd just TP back to town, have Jamella remove it, then go back and continue the slaughter.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If they took away Lower Resist from Oblivion Knights, there wouldn't be much to make them dangerous anymore.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_23_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I do agree that it makes them extremely nasty for hardcore characters, especially on NM and Hell--if one hits you with Lower Resist whilst you're in the middle of a group of Venom Lords, you'll be barbecued in an instant.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_24_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People usually mention the Gnarled Staves because those are among the most common type of staff Ormus in Act III Normal sells, I think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I understand what you mean.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sometimes the Mercs do take a bit of babysitting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, in my experience, that usually means keeping them from killing mobs which I don't want to engage because I'm making a beeline for a particular boss (e.g. the Countess) and I don't want to have to check for extra loot from whatever they killed!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I'm curious about how your Act II mercs seem to have trouble hitting enemies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mine (hired in Act II Normal; I'm currently in Act I NM) destroys mobs even faster than I do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In my experiences in OG Diablo II, even on Hell Difficulty, Mercs lasted quite a while except against Act bosses, which seem to have a built in damage multiplier against hirelings, as they can melt them pretty fast.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I'm running a Paladin Zealot, so my Fanatacism boosts his damage considerably.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Until the end of Act V, I was actually using the free Rogue hireling you get from the Blood Raven quest, and she worked just fine.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only times she died were against Diablo and to a pack of Unique Blood Lords in one of the portal side areas in Act V. I only switched because I realised that my physical defence rating was too low, so I wanted a Defiance merc to help boost that a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As others have pointed out, if you equip your merc decently (decent weapon, + resist gear, and life leech) they tend to hold their own pretty well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_25_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't care for the Act III mercs as their spells barely damage anything unless you are running Conviction or Lower Resist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think being dumped into the lava would do much to faze Diablo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Andariel, maybe, as according to Deckard Cain, she "is not fond of fire."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But to Diablo?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Being dunked in the lava would probably be like a spa to him, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, the Dark Wanderer was *far* from helpless against Tyrael--he was tanking and dodging hits from an angelic blade  gt;!(the same one that Tyrael uses to shatter the Worldstone)!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>lt; like a boss, despite being an "unarmed human."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for why Tyrael didn't stop Marius earlier, I think this is hinted at throughout the game: the angels are severely restricted from directly interfering with mortals too much.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Tyrael is somewhat of a maverick as far as archangels go, as even his interference (and assistance to the player) is really pushing the rules of engagement as far as mortals go.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If Tyrael could just do what you said, then he could easily lop off the Dark Wanderer's head as soon as he showed his ugly mug in Tal Rasha's Tomb.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_26_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Problem solved, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, I've never noticed that bug.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have noticed that Act II mercs don't activate their aura *instantly*, but will do so in combat after a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have observed that the Defiance aura *does* apply when I have Holy Shield active.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, what do you mean by "summon" your mercenary?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do you mean resurrect him?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If so, then it could just be that the merc doesn't activate his aura immediately until you've been in combat for a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_27_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That could just coincide with when your Holy Shield runs out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_28_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is true to some degree.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_28_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason is that anything above P1 will mean additional items drops that can take the place of runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_28_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The added reason to run the Countess on P1 is for faster kills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm curious about how does killing a demon "make it all worse"?!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Using that logic, then the player's actions in Act I and Act II really screw things up--killing Andariel and Duriel would have been the worst course of action.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But yet, *everyone* including Deckard Cain tells you to kill Andariel.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are correct that demons can manifest in the world again after they are slain.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Death isn't permanent for them the way that it is for humans.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I'm pretty sure that it's a major inconvenience even for a Prime Evil, because they certainly do whatever they can to avoid being killed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Baal and Diablo travel in disguise until the very end of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mephisto corrupts the entire Zakarum priesthood to protect him and even has them hide the entrance to his lair to avoid unfriendly visitors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All that seems like a lot for creatures which don't mind getting killed, because they only come back stronger!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for imprisoning them, **that** actually seems like the worst thing--the entire plot of the game centers around the fact that the Horadrim tried imprisoning the Prime Evils, and we see how well that worked out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I'm not considering the plot of Diablo 3 at all in my analysis--I don't remember that game well, as I barely played it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_29_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I do think that if Tyrael had killed the Dark Wanderer, that would have saved everyone a lot of trouble.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_30_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Two tips for the OP and everyone--make sure that the polearm in question is *actually* a polearm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_30_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spears don't count as polearms in this game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_30_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't try using a Bardiche or Lochaber Axe (exceptional version of Bardiche) for this.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_30_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Polearms in that class (Bardiche/Lochaber Axe/Ogre Axe) can only get three sockets maximum.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Get the Horadric Cube ASAP.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is an extremely invaluable tool that will serve you well throughout the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And whatever you do, keep it in your inventory, as it will effectively give you +5 net bag space (it takes up 4 spaces, but has 9 inside).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's no way to turn magic items into normal ones, as far as I can recall.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are a number of ways to get the socketed (grey) items you need: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Buy 'em from Act I and II vendors on **normal** difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Past Act II Normal, the vendors will exclusively sell magic (blue) items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This works best when you are looking for staves/wands/sceptres with +skills for a specific class.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, if you want to make a White (Dol + Io) wand for a future Bonemancer, you'll want to check Drognan in Act II normal repeatedly for a bone wand with at least +2 Bone Spear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that this *must* be a Bone Wand since that's the lowest tier wand that can get + 2 sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The item you get doesn't need to be socketed at the vendor because... 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Use the Act V quest reward (Siege on Harrogath) to add sockets to the item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Larzuk will *usually* add the max number of sockets for that item's ilvl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The items ilvl is an invisible stat based on where the item was dropped/obtained from.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, you wouldn't get 6-socket crystal swords in Normal difficulty, as no crystal swords with the ilvl to support 6 sockets will typically drop in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Use a [Horadric Cube](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) recipe to add sockets to the item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't guaranteed to get the max number of sockets, so hopefully you have a spare in case it turns out suboptimal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Find the socketed item normally.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In this case, running areas with high monster density (e.g. Cow Level) with *low* magic find may help.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And make sure to check the max sockets on an item and the item type carefully before making it into a runeword.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Orbs (one-handed Sorc-only weapons) don't count as staves for runewords like Leaf.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sceptres don't count as maces for runewords that specify "mace" usually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_31_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you really mess up, there is a Horadric Cube recipe to clear the socketed items, but it requires a Hel rune (which you won't find for a while), and it will also destroy the socketed items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, Act 3  gt; Act 4  gt; Act 1  gt; gt; Act 2  gt; gt; gt; Act 5.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've somewhat disliked Act II since I first played Diablo II classic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It might just be because starting a new game on Normal, you don't really feel the power increase between Acts 1 and 2 the way you do when you reach Act III, and gain access to a variety of new equipment from the start, whilst in Act II, you'll pretty much be using the same kit from Act I for a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also wish that they had extended Act IV instead of making Act V a 6-quest location.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Too many of the areas in Act V seem copy-pasted, and after a while, icy caves and tundras gets pretty repetitive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The outdoor areas in Act V also feel way too large compared to the previous Act.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Everyone complains about the annoying enemies in Act III, but for me, Act II introduces some of the most irritating monsters in the game: leapers, scarabs (beetles with innate lightning enchantment), sabre cats, and the burrowers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_32_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act II is also home to the Maggot Lair, which needs no further explanation as one of the worst levels in the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act IV has some great atmosphere.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I recall the first time I saw the Outer Steppes on D2 classic in 2000.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was just a middle school lad at the time, so you can imagine that seeing that burnt, blasted landscape in what were great graphics for that era left a deep impression on me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I continued playing D2 through high school, so it resonated with me even more when I was reading the *Divine Comedy*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add the splendour of the Pandemonium Fortress, and it's easily the most memorable act.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, it has four areas outside of the town, since the Chaos Sanctuary is a different zone from the River of Flame.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I definitely have to agree with everyone who says that Act I is great.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's something newer games don't seem to do much anymore--hit the player with some great content out of the gate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One can compare the greatness of Act I to how Episode 1 of Doom is actually the best part of the game... although unlike Doom, Diablo 2 still remains fun throughout all five acts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_33_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act V is a bit of a slog, but it serves as a great buffer to help the player level and gear up a bit more for Nightmare difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This + 100.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Crushing blow will really help speed boss-killing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Two easy-to-make runewords for this are Strength (Amn + Tir) in *any* two-socket melee weapon, and Black (Thul + Io + Nef) in any three-socket Club, Hammer or Mace.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that Sceptres don't count for Black.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add in some extra CB from crafted Blood Gloves (which will also add some life leech), and you should be good.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can easily get the runes for Strength in Normal difficulty without too much trouble, but finding an Io rune in Normal is pretty unlikely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Knockback on Black can be a mixed bag.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It can be a bit annoying in an open area, but it can also help get you out of trouble if you get yourself surrounded.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act bosses are immune to knockback, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_34_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And since Oblivion Knights don't have Iron Maiden anymore, the Chaos Sanctuary isn't *quite* as sphincter-clenching once your damage really starts to spike.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_35_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pretty much this.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_35_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo and his brothers had been gone from Hell for a while (over 260 years, if we assume that the Horadrim used the soulstones successfully in the same year that Tyrael gave them to the mages).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_35_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can imagine that demons being what they are, the other Lesser Evils and other upstarts would be getting some funny ideas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_35_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Big D needed to go back into Hell to whip them into shape and show them who's really in charge, because the other demons' agendas and plans wouldn't necessarily align with those of the Three.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most caster builds will have mana issues starting out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The guide which I followed ([https://d2.maxroll.gg/guides/necromancer-leveling](https://d2.maxroll.gg/guides/necromancer-leveling) ) actually suggests raising Energy to 45.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes, that's on the Group tag, but so far in Act II NM, I find it's been working well for me, and that is playing on /players 5 the entire time. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't play on /players 8 as a Necromancer largely because Corpse Explosion doesn't scale with increased monster life.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Using a Spirit sword will help negate mana issues, as will an Insight on your Merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, this Bone necro wasn't my first character--I reached NM first on my Paladin (which I respecced into a Hammerdin around that time), then I farmed the Countess repeatedly to get enough runes (on both Normal and NM) to make two Insights and three Spirits for both my Pally and my Necro.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was also lucky enough to get a Dol and Io rune from NM Countess runs which my Bonemancer has made good use of as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you find you are getting destroyed that early in the game, it's likely because you have no resistances, or you didn't put any points into vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even on your Necromancer, be sure to prioritise resistances (lightning and fire especially).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't raise your strength to more than 48 points--and even that's a stretch, as no armour you'd want to use throughout Normal will require more than that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't need dexterity as a Bonemancer (since you aren't fighting in melee), and you can dump the rest into vitality once you have your desired strength and Energy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, you shouldn't need to "explore all areas for gear," because there are certain areas that are better to farm than others.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On Normal, I'd only recommend doing Countess runs and maybe Cows for runes and potential runeword bases from the latter.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can run NM Countess for slightly higher runes you'll have trouble finding on Normal (e.g. Dol, Io, Sol, Shael) that you will need for your runewords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On NM, I'd run bosses (Mephisto, Baal, maybe even Andariel?)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>with high MF for items if you find you are lacking once you get to Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if you are busy (and I don't know if you work 10-hour days like I do), that doesn't mean you cannot play more than one character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I'd recommend having multiple characters, as a lot of time, you'll find gear that is great for other builds/classes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Otherwise, what are you going to do with all those great bows you keep finding, but that you have no Amazon to give them to?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_36_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or if you find yourself a Buriza in late nightmare, what are you going to do with it other than turn it into Charsi food?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Make sure you get that Teleport staff in Act III.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll have to check Ormus' inventory each time you return to town, but it will make your life a lot easier.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that repairing it can get a bit pricey, so be sure you are making plenty of gold.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pick up staves, wands, and sceptres with + skills for particular classes, as these usually sell for the max amount at vendors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless they are ethereal or cracked.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, put at least a couple points into Corpse Explosion, if you haven't already.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>According to the original D2 devs, it's the best skill in the game.... it really is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not uncommon for Corpse Explosion to start a chain reaction of death in crowded areas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Bonemancer, it will be your crowd-pleaser, since Bone Spear isn't exactly an AoE skill; Teeth don't work like shotgun pellets (more teeth hitting a target !</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_37_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>= more damage, apparently).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_38_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>id Software knew what they were doing ;) Episode 1 of Doom (and Quake, if I recall correctly, but it's been over 20 years, lol) were released as shareware--free demos.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_38_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You had to order the rest of the game via phone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_38_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>From a marketing standpoint, it made a lot of sense for them to frontload the best content first, so you'd want to pay for the rest of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_38_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some parts of Episode 4 feel like a giant middle finger from the devs (especially E4M1 on Ultraviolence).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_39_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Before you can get an Insight runeword on your Act 2 merc, your best bet is to go with one belt slot of health pots and 3 of mana potions... along with an inventory full of them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_39_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't be afraid to put *some* points into Energy when levelling up, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_39_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll probably respec at some point, and by that time, you'll have more than enough gear to give you a metric ton of mana and regen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_39_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's likely that you'll get access to a Spirit runeword (4 os crystal sword or broadsword) well before you get an Insight--the runes for Spirit (Tal Thul Ort Amn) are readily obtainable in Normal difficulty, whilst you might be hard pressed to find a Sol on your own before Nightmare.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_39_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, any sword capable of holding 4 sockets will work, but Crystal Swords and Broadswords are best as they have the lowest strength reqs and no dexterity, and are both one-handed, allowing you to use a shield for extra resists and defence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_40_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's an excellent plan!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_40_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NM is where the game *really* begins, because on Normal, you don't really need to think too much about your build plans or direction and can generally just dick around (other than a couple stumbling blocks like Duriel and Diablo).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_40_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's equally interesting (and a little ironic) that most of the runes (and runeword bases) you would want in Normal are only reliably obtained in Nightmare.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_40_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, at least, Nightmare is the most fun part of Diablo II--it's challenging enough that you may need to be careful in some areas, but you also have a complete toolkit to deal with what the game can throw at you... and you don't need to worry about immunities either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_41_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Charge + vigor can make your Pally go extremely fast across open areas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_41_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Vigor at level 1 isn't going to provide much noticeable difference, but at higher skill levels the speed boost is pretty substantial.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_41_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And unlike Charge, Vigor works when in town, so it can help speed up your return trips by minimising the amount of time you have to spend running around some of the bigger towns like Lut Gholein, Kurast Docks, and Harrogath.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_41_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, one shouldn't put points into Vigor solely for the speed boost.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_41_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You get those extra points via +skills on gear or because you were levelling Vigor anyway as a synergy for Blessed Hammer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_42_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>[Guest monsters](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/monsters/act5.shtml) are a thing on Nightmare and Hell difficulty in Act V. Those lightning-spewing scarabs you missed so badly from Act II; the bone fetishes which always ran to give you hugs in the Durance of Hate... well, there's a chance they may be back in Act V NM and Hell :P. This was always the case since LoD classic, I believe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_42_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It definitely spices things up a bit since by the time you've played until Act V NM, you have pretty much seen them all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_42_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So in theory, you could encounter monsters from *any* of the previous acts in NM and Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_42_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's been a while since I played Act V NM (I haven't gotten there yet in D2R), but if memory serves me correct, certain monsters wouldn't be as common in outdoor areas, I think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_42_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, Greater Mummies would be far less of an issue to deal with in the open (as you can just run away from them on the tundra), so I normally assume they'd only spawn in the ice caves and such.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_42_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I may just be talking out of my arse... and I'll have to get to Act V NM to see for myself (currently two more acts to go on my highest level character).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_43_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest reasons to go for D2R are: \+ Modern graphics along with some minor, but nice baked in Quality of Life features (shared stash, a *mostly* honest character screen, ctrl + click to move items back and forth, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_43_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\+ Plug-and-play convenience with widescreen support compared to LoD classic (which you can get to run in modern resolutions, but I was too lazy to do so, heh) \+ Console and gamepad support (for those too lazy to use a M amp;K, lol) The biggest reasons not to get D2R: \- Some aesthetically questionable redesign to iconic characters \- Your computer doesn't meet the minimum specs \- You are tight on money (and buying the game now would put you in dire financial straits) \- Poor multiplayer and matchmaking support for console users (there's even no /players x on console, apparently) Other than No.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_43_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>2 and 4, the 1st and 3rd reasons not to get this game are either subjective (maybe you like the new character redesigns more than the originals) and/or highly specific to your circumstances in the given moment.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_43_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, the game is pretty much everything I could have wanted from D2, other than my dislike of certain character redesigns and the fact that some of my old, favourite mods for LoD like Hell Unleashed and Median XL aren't compatible with this.... yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_43_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, if you were a huge fan of Diablo 3 (I personally hated it as a longtime Diablo 2 player, and D3 was the only game I've ever refunded in my life) then I can't say for certain you'd enjoy D2R since the gameplay may be much more antiquated from what you are used to in D3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_43_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, you should try the versions you have of D2 classic--if you enjoy those, then you'd enjoy this as well, as it has arguably **better** graphics and aesthetics than Diablo 3, better music... just about better everything.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_44_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My preferred caster set up is one column of health pots, 2 columns of mana pots, 1 column of rejuvs (full rejuvs on most of my characters past Act III, since I have a metric ton of those).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_44_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't see why you'd need TP scrolls in your belt, however, especially as a Sorc who has innate access to teleport and is likely a ranged character who shouldn't be hammered on so quickly that you can't teleport away then hit your tome of town portal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_44_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Assuming your Sorc is brand new, try to get a 16-slot belt (+12 slots) as soon as you can.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_44_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The easiest in Normal is a plated belt, but if you don't want to dump 60 points in strength just for that, every exceptional belt (Demonhide Sash and up) will have +12 slots.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_44_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Demonhide Sash itself only requires 20 strength, so if you can get one earlier (easiest way is to just buy one with a character that has reached NM or higher) that would be better than investing in strength up to wearing a plated belt in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_45_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's a very clever idea to map the first two belt hotkeys to side mouse buttons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_45_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since your hand is already on the shift key to cast whilst standing still, it can make it a lot faster to feed your merc a potion before he evaporates.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_45_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I ought to try that some time soon!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wait... since when does Lore (Ort + Sol) in a helm give life on kill?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It gives mana on kill, if I recall correctly, but I could be mistaken.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The main reason I made Lore was for + 1 skills for relatively low rune investment, although if the OP is struggling to even find a Sol at this point, I'd personally save that Sol rune for an Insight polearm first.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, to answer the OP's question about Insight, you can do without it in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Pally, you have access to 4 os shields from the get-go: every normal Paladin-specific shield you equip from the Targe up to the Crown Shield can host up to 4 sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other classes need to wait until Hell to actually get a 4 os shield (Monarch, an elite Kite Shield requiring 156 strength.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I doubt even a low-quality Monarch would drop in NM Act V or Cows... Getting the Amn runes in Normal is quite doable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll need to do a lot of Countess runs, and hope that she drops near the top of her loot table, i.e. a lot of Rals, which you will transmute into Orts, then Thuls, then 3x Thul + one chipped topaz = Amn.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This isn't considering that you'll also be finding plenty of these runes on your way through the game as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also keep in mind that the Hellforge can drop up to an Amn, but you'd need to be very lucky for that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Usually I just got an Eld on Normal, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One Spirit Runeword in your weapon... and if you can finagle another into your shield can help a lot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_46_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You also won't die due to lack of mana, but your Paladin's skin may turn blue due to all the mana potions you'll be consuming along the way :P. Here's a good official resource for [horadric cube recipes](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_47_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Automatic arrow/bolt pickup (as a toggleable option) would definitely be a great idea, especially for if you are playing online with randoms (and not your friends).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_47_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have the utmost sympathy for anyone who missed out on a good drop just because his/her inventory was clogged with a partial stack of arrows!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_47_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I do wonder how automatic arrow/bolt pickup would solve that above problem--because wouldn't the remaining ammo then go into your inventory?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_47_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless it were coded to only pick up enough arrows to fill your currently equipped stack, then leave the rest on the ground?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_48_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That does make me wonder: what would you say is too little defence?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_48_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The issue is that if your defence stat is only in the low hundreds (say around 300 or so), aren't you going to get shot to pieces by monsters using physical ranged attacks (e.g. corrupted rogue archers, spear-chucking sabre cats, flayers with blow darts, etc.)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_48_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And if those spawn as a unique mob with Cursed, well, that will be painful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_48_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, most classes do have some innate tools for dealing with ranged physical attackers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_48_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Paladins and Barbarians can Charge or Leap (Attack) respectively to close the distance fast; Necromancers have Dim Vision and Bone Prison; Assassins have Cloak of Shadows; Amazons have Slow Missiles, and Sorceresses can teleport.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_48_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm not sure about Druids as I've never really played one before.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_49_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>An even better idea may be to make that runeword in a shrunken head (Necromancer-specific shield), as all of them can get 2 sockets from the get-go.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_49_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And unlike Bone Shields, they'll often spawn with +skill mods.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_49_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the head doesn't have two sockets in it, one can use the Larzuk quest reward to put them in, or use the Horadric Cube recipe (Tal + Amn + Ruby \* shield to be socketed) and hope for the best.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_50_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Aye, that's part of what makes the game still great even after all these years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_50_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have to weigh the hard choices with your kit (unless you have endgame gear that gives you everything you could want, heh)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_51_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are definitely considered shields.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_51_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm using one on my offline Bonemancer right now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_51_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, there is a lot of understandable confusion to what [works](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml) with runewords and what doesn't.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_51_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oddly enough, Sorc orbs are not considered staves for runewords (like Leaf) which require staves; sceptres aren't considered maces for mace-specific runewords like Black, etc even though both of these items are included under their respective classes for in-game description purposes...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_52_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When did mana potions not exist??</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_52_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I could swear they had them in D2 pre-expansion?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_52_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I may be remembering things incorrectly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_53_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One low-level set item that I really like is Cleglaw's Pincers: these chain gloves give +25% target slow and knockback *on the item itself*, not as a set bonus.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_53_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those gloves work great for any non-caster character, especially against bosses, since the +25% slow will truly make most most monsters much less threatening.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_53_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The knockback is a bit annoying on melee characters, but since Act bosses are immune to knockback, it isn't an issue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_54_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Any reason why you aren't considering low level runewords, considering that things like Spirit\*, Stealth, and Strength are extremely easy to acquire (in terms of runes and potential bases) and also remain relevant throughout the game?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_54_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\*Spirit is easy to make in a sword in Normal, since you can get 4 sockets in a crystal sword that drops in Normal Cows (use the horadric cube recipe or Larzuk quest reward).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_54_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you are a Paladin, you aren't going to get a 4 os shield before Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_54_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Countess drops most of the runes you need for those above runewords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_54_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For things requiring runes above Ral, you'll just need to do a lot more Countess runs or play the game normally as I've easily found runes up through Shael runes in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can already see why you are having issues--your tactics need a bit of revision, I think!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>First, all curses are generally one-point wonders (I hope that 2nd point in Weaken was from your gear!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Second, you are level 25 and don't have a point in Decrepify?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Slow monsters = dead monsters, my friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm surprised you got past Duriel with this build, as he's normally a bit of a roadblock for most characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll likely also run into issues against Diablo as well, but that's to be expected as he is a tough nut to crack for summon necros on Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Third, you should be using **amplify damage** (or decrepify) on things your skellies are fighting, not Weaken.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The added bonus of Amplify Damage is that it will make Corpse Explosion hurt even more, since CE does 50% physical, 50% fire damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I can recall, Weaken only affects monsters' physical damage, and many of the most dangerous enemies in the game tend to be casters, not things with physical damage output.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine that what's eating your skellies for breakfast is elemental damage--Durance 3 generally has only Blood Lords (fireball, firewall, meteor) and Council Members, not to mention Mephisto who *mostly* inflicts elemental damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some Stygian Dolls can spawn there, but I haven't seen any in a while.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The undead dolls only become threatening on Nightmare and Hell; their death explosion doesn't inflict much noticeable damage on Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't be surprised if the lack of points in Summon Resist means that your skeletons are getting roasted by the flames.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, don't despair just yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Clay Golem is useful for the target slow, which stacks with Decrepify, I believe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Summonmancers actually get better in Nightmare, as your minions gain substantial life buffs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In short, get a point in Decrepify.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll need it against Act bosses like Mephisto and Diablo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Start using Amplify Damage to help your Skeletons hack down monsters faster (Iron Maiden is ok against melee enemies; it's not so useful against the meteor-spamming vampires since they usually don't use their melee attacks).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Get a staff with teleport charges to help reposition your undead army (and generally get yourself out of trouble).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_55_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ormus sells them occasionally.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Np, good luck and have fun, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now you've inspired me to roll a Summon Necro as well!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My current necro is a Bonemancer, and it's working pretty well, but I do miss that old feeling of having a veritable army of the dead, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One other tip is to not get *too* carried away with Corpse Explosion in fights--the corpse targetting in this game feels a bit... off compared to the original game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that you still need corpses for Revives (which can be even better than your skeletons) and of course, more skellies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sadly, there really isn't anything that can make Skeleton Mages good, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They'd be better if one or more of the following applied: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You had control over *which* element you got at the time of summoning. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You usually don't want a cold mage).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, you can just summon them again until you get the ones you want, but that's a bit wasteful of corpses and time!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They got access to actual Sorceress spells (e.g. Fireball, Glacial Spike, Chain Lightning) at higher levels.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Their cast rate was vastly increased so that they could cast fire bolts at machine gun rates.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They passively pierced enemy resists for their given elements (similar to how Cold Mastery works for Sorcs) 5.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Their damage output was scaled up a lot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_56_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could designate targets for them (which would make them an interesting alternative to regular skeletons) Now, I know that Lower Resist would help them out, but even with Lower Resist, they still are kind of pathetic compared to regular melee skeletons, which at least attack fast, are tanky (or can be), and tend to block enemies from actually targetting you directly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_57_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It doesn't quite make you invincible, since you actually need to be able to land those hits, but having those life tap charges can save your life.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_57_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The more expensive and convenient way to do this is to make an Exile runeword, but that isn't a viable option for most of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_57_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest issue with melee is that you typically need the following from your gear: \- Good physical defence \- 75% block (maximum) \- High weapon damage \- Max resistances \- High attack rating (so you can actually hit things) \- Source of life and mana leech With a caster, you don't necessarily need block rate, attack rating, or much in terms of physical defence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_57_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can get by with less than max resists if you are careful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_57_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And you don't need life or mana leech.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_58_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is true.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_58_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Black is a great runeword available from early Nightmare... but you still need it in a decent, high-damage, and *fast* base.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_58_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whereas the same crystal sword you got from Normal Cows for Spirit can serve you well into the endgame.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_59_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is true, but if you aren't a Pally, Smite isn't an option.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_59_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And getting stunlocked, desyncs, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_59_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>can still kill you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_59_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I'm just being pedantic here as I interpret "invincible" to mean "literally unable to be harmed/killed" whereas you probably meant *practically* invincible :D</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll need just enough strength to equip your gear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No need for dexterity whatsoever on a casting build like your Sorc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Dexterity will also increase your block chance, defence rating, and attack rating (chance to hit with physical attacks)--none of which you need.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't whacking things with a stick so you don't need attack rating.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And you shouldn't be getting in melee so you don't really need block chance or defence rating.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a general rule of thumb, most build guides will tell you to put enough points in strength to equip your gear (accounting for +str modifiers on various charms, rings, armour, etc.),</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>then dump everything else into vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even for a Sorc, most guides will tell you not to put points in Energy--the reason for this is that you'll find enough +mana or +energy gear to account for any mana issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And before then, you can keep a couple columns of mana potions in your belt.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, when levelling, it doesn't hurt you to put a few points in Energy to ease the early mana issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that you another two free respecs in Nightmare and Hell (one for each Den of Evil quest), so you can always re-allocate when starting the next difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And **remember not to shift + click when assigning attribute points after a respec.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ctrl + click is how you put 5 points at a time into an attribute.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But just to be safe, assign them one by one--starting with strength until you reach your desired level, then vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_60_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Vitality is probably your most important stat, because if your max health is too low, you'll end up being one-shotted by tougher monsters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have a long way to go before you'll even reach Tal Rasha's Tomb.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just play through Act II normally and you'll get there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are only three potentially missable quests in this game, and two of them are in Act I. 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Search for Cain--if you completely bypass getting the Scroll of Inifuss and going to Tristram through the Cairn Stones, Cain will be eventually rescued by the Rogues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only difference is that he will charge you 100 gold every time you want to identify stuff.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Forgotten Tower--if you just run through the Black Marsh and never visit the Forgotten Tower (or you don't click on the Mouldy Tome in the Stony Fields), you'll never get this quest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Golden Bird--If you never pick up the Jade Figurine (usually dropped by the first unique mob in the Spider Forest), you'll miss this quest entirely as it isn't given to you by an NPC.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I guess you could also miss Blade of the Old Religion and Lam Essen's Tome in Act III as well, but you'd need to try pretty hard to avoid completing those.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, unlike the quest to rescue Cain, you could return to the act to complete these ones if you somehow missed it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This isn't Baldur's Gate--there aren't a ton of quests and the game's progression is quite linear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_61_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The challenge here is primarily the combat (finding good gear, allocating your skills and attributes so that you can kill monsters effectively and not die), not figuring out where to go or what to do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Duriel is a notorious spike in difficulty since the pre-expansion days of D2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll potentially encounter another difficulty spike when you encounter Big D himself in Act IV.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What makes Duriel so nasty, in my opinion, are two things: his charge attack and his (Un)holy Freeze aura.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, there's no real reason to "force yourself to get weaker" to increase the difficulty by purposely equipping crappy gear and not using your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only valid rationale to use less than optimal gear is if you wanted to stack magic find as high as possible (since most of your MF gear will probably entail giving up some +skills, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, it isn't really worth doing MF runs in Normal difficulty, as most of the things really worth farming for only start dropping in late NM and Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus if you want a challenge, just continue on with the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may find another challenge in the Act III and IV bosses (although the boss of Act III can be cheesed with good positioning and if your attacks are mostly ranged).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And you'll find even more challenge in Nightmare and Hell difficulties, which are basically New Game+ modes, but with beefed up monsters, maluses to your base resistances (-40 on NM and -70 on Hell), and a lot more champion and unique monsters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On Hell, pretty much every monster from the Fallen you encounter in Act I onward has some sort of immunity to a particular damage type as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Dual-immune (e.g. fire and cold immunity) monsters on Hell are not uncommon, either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_62_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you weren't playing on console, I'd suggest using the /players x command to spice things up a bit, but sadly, that isn't an option for console players yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, that doesn't sound ideal at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, you haven't completely ruined your character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's why: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did you use your respec after completing the Den of Evil on Normal?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If not, go back to Akara in Act I and respec.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Problem solved.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have already used that respec, again, don't worry.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can make it through Normal even with suboptimal stats and skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your build really doesn't start to matter until Nightmare, and even then... 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can easily complete Den of Evil on Nightmare with a subpar build (you may just need to be a bit careful and take it slow).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That will get you another free respec.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can use it then to fix everything.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And in the worst case scenario that you cannot make it past Act IV on Normal with your current build, remember that lvl 30 is not high at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's the infancy stage for most planned builds, as you'll either unlock your main skill then, or you'll have enough points in your main skill(s) to make them actually useful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So if you really want to re-roll your Sorc, you can just toss all her kit (and gold) in a shared stash tab, then give it another go.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, based on the three above points, rolling a brand new Sorceress probably isn't necessary at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_63_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd only re-roll if you find you are getting one-shotted left and right at your current point in the game and have no real hope of making it any further.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For how easy it is to make (in terms of runes *and* the base), Spirit is stupidly powerful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+2 skills, up to 35% FCR, +22 vitality, and up to +112 extra mana all for four runes you can technically get from running the Countess in Act I (with a bit of cubing, of course)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Melee characters don't have anything that compares to that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only difficult part is getting it in a shield, but since Paladin shields can all get 4 os, it's even better for Hammerdins!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know this will probably never happen, but there needs to be an equivalent low-cost, but potent runeword for melee characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I liked using King's Grace when levelling my Zealot (which I respecced into a Hammerdin in NM), but it doesn't compare in terms of sheer utility to Spirit on a caster build--my Hammerdin is still using Spirit into Act III of NM, and I doubt I'll replace it until I reach Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, melee characters need to upgrade their weapons frequently.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, I don't think Spirit should be nerfed at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I definitely agree with you that melee characters could do with a similar early-game boost.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In my experience, melee builds have a slight starting advantage until around level 24 (when you can first equip Spirit runewords), then casters leave them in the dust.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_64_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add that Insight isn't difficult to make in NM Act I *and give to the same Act II merc you brought along from Normal*...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hate to be *that guy*, but using your logic, the Paladin should never have been black in original D2 or in D2R. His weapons, armour, and even the very name of the class are reminiscent of medieval Europe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The name "paladin" itself originally refers to the (legendary) knights of Charlemagne's court, and I'm pretty sure there weren't any knights of African extraction in France during the VIII century AD.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, nobody had a problem with the original Paladin being dark-skinned, because it fit the lore of the game, and the world of Sanctuary doesn't match the geography of Earth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Zakarum and its Paladins originated in Kurast, and people there tend to be dark-skinned.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Assassins in Diablo II are from the same area where the Vizjerei originated--around Lut Gholein.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So if anything, the Assassin should have more of an Arab or Persian look than East Asian.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, it's not a huge deal, other than the fact that the new model looks hideous, and her starting armour was 'censored.'</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But you only need to see her ugly mug and burlap jumpsuit on the character select screen, and even that not for long as you find better kit (including full face helmets) pretty darn quickly!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_65_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The art also wasn't vague at all in the original game--she didn't look remotely Asian at all in any official concept art.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_66_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, your comment **is** valid, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_66_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the OP is a Zealot, then he *does* have access to smite and quite likely he will have a point in it as a prerequisite to Holy Shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_66_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, there's no reason why he can't swap to the Life Tap wand, curse a tough mob (e.g. an act boss), then swap back and start zealing, and maybe switch to smiting if he gets in trouble :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_66_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, all this requires speed of action and not being slow-fingered, but D2R is a fast-paced game--in fact, it feels faster-paced than the original LoD, probably because that ran at 30 fps (I think) whilst this runs at 60.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_67_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Congratulations :D I'm glad to hear that you're able to proceed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_67_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whilst it can be helpful to look at some of the build guides, remember that you aren't obligated to follow them to a tee--what matters is that you are having fun with the game :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_68_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes, it can take a fair bit of grinding.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_68_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll need to run the Act bosses on Hell difficulty many times to get various essences.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_68_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can get the Essence of Suffering from Andariel or Duriel, but you'll need to run Mephisto, Baal, and Diablo for their respective essences, which are *not* 100% guaranteed drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_68_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On the upside, Hell boss runs can be a decent way to MF, although I don't know of anyone who'd ever want to do Duriel runs, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_68_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, you could also look at it this way--if you already have a character doing boss runs in Hell, you could just use that character to farm for essences along the way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_68_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, if you have nothing better to do, this may not be a bad idea if you play online, since those tokens are tradable (I think), and they could end up worth a fair bit, if they are tradable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt; /players command.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Enhance your drops easily at bosses with /p3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>/players 8 is where it's at (unless you're a Necromancer, since CE doesn't scale with increased monster health.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Necro, I wouldn't play above /players 5).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I agree with you 100% on single-player.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest draw for me is that I can play at my own pace, have fun with some minor QoL mods (and hopefully eventually some gameplay overhauls and graphic mods to improve certain character models... like the Assassin), **and I am never at the mercy of internet shenanigans**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_69_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Not being able to trade for items is a bit of a downer, but again, as you stated, it's about the journey, not getting stuff now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Reaching level 15 can be done in a couple hours, friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only mistake you made was in maybe improperly allocating your skills and stats after respeccing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, your build does not matter much for Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can clear the game with a crossbow-wielding Necromancer ffs if that's what you are into. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know I was when I first played D2 classic as a snotty-nosed middle school lad in 2000).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you find you are truly unable to progress when the Act II merc can just about kill everything for you if you give him some decent kit (look for the highest-damaging polearm or spear you can get, for one), well, like I said, level 15 takes no time to reach at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So you can just toss your poor Necro's kit in a shared stash tab along with his gold, then start again with a bit more knowledge.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If there weren't any shared stash tab, well, that could make things a bit worse, but even then, at lvl 15, you probably don't have anything really worth keeping either!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_70_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Good luck and have fun :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If an item already has sockets, you cannot add more sockets to it\*\*--either via Larzuk's quest reward or the Horadric Cube recipe. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that the Horadric Cube recipe doesn't work on Superior items).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unique items can only get **one** socket, unless they intrinsically spawn with more (e.g. Rune Master Ettin Axe).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The same applies to set and rare items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runewords **cannot** be made in magic, rare, set, or unique items (no blues, yellows, greens, or golds/browns).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have the Arm of King Leoric, the most you can do is add **one** socket to it, and stick something else in there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I wouldn't waste the quest reward on that when you can save it to socket an ideal base for a runeword at some point in the future.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\*\*NB: The only exception to this are the formulae for adding sockets to magic items (blues).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can use this formula even on socketed magic items (3 chipped gems + 1 magic item).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_71_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, this will just re-roll the magic properties and re-roll between 1 and 2 sockets, with a maximum ilvl of 25.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_72_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You know, I'll give that a try.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_72_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I usually play on p6 to 8, but as p3 will allow me to kill things much faster, perhaps I'll stick around that point--especially for boss runs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_72_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have heard, however, that for Countess runs, p1 is best.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_73_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, there are plenty of ways people can be toxic without using profanity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_73_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Half the time, most of the uses of profanity aren't abusive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_73_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's nothing inherently abusive about "We kicked Diablo's scaly red ass," for instance :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_74_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People are already working on it: [https://www.nexusmods.com/diablo2resurrected/mods/25](https://www.nexusmods.com/diablo2resurrected/mods/25) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_74_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, they just added a simple red stripe to the Barbarian's face, but there \*are\* visual mods already available.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_74_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some rather pervy modders even managed to make the Amazon's model bottomless.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_74_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do wish that these folks would apply their talents to slightly better things (like restoring the original armour look for the Amazon and Assaassin), but the fact that they can do this already is promising.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_75_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are going to need to wait for modders.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_75_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree that most of the character models are a lot uglier (and in the case of the Assassin, have some extremely unaesthetic changes), but that doesn't hinder my enjoyment of the game and it shouldn't for you either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_75_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, the isometric perspective of D2 means that you aren't staring closely at your character's model the way you do in games like RE2 and 3--the latter of which is an excellent example of unwanted, unnecessary, and unaesthetic changes to an iconic character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_75_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Which was promptly fixed by modders.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_76_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One other thing you can do is equip gold find gear--once you get up to above 100% (not hard to do at all), you will notice a substantial increase in the amount of gold you are picking up, especially from champion monsters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I feel your pain, but that's what you get for playing Hardcore, friendo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did you ever own a physical copy of the original Diablo 2?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If so, you may remember a small disclaimer in the instruction manual about HC characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It more or less stated that Blizzard has zero responsibility for your Hardcore character and will not restore a dead character for any reason, including acts of God, your little sister, etc. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>La la la la la, we're not listening*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It really did say the last part.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With HC, you accept that risk of losing your character permanently due to bullshit beyond your control as a player.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Such is life when you only have one of them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_77_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's why *I* don't play HC--I don't like the thought of losing all the time I invested into a character permanently due to something entirely beyond my control.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_78_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is the gold in your **personal** or your shared stash tab?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_78_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Vendors don't see gold in shared stash tabs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_78_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Move the gold from a shared stash tab to your personal one, and you shouldn't have any issues... unless it's a new bug</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What class, what build?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just saying that you are lvl 27 doesn't tell me very much at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A level 27 Sorceress going for a Meteorb build will play **very** differently from a level 27 Zealot Paladin, for instance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A summon Necro would face different challenges from a Bonemancer, and so on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are correct that you need better resistances (lightning and fire), but depending on your class, you can approach Diablo differently. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are a Summoning Necro, it will be a bit tough (he will obliterate your skellies), so you'll need to spam clay golems, hit him with decrepify, and force-feed your merc potions whilst he wails on Big D. When you run out of potions and/or skeletons, TP out, go somewhere with some corpses, raise some more (don't open another TP, heh) then go back to Act IV and resume until the red lizard is dead. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are a melee class, you'll need to hit-and-run.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fill your belt with as many full rejuvs as you can, and don't be afraid to run away and TP out if possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Paladin, hopefully you have Salvation so you can resist the elemental damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't try to tank the lightning hose (it's not a Chain Lightning spell, but it's more akin to Palpatine's 'Unlimited Power' force lightning, heh).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just back off whilst healing with rejuvenation potions, then get back in the fight when he isn't spamming lightning at you. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're a Bowazon, just stand off at range, spam decoys, and needle Diablo to death with guided arrows whilst chugging mana potions as need be.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you don't have one already, hire an Act II Merc (I'd go with the Defiance one, as Prayer isn't going to heal you fast enough to keep you alive), then equip him with the highest-damage polearm or spear you can find.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Give him good resistance and high defence armour, and ideally some lifeleech, and heal him when he's too low on health.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In addition, go back to Act III and check Ormus' shop for a staff with teleport charges.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep this in your secondary weapon slot, as it will help with navigating certain areas faster, and also help you keep your merc alive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, I can't offer any more specific tips since the most optimal strategy will depend highly on your particular class and build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could also go farm parts of Act IV for better kit and levels, but you aren't going to find much in Normal difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only area really worth farming in Normal is the Countess for low runes for basic runewords like Stealth (Tal + Eth) and Ancient's Pledge (Ral Ort Tal in a shield).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_79_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The latter will give you excellent elemental resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I know, there isn't any such recipe, but I can't see why you'd even want that because: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Magic items (blues) are extremely common in game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can convert a normal item to rare by using Charsi's quest reward in Act I. 9/10 times, however, she will just turn your item into a nice snack for herself, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Normal items (whites) can be socketed to serve as bases for runewords, which tend to be some of the most potent items in the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can't make runewords in anything but normal socketed items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runewords are powerful enough that some socketed (grey) items are actually worth much, much more than their magic equivalents.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A 5 os superior Phase blade would be worth much more than a magic (blue) Merciless Phase Blade of Butchery.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The former can be used to make Grief, a potent runeword for many melee builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The latter will never be anything other than a rather high-damage sword... and by the time Phase Blades start dropping, you are already well into Hell difficulty, where a normal magic weapon probably isn't going to cut it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are Horadric cube formulae for rerolling magic and rare items, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These formulae are useful, especially in the late game, as you can use them to re-roll Grand Charms in the hope of getting +skill modifiers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, you could re-roll a Grand Charm dropped in a lvl 50+ zone to hopefully get something like Graverobber's Grand Charm of Sustenance--+1 to Summoning Skills (Necromancer only)  amp; +35 life.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_80_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Likewise, you can use these to re-roll amulets to hopefully get +2 skills for a given class, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_81_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Enigma is useful for way more classes--just about every build could benefit from the ability to teleport (other than Sorcs, who have it as an intrinsic skill).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_81_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you were fine relying on an item with teleport charges instead, then I'd go for Infinity, which would benefit nearly any Sorceress build I can think of as well as some Paladin and Druid builds, and maybe even a Trapassin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_81_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One minor advantage of the teleport charges vs. Enigma is that the teleport charges don't consume mana.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_81_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If something nasty with mana burn hits you very hard and you are relying on teleport as an intrinsic or oskill, then you might be in a bit of trouble as you aren't going to teleport with zero mana.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_81_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, by the point that you can even consider making an Enigma, you probably have enough +skills on your gear to drastically reduce the mana cost of the lvl 3 teleport you get from Enigma (+1 Teleport and +2 all skills).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_82_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't going to find an Io rune in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_82_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Making Strength for crushing blow is a slightly more viable option, since Amn runes can theoretically drop in Act IV normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_82_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, crushing blow would only apply if the OP is running a build that relies on physical damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_82_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If he is, one other item that could really help a bit are Cleglaw's Claws set chain gloves.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_82_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+25% slow on top of the normal chill effect from cold damage will make Diablo a lot less threatening.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't listen to anyone who tells you that X class is hard to play starting out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>None of the classes are inherently hard or easy to play; it's your **build** that makes the difference... mostly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, a Hammerdin (Paladin relying on Blessed Hammer) is a very powerful build, but until you learn the correct positioning for hitting enemies with the spiralling hammer, you'll probably find it harder and more frustrating than a Sorceress using Fireball (just spam fireballs until everything is dead).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The best tips I can offer are as follows: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Only put as many points into strength as you need to equip your gear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For most caster builds, I wouldn't go above 43 in normal (i.e. raising strength to 43, not putting 43 points into strength).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't put any points in Dexerity--if you are a caster, you aren't using bows, and your physical attack rating and block chance *generally* don't matter since you shouldn't be in melee combat range either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Put maybe 10\~15 points in Energy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All the builds say to ignore Energy, but they assume that you already have your near-endgame gear that gives you a ton of Mana, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since you don't have this yet, you wouldn't be hurt too badly by putting 10\~15 points in Energy, especially since you have another free respec coming up in Nightmare.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Put all your remaining points into Vitality once you reach your desired max strength**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I would put 5 points into Vitality every other level-up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_83_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Make sure you have elemental resistances, especially lightning and fire.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_84_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd argue that the Sorceress is easier than the Paladin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_84_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With a Zealadin, you need to consider things like attack rating, keeping max block chance, life leech, crushing blow etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_84_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, melee builds are *much* more gear-dependent than casters on average.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_84_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, the Sorceress has Teleport as an innate skill, which really helps with survival in sticky situations and generally with navigating the map faster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_84_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Considering that caster builds play differently from melee builds, I don't think that rolling a Zealadin will help the OP figure out how to make a good Sorc build at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_84_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, the Sorc can be used to easily MF for other builds as well!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_85_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are dying in Act I, how would you have even unlocked Frozen Orb, which is a level 30 skill?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_85_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you got rushed to NM, and are in Act I at level 30.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_85_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you confusing Frozen Orb with Ice Bolt or Ice Blast (the latter does indeed fire a small freezing orb, heh)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_86_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You want to lure him off the Pentagram and into the main part of the Chaos Sanctuary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_86_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This gives you a lot more room to maneuver.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_86_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fighting Diablo on the pentagram isn't a good idea due to the cramped space and the fact that you would have to run away from him in a straight line if you need to heal or return to town.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_86_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if your character could face-tank Diablo easily, I'd still want to pull the fight into the more open area if I were you just in case things go wrong.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_86_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sometimes he will spam the red lightning hose multiple times.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ah, you are a Paladin--you should have mentioned that in your original post (though I see you edited it now).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm glad to see you got past Big D. He *is* supposed to be a challenge--after all, Diablo is the eponymous boss of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I do have some good news for you: when you face him again on Nightmare, you'll have a *much* easier time since you will have better gear, more experience (in the real-world, not RPG sense), and a full toolkit of skills to use.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for people suggesting you get runes "not available" in Normal, well, you could *technically* get an Io rune in Normal, but it would take a metric shit ton of grinding the Countess to do so--which is not worth the trouble.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Strength (Amn + Tir) works well enough if you're a Zealadin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Combine that 25% crushing blow from the runeword with an extra +5\~10% from Blood crafted gloves (Magic Heavy Gloves + Perfect Ruby + Nef Rune + Magic Jewel) and you'll be able to easily chunk most tough enemies pretty quickly, then finish them with your melee damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, only put *one* point in Salvation when you get it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It benefits from + skills on your gear, and it's a waste to invest more points in that skill when you can use those points for other skills actually relevant to your build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_87_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The same goes for Redepmption--it's a one-point sidetrack that can be useful, but isn't 100% necessary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's really quite inane that so many people seem to think that a warrior or fighter **needs** to look ugly, brutish, dirty, or generally unattractive in appearance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In the real world, there are plenty of good-looking guys and gals in active duty combat branches.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Being a fighter doesn't mean that you automatically need to look like shit--even if your style of fighting involves taking plenty of hits.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did Muhammed Ali look like trash 24/7?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is Travis Haley not a real SOF veteran just because he doesn't look like a hobo?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If this is true in the real world, then why shouldn't it be true in a fantasy setting?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even in ancient and medieval times, there were good-looking warriors and fighters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't imagine that Alexander the Great was a minger, or that Boudicca looked like hammered shit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, historically, warriors in every culture **did** care about aesthetics as much as was possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It wasn't just a matter of looking presentable, but also a matter of hygiene to not let yourself turn into a complete slob in the field if you could help it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Think about it this way--if warriors didn't care about aesthetics, you wouldn't see ornately decorated armour.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's no reason why you can't have an attractive-looking female character who can also kick major ass.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To think otherwise is really quite sexist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the arguments that "well, she shouldn't be wearing makeup" well, our characters in game aren't living in tents in the wilderness the entire time, nor living in besieged towns.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the Barbarian has the time to apply blue war paint to his face before showing up in the Rogue Encampment (because that matters to him), then an Amazon or Sorceress would equally have the time to apply whatever cosmetics they deem fit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, you lot need to keep in mind that Diablo is a **fantasy** setting, where magic is prevalent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Magic changes the rules considerably.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A piece of leather armour with two Ral runes stuffed into it can protect you better against Diablo himself than a set of Superior Plate Mail without any resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_88_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, you can't argue that "X character needs more realistic/practical armour" when the threats that the characters face are *not* just arrows and blades, and armour is commonly enchanted to be more protective than any real-world equivalent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_89_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The best Mercenary changes I've seen were those in the Hell Unleashed mod: [http://hudb.arimyth.com/mercenaries](http://hudb.arimyth.com/mercenaries) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_89_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Among giving the Act III mercs more skills (and adding a fourth poison and bone specialist), it also gave them elemental auras--Holy Fire, Holy Freeze, Holy Shock, and a poison resistance piercing aura.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_89_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That made them actually viable choices for certain builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_89_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Act I mercs aren't bad, but my issue with them is that their attack rate is way too slow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_90_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Immunities encourage cooperative play with other party members.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_90_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They do suck if you are on single-player, but... there are mods out there that remove monster immunities from singleplayer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_91_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are indeed very few magic-immune monsters, but you'll encounter some in Act II (the zombies around the Lost City), in Act III (Wailing Beasts in the temples where you need to search for Lam Essen's Tome), and Act V (the mummies summoned in Wave 2 or 3 by Baal).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_91_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, those are rare enough that you can usually skip them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_91_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, the zombies in Act II mean that a Hammerdin won't be able to farm the Ancient Tunnels that well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_91_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I hate physical immune monsters the most--those are pretty common, and what convinced me to respec my Zealadin into a Hammerdin, although I greatly prefer the Zeal playstyle.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yep, you are right mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, it doesn't cost me a halfpenny to voice my opinions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If even just one person agrees with me, I am a bit happier.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If they stick to their absurd views, well, it doesn't change anything.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe I'll create a blog about this disturbing trend toward "uglification" of female characters in media, because it is something I've been thinking about, and the people in favour of it actually evince far more sexist and regressive beliefs than those who prefer the older, original styles.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'll conclude with this: one can have a tastefully done and appealing-looking character design.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There is a very broad middle ground between dental floss bikinis and niqabs, between showing enough skin to be appealing without looking completely crass.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_92_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Anyone who cannot see this is either blind or has some serious unresolved issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd be careful with how you put that, lest some people accuse you of certain 'isms.'</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I personally have no issue with the Assassin being Asian *if the original character had been Asian-looking*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, she clearly was not.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also don't see why they saw the need to change her starting armour to a flesh-coloured burlap jumpsuit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For those who say "it's more practical," well, burlap is pretty damn flammable, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And the Assassins train to fight magic users, not people relying on swords, slings, and bows.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So real-world arguments on practical vs. impractical armour don't apply here since magic doesn't exist in reality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is a world in which Barbarians can develop innate resistance to elemental magics on their bare skin, and Necromancers can raise human skeletons from swarms of insects or overgrown porcupines, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Real-world armour designs have little place here except for the sake of recognisability.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I wouldn't let all this derail your enjoyment of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_93_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Modders *will* improve some of the character models; there are already some rudimentary visual mods available.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_94_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Probably quite a few, based on the pictures I've seen of some game developer teams, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_94_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your anecdote does help put things in perspective, but to be frank, I don't think I will *ever* understand that mentality your friend and his sister have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_94_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm no Christian Bale myself, but I don't begrudge better looking men at all and I like having attractive characters in my games.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_94_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Who wants to play as an overweight, balding slob, or a mannish-looking, slovenly woman (unless that unattractive look is central to the character's identity and role in the story)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_94_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What makes this even sadder is that people excuse uglification by claiming it's "more realistic."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_94_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't know what unfortunate hellholes these people call home, but in the places I've lived in--including even the northeastern U.S.--most people didn't look anywhere as homely as some of these character designs ffs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I feel this guide is better: [https://d2.maxroll.gg/guides/necromancer-leveling](https://d2.maxroll.gg/guides/necromancer-leveling) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The other guide the OP linked seems to leave out Bone Armour, which can greatly increase your survivability against physical attackers who may occasionally get in a swing at you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The key is to not be afraid to put a few points into energy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if you put 20 points into Energy and left it that way, you wouldn't suffer too much in the long run.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A bit less total life in the long run, but not so much as to make your character gimped at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The nice thing about Bone Armour is that it's a one-point wonder--it actually gets more damage absorb from the synergies (which also fuel Bone Spear) than from extra points in it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, that other guide seems to overlook Decrepify, which can be very helpful against bosses and for generally saving your arse against dangerous foes which get too close.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As everyone else says, getting your Merc an Insight runeword ASAP is a good idea.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And as for Mercs, stick with the Defiance Merc in Normal, and consider switching to a Holy Freeze one in NM for extra crowd control.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_95_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your Merc will not shatter corpses often enough to have any effect on your use of Corpse Explosion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_96_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What weapons are you using?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_96_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Until you get a White (Dol + Io) wand, using Spirit in a Crystal sword can help quite a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_96_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, these guides seem to assume that you have the means to "twink" your character with all the kit you need at the appropriate levels, that you are playing in a party, or that you can trade for everything you want/need at a given level.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_96_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are playing single-player or SSF, well, consider that putting 10 or 15 points into Energy would *not* seriously gimp your build as a whole.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_96_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It may mean a bit less life down the line, but keep in mind you have two more free respecs coming up in Nightmare and Hell, especially if you used your Normal respec to tune your build a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_97_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not hard to lure the mobs away from Baal so that you can fight them without dealing with Decrepify, you know?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_97_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, the Oblivion Knights used to have Iron Maiden back in the day.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_97_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If that wasn't a "fuck you" to melee classes, I don't know what is, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_97_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you got cursed with Iron Maiden in the middle of Zeal or Whirlwind on a high level Paladin or Barbarian, you'd kill yourself almost instantly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_97_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, if you get hit with Lower Resist, you should generally be able to back off and let the curse expire (or head back to town to remove it), then jump back into the fray.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_98_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why would they take out Lower Resist?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_98_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Removing Iron Maiden from the Oblivion Knights made them *much* less threatening.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_98_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, it's worth noting that the AI for the Oblivion Knights is very predictable, and not particularly coordinated--they will regularly overwrite one another's curses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_98_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you get within melee range of an OK, he'll hit you with Decrepify then scurry away almost 100% of the time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_98_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Use this to your advantage when fighting them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This only applies to 2h swords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For other two-handed weapons (2h axes, polearms, mauls) you cannot equip anything in the offhand.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The advantage of 2h weapons is greater damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The downside is less defence due to the lack of a shield, which also means less resistances--diamond in a socketed shield are a cheap and effective way to stack resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ancient's Pledge (Ral+Ort+Tal) is also a very cheap and easy way to boost your resistances with a shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are **guaranteed** to get these runes on every playthrough with zero farming, as they are given as a quest reward early in Act V, and you can readily find 3 socketed shields in Act II normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just make sure the shield in question isn't a blue (magic) shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Certain skills (e.g. Fanatacism, Frenzy) can also increase your attack speed and can help boost slower weapons to acceptable rates.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, the reason why one should typically choose faster weapons over slower ones is that a slow attack speed will feel even worse when you are hit with cold damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If your attack speed is slow, then it is easier for monsters to interrupt your attack--though there are again skills that grant uninterruptible attacks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One added bonus of faster attacks is that certain % effects (e.g. Crushing Blow) will proc more often.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_99_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Against a tough monster like an Act boss, a low-damage, but high percentage Crushing Blow weapon can actually work better--use it to chunk the boss' life fast, then switch to a higher damaging weapon to finish it off.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you say so; to me, they are all the same, with casters actually being easier since you usually aren't in the thick of melee combat or getting hit that often.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Not needing to worry about attack rating, weapon damage, or weapon speed is also quite nice... as is potentially having access to a cheap endgame runeword by Act III at latest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Spirit sword that you can easily make in Normal will serve you well until Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Leaf staff you can make after potentially **one** Countess run will serve you well until you can get that 4 os Crystal sword or Broadsword for Spirit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There isn't anything that comes close for melee builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you find that you aren't inflicting enough damage as a caster, it comes down to your skill allocation, mostly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you find you aren't inflicting enough damage as a melee build, it's probably your weapon choice **and** your skill allocation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have complete control over how you allocate your skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_100_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The weapons you can get are partially at the mercy of RNG.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of those three, the last one--Diablo's Soulstone makes the most sense in terms of the game's story and lore.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, the first two don't fit into the story and break the fourth wall a *bit* too much when compared to every other quest in the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Almost every other quest involves doing X or Y that some NPC told you to benefit them (or everyone else).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even The Forgotten Tower falls into this category: the Rogues were losing a lot of Sisters who went to explore that Tower and never came back, but at least you (the player) were able to get something good out of it (Akara even hints at this when you talk to her after the quest), so they don't feel *quite* as bad as they would if it turned out that the Tower contained nothing but some cobwebs, hunks of mouldy cheese, and rat dung.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For Act IV to be fleshed out more, however, it would also need additional zones (with more waypoints).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Six quests crammed into three areas would feel a bit crowded, I think!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Perhaps there could be some additional areas, like a hellish swamp, or perhaps the Stygian Pit (a near pitch-black area) where [Reziarfg](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/monsters/act5-reziarfg.shtml) could be fought for unique benefits.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NB: Reziarfg is an old April Fool's joke at the expense of a Blizzard North employee (G. Frazier).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sadly, they never added this in.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some other ideas for expanded quests could pertain to those red portals you encounter in the next act (Pit of Acheron, Abaddon, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those seem to serve as demonic staging points for the invasion of Mt. Arreat.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_101_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Perhaps there could be an Act IV quest that has Tyrael sending the player to clear out some of these zones from the Hell side, thus reducing the tide of minions that Baal can call upon for the invasion of Mt. Arreat.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My **Last Wish** would be that I could give your post more than one upvote just for the puns :D However, jokes aside, there is one other option you could take to get those unobtainable runewords, but I don't think you'll like it: use a hero editor.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, before you cry foul, consider that you could use it in this way: to simulate trades.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Look up the average running price for, say, a Jah in online games.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Chances are, you've probably accumulated kit that people normally trade for it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can simulate the trade by selling those items you want to "trade" for a Jah to a vendor, then editing a mule character to give him/her a Jah.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then transfer it to your main character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not an ideal solution, as trade prices in-game are variable, and highly dependent on the player you are bartering with, but as most of those runewords were designed with the idea that you'd be playing online with other players to trade with, and not playing solo/offline, I think it's fair and not cheating to do this.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What would be cheating is to just give yourself the runes with no exchange, perhaps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Alternatively, there are single-player mods already that increase HR drop rates to be more viable for single-player.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_102_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't use any of them, as I am concerned they could break other things, and I'm nowhere near the point with any of my characters in D2R to start worrying about high rune drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_103_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hotkeying the skills that you need (with F1 to F8l--these can be expanded or even changed altogether in the controls menu) is vital to survival once you get past Act I. Trying to select skills manually is too slow and will get you killed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_103_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that you can hotkey your left-click skills as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_103_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For some builds, this can be important to do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_103_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Consider binding hotkey options beyond F8, as you'll definitely need more than 8 skills hotkeyed, especially if you are running a Necromancer build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_103_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also suggest changing the hotkey options to something a bit more ergonomic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_104_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The one thing I am hoping for is true modding support.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_104_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That will "fix" 99% of issues people have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_104_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just allow for private servers or TCP/IP play like the original game, and everyone's happy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_105_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's pretty impressive, then!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_105_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, definitely get used to the hotkeys--they will make your life a lot easier :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_106_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think I have ever seen a crown drop in Act II normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_106_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The OP's best bet is to pick up a white (non-magic, rare, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_106_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>crown in Act IV or V normal and either use it for Larzuk's quest reward, or, better yet, take his chances with the Horadric Cube recipe (Ral + Thul + Perfect Sapphire).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_106_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Both of those runes are pretty common drops in Normal, as are white crowns, so one doesn't lose much from giving it a couple tries.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_107_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that this recipe doesn't work with low quality *or Superior* items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_107_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It needs to be a baseline white item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_107_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't guaranteed to get 2 or 3 sockets with it, but usually you should get at least 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_108_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's worth noting that even before you smash the Compelling Orb, the Zealots do have a tendency to back off when low on life.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_108_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, it was true in the original game that after you smash the Compelling Orb, the Zealots will only run away from you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well... it's debatable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Zakarumites you encounter from Lower Kurast onward are certainly not demons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's arguable that they are just misguided fools.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, they did willingly aid and abet with a whole lot of atrocities (take a close look at the various altars you see throughout Kurast), whilst other followers of Zakarum, like the Paladin and his brethren, saw what was going on and left a long time ago.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, they can drop nice stuff if you kill them, so there's no good reason not to slaughter them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Story-wise, they certainly didn't give the good folks of Lower Kurast, the Bazaar, and Upper Kurast any such consideration... nor did they consider whether Akarat was *really* in favour of human sacrifice and such.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_109_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're playing as a Necromancer and feel especially evil, trap 'em with Bone Prison so they can't run, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is still the case.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ctrl + click to add five at a time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They really need to add a tool-tip somewhere in game so that people stop making this mistake.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I feel bad for anyone who ends up blowing their last reset due to that mistake, especially since shift + click in some other games doesn't result in adding all points at once.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>PSA: When in doubt, add the points to your limited attributes (e.g. Strength/Dex for gear) **first** one by one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't rush and be patient.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When you're done with Strength, then do Vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Clicking that button 140 times is nowhere as tedious as having to level a new level 75 character just because you dumped 200+ points into strength and have nothing left for Vitality on your last reset.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, you could just continue playing with your extra-swole, glass cannon Sorc, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_110_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In the case of the OP, that isn't ideal, but it isn't horrible--you may just need to stuff all your non-runeword kit with perfect rubies and be *extra* careful in combat until you reach Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_111_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What is your lightning resist?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_111_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it is maxed out and you have decent life, Gloams shouldn't be able to one-shot you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_111_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may want to increase your Lightning resist as Act IV can be chock-full of the Gloams more hellish cousins, especially in the Plains of Despair (where Izual hangs out).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_111_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could consider swapping out your MF gear for some resistance rings, amulet, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_111_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>and switch to the MF gear when doing boss runs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_112_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Doesn't Lawbringer mostly add elemental damage, not physical?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_112_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NM Countess only drops up to Io (though you can get a Ko on the first quest kill if you are *extremely* lucky).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_112_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hell Countess will drop Lem and Ko.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_112_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, the decrepify from Lawbringer is useful, and the main reason to make one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_112_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The elemental damage could be handy to help chip away at physical immunes, and if I recall correctly, Sanctuary will ignore physical immunity of undead monsters, like Ghosts (which are among the most common PI monsters).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did you up that Bloodletter (Lum + Pul + Perfect Emerald) to an elite version?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or are you still using it as a Gladius (exceptional sword)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine that by lvl 76, its damage output would have fallen off considerably by now!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have little experience with Barbarian builds, but one decent option that could work is an Oath (Shael Pul Mal Lum) in the highest-damaging, fastest, **ethereal** 4 os sword you can get.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason why you want it to be ethereal is for the extra damage, and because Oath makes the weapon indestructible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can technically find all of those runes from running Hell Countess a bunch of times.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_113_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Mal may be a bit tricky, as it's near the top of her drop table, and she could just drop you a bunch of lower runes time after time if you are unlucky.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_114_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I played D2 from when the original game was released up through 1.13 patch for LoD. I never played the 1.14 patch, so in my memory, Oblivion Knights **always** had Lower Resist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_114_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, in every source that I have checked, I never saw anything about Lower Resist *ever* being removed from their curse repertoire--just Iron Maiden in 1.13.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_114_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, since you are obviously far more expert at D2 than I am (since you find my advice "meaningless"), then you shouldn't have any issue with Lower Resist or Oblivion Knights in general.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_114_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So I don't get what you are bitching about in the first place, since I don't tend to bitch about things which aren't causing me any problems... although I don't tend to bitch about things in general as I find it to be counterproductive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act II Mercs are your best bet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In normal, I'd go with a Defensive Merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I haven't found the extra AR from Blessed Aim to make that big of a difference for most melee or bow builds (Amazons have Guided Arrow if you're really having trouble hitting things), and Prayer doesn't feel like it heals fast enough to save you in sticky situations.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, potions are cheap and common anyway. ***</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, your mileage may vary!***</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, the extra defence from Defiance can make you less of a pincushion against ranged attackers, and it also makes your Merc himself a bit harder to hit, which can increase his tankiness.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, you'll mostly rely on him as an aura bot for runewords like Insight.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When you get to NM, it's a choice between Offensive (Might) and Defensive (Holy Freeze).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Offensive is good for melee builds, physical damage Bowazons, and Summonmancers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Holy Freeze works well for any other build that would benefit from extra crowd control, although the radius on his Holy Freeze aura feels *a lot* smaller than I recall from LoD classic, although my memory may be faulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thorns isn't worth using because by NM, most monsters have significantly more health than the amount of damage they inflict.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_115_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The added physical damage resistance many monsters have in NM (and nearly all have in Hell) makes Thorns and damage reflect abilities generally feel even more underwhelming by this point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Many white items (e.g. class-specific kit, staves, wands, and sceptres) have innate magic properties.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This does *not* make them magic items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those properties will carry over if you make a runeword in it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, if you make White (Dol + Io) in a white (or grey) Bone Wand with +3 to Bone Spear, you will end up with **+5** to Bone Spear. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+2 from the runeword, and the original +3 from the base item).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Drognan in Act II Normal can apparently sell +3 Bone Spear white wands.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've only seen up to +2, but keep shopping if you are planning to roll a Bonemancer!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, to make a runeword in a white (normal or superior) item, you need to socket it first.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can use a Horadric Cube recipe for this (doesn't work with superior items), or Larzuk's quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_116_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The latter is generally more likely to give you the max sockets that item can have, but this depends on where the item dropped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't really need physical defence as a Bonemancer--you shouldn't be getting in melee range anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only things physical defence *might* be useful against are archers, quill fiends, and those spear-chucking sabre cats.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, you will likely have a very powered-up Bone Armour to protect against the odd arrow or javelin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And for everything else, just drop a Bone Prison on them--it will block physical projectiles, but *not* your Bone Spears.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just make sure not to trap yourself in the Bone Prison with the monsters, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In addition, remember that defence doesn't provide damage reduction per se.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It only reduces enemies' chance to hit you with *physical* damage, and it is completely negated if you are running.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What you do need, however, are resistances (especially lightning and fire).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_117_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are many long-range enemies, like Gloams in Act III, IV (and as "guest monsters" in Act V NM and Hell) which will fry you in an instant if you don't have lightning resists, for example.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_118_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yup, those Gloams are a good reason to stay out of the Great Marsh, since you generally don't need to actually go there for any of the Act III quests.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_118_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, the worst monsters in Act III have to be those Bone Fetishes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_118_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now *those* things will ruin your day on NM and Hell with their death explosions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_118_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm guessing that % physical damage reduction could help, but I'm not sure how much difference it would make.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_118_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They seem to exist solely to punish melee or close-range attackers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_118_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorcs, Summonmancers, Bonemancers, Bowazons, and other ranged builds can just nuke them from a safe distance... usually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_119_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heh, now I need to go back to Act II and start shopping for one, since I gave up and made my White runeword in a +2 Bone Spear wand.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_120_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As someone who grew up watching Jeopardy, this hits me right in the feels.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_120_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Requiescas in Pace, Mr Trebek.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_120_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I honestly can't believe the chap is gone to great quiz hall in the sky.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_121_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Swole-ress is the way, you know :D. All jokes aside, if you play extra careful and stuff your kit full of perfect rubies (the things that *aren't*) runewords, you may be ok for a bit, unless you are on Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_121_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In that case, you may just need to toss her kit in the Shared stash and re-roll.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_121_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In the future, assign limiting stats (e.g. Strength) first.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_121_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Be patient and assign those points one by one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_121_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then, move onto vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_122_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D. You know... it might not be a bad idea to farm respec tokens if you have nothing else to do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_123_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What exactly was your Druid's name?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_123_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if you cannot post it here verbatim, at least give us a hint!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_123_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can imagine that they could just change your character's name, but I wouldn't be surprised if they may just delete it altogether, especially with all the server shenanigans.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_123_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were you, I'd drop your druid's stuff in the shared stash, and roll a new character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_124_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The issue I have with 'cancel culture' is that it's pure virtue signalling and theatre.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_124_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They go after things that are by no means actually offensive to anyone, whilst ignoring the things that actually **are** abusive, discriminatory, and just plain wrong.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_124_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are like Don Quixote tilting at windmills whilst there is an actual fucking Cyclops devouring the flocks in the fields.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_125_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you upgraded War Traveler to an elite unique, it would require 163 strength.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_125_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As others have pointed out, it isn't worth the cost in runes just for a bit extra defence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_125_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, if you ever decide you want to trade those War Travs for something else, nobody will want them as an elite unique with super-high strength and level requirements.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ach, I am sorry to hear that mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that you are *not* your work, and you will find another--and better--job.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Work is just a means to an end; it isn't an end in itself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Take it easy but don't give up looking for a new position.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish you best of luck.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apropos of your stats from those 50 Meph runs, I'm wondering whether this was NM or Hell Mephisto?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Posts like yours are very helpful, because they give me an idea of what to expect.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>50 runs isn't excessive, 300+ MF isn't ridiculous either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_126_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, if I'm hoping for Hell Mephisto to drop me a Buriza after a couple runs, well, now I know not to get my hopes up too much!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is true, but in terms of gear, the Hammerdin feels easier to equip.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Dual Spirit Crystal Sword and 4 os Pally shield will serve you well potentially until Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, with the Zealot, you'll need to constantly upgrade your weapons, and there really isn't any early equivalent to Spirit for melee classes. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe* Black in a Knout could help, but the knockback on that runeword can be a bit annoying in open areas, and you aren't going to get an Io rune before NM, whereas everything for Spirit--including the bases--can be obtained in Normal difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, physical immunes may be an issue for a Zealot in Hell, unless you have a reliable source of casting amplify damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, I can only think of three magic immune monsters: \- Wailing Beasts in Act III \- Plague Bearers zombies in Act II \- Super-unique greater mummy summoned by Baal in Act V \- Maybe some variant of tomb vipers in Act III or V, but I'm not 100% certain.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And that's about it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Two out of the three can be busted down with Holy Bolt, since they're undead; you probably have a lot of +skills (and Blessed Hammer is a synergy to Holy Bolt); and you probably have an insanely fast cast rate as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_127_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, the Maggot Lair will make you regret rolling a Hammerdin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_128_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I like to think that whoever designed the Maggot Lair must have been having a bad day, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_128_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, it isn't *that* bad for certain builds, but overall, it's one of the shittiest locations in the entire game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_128_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even the Kurast Sewers in Act III aren't as bad, although that dungeon itself is rather boring.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_129_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nice :D. Still, I'm curious about why you had to make your Lore in a Crown?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_129_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Was it just aesthetics as the Crown is a nice-looking helm... but the original graphics version looked *a bit* better, I must say!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_129_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair though, I would just make Lore in any 2 os helm you could find--Skull Cap, Cap, War Hat, Full Helm, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_129_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For most builds, the physical defence from your helm doesn't make that big a difference, and by the time it does, you'll probably have something better than Lore for your headgear slot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_130_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was thinking of using it on a Freezing Arrow Bowazon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_130_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For better or worse though, I'm playing offline, so trading would be out of the question!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_130_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, though, I want the Buriza also for the sake of nostalgia and prestige--I never managed to find one in the original LoD, and I fondly recall the days of 1.09 when Bowazons with Buriza do Kyanon were borderline OP, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_131_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to belts, every belt above the Heavy Belt will have 4 rows (16 total).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_131_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep in mind that exceptional belts (Demonhide Sash and onward) **all** have 16 slots.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_131_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a good idea to get a bigger belt as soon as you can.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_131_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sadly though, since we cannot upgrade Set items, this makes low-level sets that contain belts (e.g. Death's Touch) quickly obsolete or even borderline useless (except for individual components).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_131_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time you have enough strength to equip a War Sword, you wouldn't be using an 8-slot ordinary sash.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_131_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I really don't know what Blizzard was thinking with that set in particular.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_132_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yours is an unpopular opinion (and you did base your handle off the boss which everyone hates, heh), but I agree with you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_132_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Casting builds *already* have a potent endgame runewod available from **Normal** difficulty onward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_132_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Melee or physical damage builds (e.g. Bowazon) don't get anything equivalent to Spirit, *and* they need to change their weapons practically every Act, whilst the Spirit you can make at the end of Normal difficulty will serve you well through all of NM and even halfway through Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_133_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Redemption is the skill you are thinking of.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_133_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The OP mentioned that he/she is using a Sorceress.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_133_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless the OP has a Paladin in the party, or has a Phoenix runeword (which gives Redemption aura), his/her best bet is an item with Slain Monsters Rest in Peace (e.g. Nature's Peace or Lawbringer runeword), because otherwise, Redemption wouldn't be an option.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_133_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Phoenix grants lvl 10\~15 Redemption aura, but it's a damned expensive runeword to make (Vex Vex Lo Jah) whilst giving no buffs that a Sorc would actually find useful, other than the -28% to enemy fire resistance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_133_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But even that doesn't outweigh the benefits of a Spirit shield, I'd imagine.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_134_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I admire your persistence, mate!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_134_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I personally don't have the patience to do that, heh... especially when the map seed for Lut Gholein isn't kind enough to place the town exit on the east side (near Drognan).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_134_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I can't help but wonder whether my Bone Necro would be having an even better time with a +3 Bone Spear and +X Corpse Explosion base for his White wand?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_135_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is very helpful!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_135_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've been uncertain about whether max block is worthwhile for a Hammerdin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_135_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On the one hand, you are technically a caster, not a melee build, but on the other, you are normally getting pretty close to monsters to guarantee hits from Blessed Hammer...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_136_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, the issue with melee builds is that they are **extremely** gear dependent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_136_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is normal for ARPGs, but by NM and Hell in Diablo 2 (and D2R), a melee build using bargain bin kit will have a much harder time than a caster build using cheap gear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_136_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most of the gear needed for melee builds to have a fighting chance in Hell is expensive and/or rare.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_136_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Casters can get by with subpar gear since.. \- They don't need attack rating or physical defence \- They are typically ranged builds, so with some careful positioning, they don't need max resists (other than lightning, since the most dangerous fire attacks usually tend to be close-range) \- They don't need life leech \- They don't need max block (or blocking at all) There's good reason why the most popular MF builds tend to be casters, rather than melee or physical damage Immunities would technically be a hard counter to caster builds except that physical immune monsters are *not* uncommon at all in Hell difficulty, and most melee builds rely on physical damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_137_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I would like to see [Reziarfg](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/monsters/act5-reziarfg.shtml) as an actual boss, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_137_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whilst this creature was an internal April Fool's joke at Blizzard North, the design for that creature is quite impressive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_138_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I spent over 800k on gambling with a level 11 character, and no joy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_138_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then I ended up finding one as a drop from a random unique mob in Act I (when I went back with a character that had cleared normal and had about 200+ MF).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_138_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't say that gambling is the best way to get one, but it *is* an option if you have the gold to spare and nothing better to do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_138_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Good luck to all of you, and remember that Gheed needs your gold to woo them love-starved maidens, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_139_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only way to roll sockets in a Superior item is with Larzuk's quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_139_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But you are 100% correct that the Horadric Cube recipe doesn't work with superior items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_139_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I found this to my chagrin when I picked up a nice 15% ED Ancient Sword which I was hoping to save for a future Zealot or Barbarian... tossed it in the cube, and remembered that the recipe didn't work with superior items, and I sure as heck wasn't going to waste a Larzuk quest reward on that thing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_140_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, the idea of being able to kill any Act boss multiple times is itself a bit immersion-breaking, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you put it that way (I appreciate the inclusion of the drop stats, by the way!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have to agree with you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, I usually don't have the cash for gambling *that* much... and even if I do, I don't have the patience to buy up to 2000 daggers, sell them back, and rinse and repeat until I get a Gull.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For those who have the coin and the patience to do so, more power to you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The other issue I had when I finally got a Gull was that using it on my Bonemancer was a notable downgrade in kill efficiency due to the loss of +skills from his White runeword wand.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It felt more compatible with my Hammerdin, since my main weapon is a Spirit runeword crystal sword, so giving that up only means a loss of +2 skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes, I know I could equip it on weapon switch, but that would mean giving up my Gnarled Staff of Teleport--I don't have the runes for an Engima yet!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I don't like MF-ing on my Hammerdin mostly because of the Bone Fetishes in the Durance of Hate--at least my Bonemancer can kill those horrible little bastards from a safe distance before they get close enough to explode in my face, eheh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In short, maybe I just need to roll a Meteorb Sorc and use the Gull with her for my MF needs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_141_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish you all best of luck in your magic finding--may the Cathan's Seals and Manald Heals be sparse in your drops, and may RNG smile upon you :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_142_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is that in Act III?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_142_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've noticed that the jungle areas have this odd, unsettling cries at intervals as part of the ambient noise--it's hard to tell whether the sound is coming from hidden wildlife or a person who got caught by the Flayers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_142_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I guess we now know who was screaming like that... and I initially liked to think it was just monkeys.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_143_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd probably make a White runeword in a magic bone wand--it would make getting a good base for it a lot easier since I wouldn't need to keep bugging Drognan every minute to see if he is selling a non-magic wand that has at least +2 Bone Spear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_143_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or more likely, I'd just get the cheapest blue bone wand I could get from any TP/identify scroll seller, and re-roll it with chippies until I get 2 sockets and the +skills I want.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I honestly don't know why they never fixed this bug.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It makes mana burn one of the worst monster affixes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One thing that could help is to keep a column of full rejuvs in your belt for those sort of emergencies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, and be very careful whirlwinding when there are mana burn uniques around.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Taking a more cautious approach will slow down your clear speed, but at least it will keep you a bit safer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for leeching mana back, hopefully the things that burnt away your mana aren't skeletons, since those can't be leeched from NM onward, if I recall correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I could be mistaken.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_144_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, as I recall, the bug is also present in Resurrected as well -\_-.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_145_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now you've piqued my curiosity... I wonder if it's technically possible to mod the game so runewords can be made in magic, rare, unique,  amp; set items?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_145_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't recall ever seeing any Diablo II mod that had that, so I wonder if it is something hard-coded into the game or whether modders just didn't want to touch that system because of how crazy OP it could easily become, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_145_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I think it could be balanced by also making the enemies, especially uniques and act bosses *a lot* tougher.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_145_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, that's my type of game: powerful kit and enemies that are *all* dangerous, with very few trash or fodder mobs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_146_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Normal, Nightmare, Heck.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_147_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A simpler idea would be if Rune Master had a hidden affix that doubled the effects of whatever was socketed in it?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_147_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, put in a perfect Emerald, and get +200, instead of +100 poison damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_147_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>40/15 jewels would become 80/30, and so on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_147_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, that doesn't really pertain to the idea of runes, but at least it would make it *a bit* more desirable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_147_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time Ettin Axes start dropping, you are probably using some end-game runewords, and just loading Rune Master with 40/15 jewels would be nowhere as effective as the Grief, BotD you might already have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_148_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Despite what the item description says, Sacred Globes and other Orbs unfortunately **don't** count as staves for runewords that read "staff."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_148_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Likewise, warhammers, mauls, clubs (normal and spiked), and sceptres **don't** count as maces for runewords that read "mace" (and not also hammer/sceptre/club). [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_148_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml) Finally, although wands are labelled as "staff class" for calculating attack speed, they are most definitely not considered staves as far as runewords go.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_148_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you started out with an actual **staff** (2h weapon) and it somehow turned into a Sacred Globe (1h sorc only weapon) then that is definitely a very strange bug!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_149_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ah, but mods cannot be played online, and there's no TCP/IP (and likely never will be, sadly).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_149_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, console players don't have access to these mods.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_150_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Glad to be of help, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_150_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A lot of things in this game are really not transparent at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_150_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, ilvl of items determines the number of sockets they can have... along with the item type.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_150_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A Crystal Sword can have up to 6 sockets, but due to the ilvl of Crystal Swords that drop in Normal, you won't get a 6 os crystal sword with either Horadric Cube formulae or Larzuk's quest reward if you use it on a crystal sword you picked up in normal difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_150_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's no way of actually seeing an item's ilvl without running some sort of mod (not an option if you are playing online!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_150_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>or knowing the level of a particular area (you'll need to look this up online) where it dropped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_151_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'll definitely need to give a Frozen Orb/Firewall build a try, then!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_151_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I used to run a Meteorb sorc back in the days of LoD, and I enjoyed that build quite a bit more than single-element builds, since I was largely playing solo/offline.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_152_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only issue with Holy Freeze is shattering corpses--it doesn't happen that often, but it can be annoying if your Merc shatters the first corpse that you were hoping to detonate with Corpse Explosion or use as the start of the spooky skeleton squad.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_153_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Halbu *Hail to you, champion*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_153_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He doesn't say much, but his solemn, almost mournful manner as he frequently kneels to pray for deliverance and make the sign of the cross left a deep impression on me when I first played D2 classic as a kid.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_153_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of actual NPCs you can chat with, however, my favourite is probably Elzix.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_153_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He doesn't sell anything that useful, but he's such a friendly chap despite his past and the things he went through.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_153_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I find it hard he was formerly a desert bandit... more like the Robin Hood of Lut Gholein, perhaps, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_154_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Paladin shields are great for Spirit since they can **all** have 4 os from the dinky little targes you pick up in Act I normal to the Vortex Shields you'll be finding near the endgame.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_154_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's yet another reason why Hammerdins are so powerful--you can get your endgame budget caster gear in Normal, whilst everyone else needs to get 156 strength and reach Hell difficulty for a 4 os Monarch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_155_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I guess you are talking about Crystal Swords specifically, or 6-socket items in general?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_155_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine that you should be able to get 4+ os items (or socketable to this) from NM cows, as the [minimum ilvl](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets_by_Number) for an item to have 6 sockets is 41.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_155_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>ilvl is tied to area level, and NM Cows has an area level of 64.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_155_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you want a 4 os Crystal Sword, I'd run Normal Cows, since a Crystal Sword dropped in NM or Hell would likely end up with 5 or 6 sockets... and there aren't many uses for 6 os **Crystal Swords.** (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_155_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>5 and 6 os **Phase Blades**\-the elite equivalent of the crystal sword--are desirable, though).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_156_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I tend to gossip with Alkor every time I return to town, and I've never heard that one come up in D2R. I wouldn't be surprised if it were removed, considering that they also truncated Natalya's post-Gidbinn dialogue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_156_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Normally, she would say, ".... tempt me to go up against the Children of Zakarum *and their midget minions." "*</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_156_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Midget" isn't exactly a very polite or PC term these days, so I guess they took out that part, since her dialogue ends with "Zakarum" in D2R, which is odd, since you don't meet a single Zakarumite until you reach Kurast, and the Flayers aren't worshippers of Zakarum (though they are working on behalf of the Children of Zakarum more or less indirectly).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_157_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>His intro if you are a Necromancer is also quite heartwarming, as is his Necromancer-specific gossip.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_157_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He's the only NPC in the game who actually seems to like Necromancers, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_158_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whoever did the voice acting for Greiz did a fantastic job.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_158_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He really sounds like a badass... a shame that they didn't have that same voice actor for the mercenaries, though. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_158_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The merc really sound like rather delicate fellows compared to their boss!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm a bit sceptical about the idea of finding a 4 os Polearm in Act 1 *Normal*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The most common polearms that drop are Bardiches, with maybe a low-quality Scythe or Voulge near the end of the Act if you're lucky.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Bardiche-class polearms (Bardiche -- gt; Lochaber Axe -- gt; Ogre Axe) can only have a maximum of **three** sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The ilvl of those occasional Scythes would be too low to ever spawn with 4 os or to even be socketable to that number.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Second, for a Voulge to have 4 os, it needs an ilvl of at least 26.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I doubt there are any areas in Act II Normal with an area level of 26.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've also never seen Fara sell a 4 os weapon of any type on Act II Normal, but again, maybe you are luckier than I am with the vendor inventories.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have a screenshot of that, that would be nice!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, I believe that the earliest point at which you could get a 4 os Polearm would be Act IV normal, although the chances of one dropping already socketed are *extremely* low.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your best bet would be to take a non-socketed polearm that drops in Act IV, and either use Larzuk's quest reward (from Normal, if you haven't used it already) or take your chances with the Horadric Cube recipe (Ral + Amn + P amethyst).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that you cannot re-roll sockets on a non-magic polearm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_159_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Otherwise, Normal Cows is the best spot, as it has an extremely high enemy density (which means plenty of drops) and any build with good AoE damage can clear the area pretty efficiently.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_160_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I believe the Horadric Cube recipe would also work.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_160_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, I'd recommend the OP just get a white item in Normal Cows, then socket it at Larzuk or with the cube.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_160_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's how I got my 4 os Polearms and Crystal Swords; neither dropped with 4 os.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_161_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These resources may help a bit: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_161_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Area levels in D2 LoD: [https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area\_Level](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level) 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_161_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sockets by number (the table is organized horribly, I'm afraid): [https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets\_by\_Number](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets_by_Number) 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_161_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runeword rules: [http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml) You can assume an item that drops in a certain area level will have a maximum ilvl equivalent to that area.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_161_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is why certain areas are so popular to farm vs. others... and not just Boss runs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_161_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, The Pit lvl 2 and Ancient Tunnels have an ilvl of 85, which means nearly the full gamut of uniques and sets can drop in these areas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I respect your opinion, but I disagree **strongly**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For one, if you're getting bored of this game and have barely played, how would spending even *more* real-world money change that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do you mean that players would be able to farm for in-game currency which could then be used to buy particular items? *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This* would make sense, but it would be going down the same route as Diablo 3 with its auction house--it would ruin the in-game economy and incentivize undesirable behaviours like botting, duping, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But please explain how a *monthly subscription* would make the game more interesting for you--or anyone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you subscribe to the sunk cost fallacy and think that you need to keep devoting more of your time to something just because you have spent (or are spending) more money on it, paying a monthly fee **on top of the base cost of the game** is no bueno.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't mean to be rude, but perspectives like the one you have outlined here contribute to the reason why games these days are so stale, soulless, unfinished, and uninspired compared to the titles from the era when D2 and LoD original were released. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Games as a service" has **not** improved the quality of the titles available to us by any means whatsoever.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is the era of permanent Early Access, day one DLC, and so forth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, I think I understand your rationale.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The D2R servers are in a deplorable state nowadays.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are probably thinking that if it's this bad now, it will get even worse going forward unless Blizzard gets some revenue from this game and has incentive to devote more resources to it, right?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I cannot blame you for thinking that, but keep in mind that Activision Blizzard is **not** a poor or struggling company, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They have billions of dollars in profits.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If they aren't willing to spend the time and resources right now to provide stable servers for D2R shortly after its launch--when interest is at its peak--trying to milk this title for more coin by adding a monthly fee isn't going to change that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, I imagine that microtransactions and/or monthly fees will kill this game deader than poor Deckard Cain in D3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_162_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And you can definitely kiss your D2R servers or any hope of multiplayer goodbye for good :(.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few more things worth noting: \- Monster health is also increased (I believe multiplicative) with the number of players.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>/player 5 = monsters with 5x more health, etc. \- **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some** runs work better at lower player numbers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, the Countess has the best rune drops at /players **1**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason is that higher player numbers will increase the amount of other treasure she drops, and potentially cut into other rune drops... or so I've heard.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So always run the Countess on /players 1 for best results! \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Boss runs above /players 3 don't provide significant additional benefits, or so I've heard \- Some builds don't perform very well at higher /players x commands.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Skills like Corpse Explosion **do not scale with increased monster health**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So a CE that may have wiped half the screen on /players 1 may only hurt a bunch of monsters badly on /players 8. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Choose the optimal setting between exp and loot drops and kill speed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it is taking you too long to kill things, don't be afraid to drop the /players x level \- /players x changes don't affect monsters already on screen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It will affect monsters about 1 screen away \- you can reset to the default (/players 1) by just typing "/players".</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_163_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's recommended to reset it before dealing with annoying bosses like Duriel (whose drops tend to be shit anyway).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a simple rule of thumb, life and mana leech only apply to skills with attack rating (and Guided Arrow).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Smite always hits, and thus cannot leech life. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NB: if you want to leech life as a Smiter, get a source of Life Tap!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Fury Druid, all of your physical attack skills (Rabies, Fury, Feral Rage, Hunger, Maul, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>would benefit from it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spells don't benefit from "on hit" effects.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm pretty certain they also don't benefit from +x% damage to demons/undead either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is for balance purposes--if a spell projectile connects with a target, it will *always* hit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If casters could leech mana and health with things like Bone Spear and Glacial Spike, that would be borderline OP, no?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Edit: I'm not sure of how these effects apply to Assassin kick attacks, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_164_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Someone with more experience than I with Kicksins can probably answer that question!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_165_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes, you can do so.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_165_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However... keep in mind this works both ways.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_165_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you change difficulty to shop for an item for a lower level character, that could result in losing your ideal map seed, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_166_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Bonesnap (unique maul) is too slow *and* low damage for Hell difficulty!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_166_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It definitely isn't worth upping either with the Horadric Cube recipes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_166_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It could be a short-term option in Normal for a budding Fury Druid, but again, there are much better options (e.g. Ribcracker which provides a much higher chance of Crushing Blow and an insanely fast attack speed to boot).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The issue with trying to hybridise--*especially as a solo player on Hell difficulty--*is that you won't have the damage from synergies or skill points invested to really be good at either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep in mind that as a Bonemancer, your damage will primarily come from your spells, whilst as a summonmancer, it comes from your minions and your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you try to make a Bonemancer who dabbles in summoning, your spell damage will suffer markedly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Bone Spear can become extremely powerful, but it requires a decent amount of hard skill points, + skills, and synergies to be competitive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The same goes for summons--they get quite potent with a lot of + skills, but many of the kit you'll want as a Bonemancer (e.g. White runeword wand) doesn't pertain to Summonmancers, and vice versa.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hybrid builds make sense for certain classes like Sorceresses, which have to deal with rather abundant elemental immunities.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Bonemancer, you will encounter very, very few magic immune monsters, and most of them are entirely optional to deal with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only magic immunes I can think of are the following: \- Plague Bearers in Act II (around Lost City and Ancient Tunnels) \- Wailing Beasts in Act III \- Guardians in Act II (Claw Viper Temple); Horadrim Ancients in Kurast Sewers; Achmel the Cursed et al.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>summoned by Baal in Act V And in most cases, most of these magic immunes are surrounded by things that *aren't* magic immune--in the case of the Greater Mummy variants, this would be their skeletons... which means you can burst down the skellies with Bone Spear, curse the Greater Mummies with Amplify Damage, then wipe them out with Corpse Explosion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, there's no reason to really hybridise as a Necromancer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_167_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are pure Summonmancer, you'll rely on your merc for the first kill to start the spooky skeleton party.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_168_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want to use the Cube recipe, be aware that it may *not* give the max number of sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_168_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a gamble.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_168_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, remember that the Horadric Cube recipe does **not** work with superior items--just normal quality white items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_169_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Teeth is a synergy for Bone Spear so it makes sense to level it, but I've heard that the projectiles don't exactly "shotgun"--enemies cannot be hit with more than one Tooth for extra damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_169_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, your Dentist Necromancer build does indeed sound like a very good choice for hardcore--anaesthise the "patients" first with Dim Vision before going to work on the Teeth, and bring out the Bone Spear drill for delivering long distance root canals :D. Your Necro is doing good work: ridding Sanctuary of demons *and* promoting proper oral health and hygiene!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_169_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now if we could just get an Assassin to partner with Larzuk to promote hand-washing before meals\*, Sanctuary would be a much healthier place!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_169_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\*One of Nihlathak's character-specific gossips consists of him trying to sic the Assassin on Larzuk for "hand-washing before meals" as evidence of "corrupt magic" because this was how Larzuk avoided catching the Red Plague last season...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_170_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's also worth noting that the following won't change: \- If ethereal, the armour will remain ethereal after upping \- If there's something socketed in it, the socketed item will stay Upgrading The Spirit Should (unique ghost armour) won't turn it into Ormus' Robes (unique Dusk Armour).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_170_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll just get The Spirit Shroud, unique dusk armour with correspondingly higher stat and level requirements.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_171_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of your last point about "skins," modders have already been releasing some rather impressive visual mods for classes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_171_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Someone made a mod that allows the Barbarian to cosplay as Kratos from God of War, and there are also mods that approximate the original armour look and artwork for the Amazon and Assassin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_171_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, you cannot use these mods if playing online or on console, sadly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_172_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That 88 strength though -\_- is what puts me off upping a Goldwrap--it will make it much less accessible to a variety of characters, since I tend to swap MF gear among different characters I am playing thanks to the shared stash.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_172_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, it's a *real* shame that we cannot upgrade **set items**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_172_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Death's Disguise would be a very nice set if it weren't so mismatched.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_172_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time you have enough strength to equip a War Sword on most builds, a simple 8-slot sash (Death's Guard) will not be sufficient at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_172_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Likewise, some of the rather nice early game sets would be a lot better if we could upgrade them to keep them, or at least components of them relevant.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_173_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes, it's a term specific to Korea.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_173_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>PC literally translates to "PC Room" if I recall correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_173_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The appeal of them isn't because most Korean kids don't have (or cannot afford) good computers; it's more for the social atmosphere and snacks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_173_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are also the place where Korean students' productivity and motivation goes to die, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The "Noraebang" () always struck me as the "PC Bang" for (ajeoshi)--middle-aged chaps who drink far more soju than they should: my type of chaps, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some of the slightly more... interesting places even allowed you to invite some young ladies on hire.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are correct that Korea is an *interesting* place.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I haven't visited any other country where the convenience stores sell Johnnie Walker and single malt whisky, and where soju is cheaper than Coca-Cola. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine Russia might be similar, but I've never been there.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't even think they are as strict about "carding" people, but then again, that might be because I first moved to Korea when I was 26, and likely since I'm clearly not Korean, they assumed I was above the legal drinking age.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, most of the locals never had any trouble guessing my age more or less correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, even when I was in my 30s, they tended to think I didn't look *that* old, but not underage or anything.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I miss the place sometimes (good, inexpensive food, pretty women, virtually no crime, and friendly people), but I **don't** miss the traffic and urban congestion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Rocky Mountains where I now reside allow me to feel a deeper connexion with nature, because like the Druid, I'm not a city person.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And I always thought I was more Paladin than Druid.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_174_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whilst I may look somewhat like the OG Paladin (if he wore spectacles under that crown helm), I certainly don't have his chastity and I tend to be a bit more foul-mouthed and irreverent than the Church of Zakarum would approve of, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just wondering, what do you mean by a "Skelebone Necro"?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do you mean a hybrid between Summoning and Poison and Bone skills?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or a pure Summonmancer or Bonemancer?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Honestly, it sounds like your main problem is resistances, friendo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Get yourself an Ancient's Pledge shield to boost those resists, especially fire and lightning.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can get by fine with shoddy cold resistance, as very few things (other than Coldcrow, that bitch, lol) inflict direct cold damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for poison, well, they have Antidote Potions for that... and just stay away from Greater Mummies since as a Necro, you shouldn't be in melee range.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since you don't have a 4 os Monarch yet, you won't lose anything by using an Ancient's Pledge shield (Kite or Large Shield; Fara in Normal Act II sells 3 os shields pretty regularly).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But whatever you do, stay out of the lightning hose.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, as a Necromancer, you probably want to focus on one tree--either Summoning or Poison and Bone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hybridizing doesn't work well at all, in my experience unless you're a Sorceress.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's your skill allocation thus far, I'm wondering?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Considering that summonable minions get a substantial life buff in NM, Summoning Necros generally shouldn't have as bad a time against NM Diablo than the Normal version of Big D. Remember that Decrepify + Clay Golem will slow Diablo to a crawl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pure Summonmancers are really not very gear dependent, since +skills is easy to obtain on the cheapest Necromancer kit, and your skellies, rather than your weapon damage, is what determines how fast you kill things.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_175_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since I'm only playing SP now, I unfortunately cannot help you directly other than offering some somewhat general/generic advice and moral support... and an upvote because your creative description gave me a much-needed laugh after a long and shitty day at work.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_176_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is the way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_176_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can stack so many Bone Prisons on even Act bosses that it's pretty much a life sentence for them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_176_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, even Bone Prison gets a significant buff to its HP in NM and Hell, which makes it even more amusing to use.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_176_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You just need to be careful not to trap yourself in the bone zone along with whatever mob you are trying to shut down, although a source of teleport (e.g. staff with teleport charges) can solve that problem if you react fast enough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_177_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep in mind that with the shared stash, you can use those items you don't want as levelling kit for other builds/characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_177_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Once you "outgrow" them (e.g. Wormskull), you can just feed them to Charsi.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_177_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember, Charsi is *always* hungry, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_178_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Read what I wrote again, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_178_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I stated that people go to the PC Bangs mostly for the social atmosphere and snacks (edited to remove "free," since you actually have to pay for the food there.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_178_2</DOCNO>
