        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_178_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even at my current age, I've gone to PC Bangs because they had good (tteokbokki).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_178_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's akin to the reason why people go to bars when they just as readily drink at home, and for cheaper too.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_178_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, given the demographics who frequent PC Bangs in Korea, hooking up with members of the opposite gender isn't necessarily a particular motivating factor whereas it can be for bar-hopping.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_179_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Somehow, that looks even more terrifying than the actual location in-game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_179_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your artwork makes it look like a veritable fortress that requires crossing not platforms, but *trenches* in between No Man's Land of congealed lava to reach.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_179_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If that is what Marius saw when he paused before the Infernal Gate, I really cannot blame him for his decision.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_179_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;!Basically noping out of that and deciding to spend the rest of his days in a madhouse until Baal decided to pay him a visit!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The way I used to 'handwave' that inconsistency is that most of the demons weren't there until *after* Diablo and Baal passed through.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But even if this was the case, the timeline doesn't add up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, even most of the demons and other beasties weren't present, there are **still** plenty of nasty things in the jungle--Giant Spiders, Flayers, Giant Frogs, those damn Water Watchers which hang out in the rivers, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But if I think about it a bit more, there are probably two things at work here: First, Tyrael was hoping that Marius would link up with the player's character, and accompany him/her on that journey.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that Tyrael just tells Marius to *take the stone to the Hellforge, where it will be destroyed*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He doesn't actually tell Marius to destroy it himself!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Second, Marius made it that far on his own likely because Diablo, Baal, and Mephisto **allowed him to**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Brothers told their demons and other nasties to stand by (and not kill Marius in a 1000 different ways) because everything was working according to their plan--Marius would see them in action (a sight not meant for mortal eyes), lose his mind, and nope out of there to become a permanent resident at his local madhouse, and perhaps scare the Akarat out of everyone else by babbling about the insane things he saw.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd even argue that Mephisto's little speech in the Act III cinematic was solely for Marius' benefit--Diablo and Baal already knew the score, and they knew that Marius was there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The demons are sadistic gits; cf.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>how Baal toys with both Marius and the Barbarian representative at the start of Act V rather than just murdering them immediately.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Slaughter isn't as fun if the victim doesn't have the illusion of hope, I guess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The three Brothers had planned their Dark Exile centuries ago, and had fooled everyone--the Horadrim, Tyrael and the other archangels, and even the Lesser Evils.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, Baal tells Marius in the Epilogue, "You haven't failed, old man.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have done *exactly as you were meant to do.*"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But all this really confirms your statement: Tyrael was an idiot of epic proportions to think that a rat like Marius would somehow redeem himself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_180_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Marius wouldn't have been able to carry out his task even if Bul-Kathos himself were carrying him, literally, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_181_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest thing I agree with is your suggested change to Vengeance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_181_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than a few very niche builds, that is probably one of the worst Paladin skills, which is a shame, because it has some of the best lore behind it (empowering your weapon with the vengeful spirits of the righteous).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_181_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Currently Vengeance really illustrates the weakness of melee combat in this game--very few reliable sources of AoE/multi-target damage compared to ranged skills and spells.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_181_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is slow, single-target, and has an escalating mana cost to boot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_181_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Giving Vengeance some AoE would make it a lot better and actually worth using!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As others have pointed out, it's likely that Diablo wanted a calm environment free from distractions to plan out his strategy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Would *you* really want a bunch of bumbling Venom Lords and Oblivion Knights bugging you about every little issue, or Hephaesto showing up several times a day to complain that the Hellforge needs more souls?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, considering that the River of Flame is filled with Blood Maggots half the time, I can't blame Diablo for locking the door.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those oversized bugs make a huge mess!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All jokes aside, that makes me wonder, though--was Baal's plan *always* to corrupt the Worldstone from the very beginning?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or was it a sort of contingency, a "plan B" after Mephisto and Diablo got killed?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's also odd about the Prime Evils is that despite being the Lord of Terror, Diablo seems to be the most straightforward in his approach--smash stuff, burn, loot, and kill.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I guess that does spread terror, but you'd think Big D would be more into psy ops than straightforward destruction, and leave that to Baal?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_182_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That really makes me wonder if the "personalities" of the Prime Evils are in any way influenced by the mortal hosts they occupy... and whether the Lesser Evils (e.g. Andariel and Duriel) also need a mortal host to manifest on the mortal realm or not.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_183_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>KHORNE DEMANDS SKULLS FOR THE SKULL THRONE!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_183_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All jokes aside, skulls (chipped and perfect) are an ideal resource for Horadric Cube recipes that call for gems like socketing magic items and rerolling charms because they are not used for crafted items or transmuting runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_183_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runes after Thul start to require a supplementary gem to transmute them to the higher level, but none of those recipes use skulls.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_183_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, if you use skulls for your rerolling and magic socketing recipes, you can save your other gems for crafted items and upgrading runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd argue that a Trapsin (Lighting Sentry + Death Sentry) is even better than a Summonmancer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's why: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are extremely tanky since you need just enough strength to equip a Spirit runeword sword (43), *zero* dexterity, at most 10 points in Energy, and can dump the rest in Vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If your resists are suffering, you can just use Fade.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You also get more HP per vitality point investment than the Necro.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You never need to actually get anywhere near the fight once you are running your traps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can even toss traps at the edge of the screen to begin killing monsters off-screen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have an extremely tanky summon (Shadow Warrior and Shadow Master) which isn't dependent on corpses, but you don't need to manage an army of bumbling skeletons which will block your path.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You laugh at Maggot Lair and Arcane Sanctuary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have powerful equivalents to *both* Corpse Explosion and Dim Vision (Death Sentry and Cloak of Shadows, respectively) 6.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your movement speed is insanely fast with Burst of Speed, so you technically don't even need teleport (though it's still nice to have).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your minions/summonables cannot be killed, and you don't need corpses to start the party 8.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are no lighting immunes in Normal difficulty if I recall correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Normal Diablo is often a pain for Summonmancers due to how quickly he shatters your skeletons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Trapsins don't have that issue--just drop 5 lightning sentries on Big D, then stay off screen, then rinse and repeat until he's dead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The more I think about it, everything a Summonmancer can do, a Trapsin can do better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A well-built Summonmancer can edge ahead in Hell difficulty, though since physical immunes are nowhere as common as lightning immunes, and the Necro has Amplify Damage to break some weaker PI, whilst the Trapsin would need Infinity on her merc (or a Lower Resist wand on switch) to do the same.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_184_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But since you mentioned you are just clearing Normal up to quest 1 of Act V, the long-term viability of your build isn't a concern.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Think of Dexterity as just a prerequisite for equipping your gear, or getting max block rate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some Amazon builds do pump dexterity for added damage, but this will effectively make you a glass cannon and isn't really advisable in my opinion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're having issues with Attack Rating, there are a few things that may help: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Equip the Angelic Wings and Angelic Halo set items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This gives a massive boost to AR.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that many guides suggest this.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Both of these items can technically drop in Normal, but I personally haven't had any luck finding the amulet... 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Find a weapon that has "ignores target defence."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that ITD doesn't apply to Act bosses 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Equip weapons with -% to target defence on hit (or put Eth runes in your weapon).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That will help increase your chance to hit, and it does work against act bosses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Use a Blessed Aim Act II merc from Normal difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A Might merc on NM does provide a substantial damage boost, but this means little if your hit chance is only around 50%!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_185_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't pump dexterity just to boost AR.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason to stay away from Yew wands is that they cannot have 2 sockets at any ilvl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Bone wands are the first wand that can have up to 2 sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for getting more Dol and Io runes, NM Countess runs are a healthy and safe source of Dol runes, and she can drop Ios occasionally.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just be sure to save plenty of chipped gems for upgrading any lower runes she drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Her quest drops (for the first kill) will often include additional runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if you're supremely unlucky like my Trapsin, there's a chance she may not drop a *single* rune on the first kill.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_186_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But that is extremely rare and I'm wondering if it was a bug.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_187_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Melee builds (and Bowazons) have it extremely rough in this version of D2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_187_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd be intrigued to hear what ideas you can offer to make melee builds more viable without needing nigh-unobtanium BiS gear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_187_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than some drastic changes in gameplay mechanics--or the introduction of new features like melee splash damage--I can't really think of any small tweaks that can make melee and physical damage builds more viable without fundamentally changing the way the game works.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_188_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You're right about the skeletons not blocking the path.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_188_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I used to like Summonmancers back in LoD classic, but for some reason, in D2R, they just don't feel quite as fun to play.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_188_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It could just be the Mandela effect--I'm remembering the Summonmancer more fondly than it actually was, but it could also be that D2R feels faster-paced than LoD classic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_188_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, the classic version ran at 30 FPS, whilst this game runs at 60?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What would be a "better" or less "fucking stupid meta" in your perspective?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To me, at least, the idea of physical attributes (strength and dexterity) affecting spell damage also sounds pretty damn silly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I haven't seen many other ARPGs (other than Diablo III) in which pumping strength somehow boosts your spell damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't see how having bigger muscles would make your fireballs or magic missiles stronger.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not like you are physically hurling your spells, scrolls, or spellbooks at the enemy!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, points in Energy should affect spell damage the way that dexterity incrementally raises bow damage, and strength incrementally raises physical weapon damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That would be consistent with RPG tropes since the pen  amp; paper days in which warriors needed strength, rogues needed dexterity, and casters needed willpower.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also wouldn't say that caster builds are "meta" at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are just easier to play and equip since they are generally nowhere as item dependent as melee builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, melee builds are still viable to get you through *most* of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, some caster builds (e.g. Poison Necro) can be quite gear-dependent to actually be effective in Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One of the biggest things that gives casters an edge is how accessible, cheap, and potent the Spirit, Stealth, and Insight runewords are.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm not saying these runewords should be nerfed, but if there were similarly cheap and effective runewords for melee, that would help even the playing field a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_189_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ancient's Pledge is a great and inexpensive runeword, but its utility is pretty general--everyone can do with some Ancient's Pledge in their life starting out... unless you're a pure Bowazon or a Fury druid, generally.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To clarify a bit--as a Hammerdin, you generally are fighting in close quarters with monsters to guarantee the spiralling hammer hits, whereas other casters can stand much further back and spam spells from well beyond the fray.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Holy shield means that you don't need to invest quite as much dex to get max block.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm glad to hear that your Hammerdin feels tanky, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For some reason, mine (currently in Act V NM at lvl 58) feels unusually squishy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do have *close* to max block, but it feels like the hits that do get through really chunk my health badly-and this has been the case since Act I NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What makes it even odder is that the Hammerdin actually has better elemental resists than the Trapsin... but it may just be that fighting up close, I will be taking a lot more hits than the 'sin who just hangs out in the back distributing lightning and death sentries like Oprah giving out free cars.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'll probably need to look again at my stat allocation, as I probably don't have enough points in vitality and maybe *a few* too many in strength (I may have overdone it to try to equip better armour).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_190_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I still have an unused NM Den of Evil respec on my Hammerdin, so I'm not too worried.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, the only thing really worth farming on Normal is the Countess for low-level runes for basic runewords, e.g. Ancient's Pledge, Stealth, and Spirit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe also Normal Cows for runeword bases.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that in the case of Spirit, the Countess *won't* drop Amn runes, but you can get enough Tals and Orts from her to brute-Cube your way up to an Amn in short order.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Getting a suitable base for Spirit could be a bit tough before the end of Normal, though--the most reliable sources of 4 os bases will be Normal Cows, but that requires you to defeat Baal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What is your level currently?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you are playing in a group, I wouldn't take on Act V under level 30, since you will also be getting a lot less experience.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, what's your skill allocation?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you specialising in Zeal, Blessed Hammer, or some odd hodge-podge of skills?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most builds really begin at lvl 30.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, keep in mind that your build doesn't *really* matter that much in normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, remember that a lack of elemental resistances will really hurt you badly in this game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Try to have max resists across the board, but if you must choose, lightning and fire are crucial The difficulty levels are, in some ways, analogous to schooling: Normal = secondary school.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do whatever you want, and figure out the rest of your life.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But do have an idea of what you want to specialise or major in!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Lingering here won't do you much good.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nightmare = university.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Have a plan for your future career, and begin to specialise (i.e. your build/major!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hell = graduate school\*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You **must** be specialised by this point with a solid build, because this is where you'll truly build your career.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you haven't prepared well previously, go back for more "education" (farm NM for levels, Countess for runes, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_191_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\*If you've attended med school or know anyone who has, you might agree that medical school *is* hell--but with fewer demons and far more sleep deprivation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It sounds like you'll need to equip your Merc better, for one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Smoke or Treachery runeword armours will give him much more survivability.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A source of life leech will also help him stay alive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The second thing you'll need to do is babysit him a bit, perhaps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since you're a Sorc, you have innate access to teleport.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If he's in over his head, teleport away to pull him out of the fight, heal him with potions (shift+potion hotkey), then start orbing those demons down again.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Depending on your positioning, sometimes your Merc *won't* get into the fight when you need him to.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The other thing you can do is pull off the mercenary bug (google this) which makes your merc untargettable by enemies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_192_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, as you probably rely on your merc for tanking and pinning monsters in place to drop meteors on their heads, I'm not sure that that having an untargettable hireling would necessarily be desirable...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_193_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have seen rune drops up to Dol in Normal Act V. You get an Ort rune from quest 2 in Act V, and depending on your luck, you can cube up to Thul (with no gems required) from the Countess alone in Act I. Finally, Normal Hellforge can drop up to Amn.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_193_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So you can **definitely** get the runes for Spirit in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_193_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It may take a bit of grinding and luck, but it's possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_193_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, those runes you need are *much* more common in NM than Normal as regular drops (and from the Countess).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_193_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest challenge in Normal (as far as Spirit) is concerned is getting a suitable 4 os base, but again, Normal Cows is your best bet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_194_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Aye, that might be it--force-feeding him full rejuvs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_194_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I feel your pain in the Chaos Sanctuary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_194_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish you best of luck, friendo, because if you rely on your merc to deal with immunes or to tank for you, that sounds like a huge pain in the arse!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When you put it that way, I agree with you that it would be nice if strength and dex served *more* purpose than just gear prequisites.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you prefer playing offline, there is hope that modders can tweak the game to make things a bit more balanced.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In all honesty, though, I would happily see bow requirements tied **solely** to strength, with dexterity governing attack speed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Logically, more powerful bows (with higher draw weight) depend more on arm strength than dexterity, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But it's an old D amp;D trope that bows = dexterity rather than strength.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, effectiveness with a sword depends *more* on dexterity than raw strength, but I digress.. As for brain-dead monkeys being able to allocate stats, I wouldn't quite say that is the case.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_195_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you don't have Insight yet, mana issues can be irksome for caster builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_196_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, you make sure that you don't have a Valkyrie *already* summoned.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_196_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't say it is a bug per se, but more of an annoying feature to ensure that all classes *don't* instantly gain access to an extremely powerful summonable for very low rune costs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_196_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That reminds me of something, though: why are the rune costs for the class-specific runewords so widely varied?! "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_196_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Peace" and "Treachery" are dirt-cheap for the benefits they provide compared to some of the other 1.11 armour runewords... and many of the others are more or less a waste of runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_197_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In some ways, I actually enjoyed Diablo I more than Diablo II, oddly enough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_197_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D1 felt like a more story-driven experience than the sequel, and the world felt far more dark, oppressive, and frightening.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_197_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo II felt more like a loot-based game where the quests and world-building mattered *far* less.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_197_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I'm comparing LoD to Diablo I. If I compared vanilla Diablo II to Diablo 1, both were enjoyable in their own right on the standard difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_197_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I ended up playing D1 *years* after I played through D2 repeatedly...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_198_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is very true--especially if one is playing offline or SSF!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_198_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if the OP already has another character who has cleared Normal (and is parked in NM or Hell), then a Spirit sword wouldn't be too difficult to get (run Normal cows with that other character until you have a good base and runes, then switch back to the Larzuk-ing builds, recycling the Spirit sword among each one).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_198_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If this character the OP is considering is his *first* character, however, then you are 100% correct!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In some Diablo 2 mods (e.g. Hell Unleashed), the Act I mercs can use crossbows.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you played one of those mods, you may be remembering that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also note that the Act I mercs are *not* Amazons and thus cannot equip Amazon-specific bows (e.g. Reflex Bow, Grand Matron Bow, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So if you find any nice lower level Amazon bows you may want to save them for levelling a future Bowazon as they'll have no other use (they aren't worth much gold at vendors compared to +skills wands, staves, sceptres, and even Sorceress orbs) As a general reminder, in unmodded D2 (or D2R), the only weapons/kit that are equippable by mercs are: Act I: Bows (non-Amazon type) Act II: Spears, polearms, javelins (they don't throw the javelins, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And again, no zon-specific javelins for... obvious reasons, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We haven't come that far yet, heh).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act III: Swords (1handed), shields.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your best bet is to give them a Spirit runeword to increase their cast rate, but these lads are sadly quite ineffective compared to the desert ramblers of Act II. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe* a Paladin with some points in Conviction could benefit from these to deal with physical immunes in Hell (whilst you tank for yourself), but their damage is usually not too great.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act V: Swords (1 and 2 handed), but no dual-wielding.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_199_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since these chaps *are* Barbarians, they can equip Barb-specific helms</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_200_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine that most Paladins who want a Spirit shield are Hammerdins rather than Smiters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_200_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, Spirit is so cheap in terms of runes that finding an "ideal" base for it doesn't sound *quite* as essential as it would be for something like Exile, which requires expensive and rare high runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_200_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you are saving that 4 os shield for an Exile or some other expensive shield runeword, I'd just make Spirit in whatever 4 os Paladin shield provides the best bonuses... especially resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_200_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you find a better base, you'll likely already have the runes to make another Spirit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_201_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This made me laugh more than it should have after a 12-hour day at work (sometimes I feel like an Administratum adept at my job).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_201_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well done :D</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't feel too bad about that, friendo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cleglaw's claw is pretty damn common at low levels... and it isn't even that great a shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's the sort of thing you use for a level or 2 in Act I normal before you find something better, aka an Ancient's Pledge you can make right at the start of Act II if you ran a train on the Countess repeatedly and had a bit of luck.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Old Cleggie's pincers, however, are nice gloves: the knockback is annoying for melee characters, but amusing for Bowazons... and the 25% slow is good for every melee/physical damage build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, that % slows target *stacks* with cold damage effects, and whilst some monsters effectively have zero chill effectiveness (like those Death Lord arseholes in Act V), nothing is immune to % slows target, unless I am remembering things differently.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For melee builds in Normal, Cleglaw's Pincers were my go-to gloves for killing Act bosses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_202_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd even hold onto them into NM for that reason, unless you have something better by that point (e.g. gloves with IAS, crushing blow, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few more things that may help you as a Hammerdin: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Try to position monsters so they are above you (attack from the bottom of the screen).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you must attack things coming from the bottom of the screen, try to position them slightly off to your right since the Hammer originates from your Hammerdin's left shoulder (if I'm not mistaken).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Learn to use the left mouse button for your attacks as any sort of Paladin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Right mouse button skills are for auras.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hotkey those auras to switch between them as need be.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Hammerdin, you'll only be using Concentration, Vigor (for movement speed between fights), Salvation (for resists if you or your merc are getting roasted or electrocuted), and *maybe* Redemption to refill after the slaughter.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cleansing could be handy for removing poison and curses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hotkey your left mouse button skills Charge and Blessed Hammer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can use Charge to zoom across the map (watch your mana) and for getting in hammer range against archers and other ranged attackers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Maggot Lair will suck.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's just something you need to deal with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On your second visit (on NM), you should have a Staff of Teleport to help get through there a bit faster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On your first runthrough, just try to fight the bugs in more open rooms, and locate the next floors as quickly as possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't even need to stick around to pop Coldworm unless you really want to.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_203_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since there is no "force move" key, there's not much reason to not use left and right click for attacks on your Sorc, unless you set your left mouse button to throw item (which won't do anything if your Sorc doesn't have a throwing weapon equipped!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_204_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never used Iron Golem very much, but I'm curious about whether the Golem will persist when changing difficulties (in single player)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_204_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The despawn bug for summonables is *very* annoying, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_204_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't recall LoD classic having that bug...</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_205_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\- Buy 'em from normal level vendors up through Act II (vendors from Act III onward only sell magic items... which may have sockets but can't be turned into runewords) \- Use Horadric Cube [Recipes](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) to add sockets to items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_205_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The number of sockets you can get is a gamble, though \- Use Larzuk's quest reward in Act V to add sockets to the item of your choice \- Just find them as drops from monsters and chests.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_205_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that socketed items will all have grey names... as do ethereal items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_205_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only way to tell whether an item is socketed or ethereal (or socketed *and* ethereal) is to pick it up and check.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_205_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can find socketed items from level 1 in the Blood Moor; they really aren't rare at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_205_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, at higher levels, note that you may want to lower your MF to increase your drops of socketed items (e.g. in the Cow Level).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_206_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By Blood Lords, do you mean the vampiric fireball-hurling undead in Act II, or those frenzy-using bastards in Act V?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_206_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't mind the former *that* much, but I hate the latter with a passion... they also gain physical immunity in Hell difficulty too and weren't even decent enough to choose a unique name for themselves ffs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_206_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although unique vampires can be surprisingly tanky and annoying to deal with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some white/grey items can spawn with implicit mods (e.g. wands, staves, sceptres, Sorceress orbs, and class-specific equipment).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This doesn't make them magic items, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the item name is blue/yellow/green/gold, it **cannot** become a runeword, no matter what.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, if you're having issues with Duriel, try drinking a lot of thawing potions beforehand to reduce his cold damage, and force-feeding about 10 of them to your mercenary as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The duration from each thawing potion is 30 seconds of +50 cold resist, and the duration stacks with each subsequent potion use.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let your merc tank against Duriel and always have a town portal open so you can retreat to heal, then return to the fight.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, consider reserving a column in your belt for full rejuvenation potions (or even just regular rejuvs) for that fight.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_207_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you've been stockpiling purple potions, start cubing them into full rejuvs, as these can save your arse in dire situations.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, you can't *really* go from "Battle Scythe to Thresher" unless said battle scythe or thresher is a rare or unique item--in which there are Horadric cube recipes for upgrading them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For normal and magic items, you just make do with what drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to upping uniques, some are worth upgrading, others are not.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But do keep in mind that upgrading an item will increase the required level notably, and it doesn't change it into a different unique.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Upgrading Rixot's Keen won't turn it into Bloodletter, for instance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, there's one important thing to remember about superior items--if they don't already spawn with the desired number of sockets, your only option to turn them into runeword bases is to use Larzuk's quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_208_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Horadric cube recipes for socketing items **do not** work with superior items!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Minor bug when depositing gold in stash</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Has anyone else experienced/noticed this bug: when you are close to the max amount of gold in your stash, and you try to top it up, nothing happens?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To give an example: If you have 2 454 923 gold in your stash and are carrying 60k gold, "deposit gold" should put in 45 077 coins (to a maximum of 2.5 million) and leave you holding 14 923.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At least I recall it working this way in LoD classic and the original D2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, in D2R, this doesn't happen--trying to deposit more than the remainder does nothing; it doesn't subtract the amount to fill the stash.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want to top up your gold, you'd need to do the math yourself and add the exact remaining amount.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_209_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not gamebreaking, but it is a bit annoying, especially when repairs will drain from your stash and if, like me, you don't like carrying around large amounts of gold in your inventory, because Sanctuary's a dangerous place, you know!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_210_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The OP did mention that he/she is a Summon Necro, so no bone spear (and likely no bone prison, either) unless he/she wants to respec.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_211_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is a *very* clever solution, I must say!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_211_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And they say that playing video games rots your brain, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_211_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Part of me wishes this bug had been present in LoD classic, because then I'd be able to tell my parents that Diablo II was actually making me better at maths... so they wouldn't be as salty if I were doing Meph runs instead of my precalculus homework.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Necro heads count as shields.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorceress Orbs do **not** count as staves.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Same goes for wands.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few other things to keep in mind (to avoid wasting runes) 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sceptres, warhammers, clubs (normal and spiked) mauls (normal and great), and their exceptional and elite variants aren't considered maces for formulae that state "mace" (and not also club, hammer, or sceptre) Thus, you cannot make HoTO (Heart of the Oak) in a War Sceptre.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Druid pelts and Barbarian helms are considered helms 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_212_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spears aren't polearms [http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hate to be pedantic, but Normal, NM, and Hell could be considered difficulty levels in the sense that NM and Hell feature the following additional challenges: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\-40 to base resistances on NM, and -**100** to base resistances on Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Champion and unique monsters are significantly more common on NM and Hell 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unique monsters gain an additional affix on NM and two more on Hell 4. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Guest monsters" in Act V in NM and Hell (monsters from previous acts can appear here) 5.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Virtually every monster in Hell difficulty is immune to at least one form of damage... hopefully not your character's primary form of damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fire immunity is *extremely* common in Hell difficulty, which is why pure fire Sorc builds are usually inadvisable for single player.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Experience loss upon death in NM and Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NM and Hell are a bit more than just New Game+ modes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I do concede they aren't difficulty levels in the sense of Ultraviolence and Nightmare in Doom, since you need to unlock the higher ones by beating the game on the previous ones (whereas you can just start from UV or Nightmare in Doom even if it's your first time).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, losing your merc in Travincal (or really anywhere) *isn't* inevitable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A quick teleport to a safe area will pull the merc out of combat, where he can be force-fed healing potions or rejuvs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Giving him full rejuv potions will also help keep him alive (although regular healing potions work just fine unless he is really taking a beating).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As the OP is a Sorc, he has innate access to teleport as a class skill, so he doesn't even need to switch weapons to do this!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_213_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, babysitting your merc in combat can be a bit tedious, but it is worthwhile if you rely on that mercenary for aura support (or dealing with immune/highly resistant monsters), and if you don't feel like feeding Greiz's, Ashaera's, or Tyrael's drinking habit by paying them tons of gold to resurrect your merc countless times.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_214_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That would probably help the OP more once he gets past Act III.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_214_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's highly unlikely he would have a Sol rune by this point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_214_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Getting a 4 os polearm at this point in the game may also be quite difficult.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_214_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't say that Insight makes mana potions obsolete, though--if you're too far from your merc or he got killed, you may still need some mana pots.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_214_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ditto if you got tagged by something with Mana Burn (which is bugged to wipe out *all* your mana on one hit) and need to teleport out of there post haste.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_214_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, Insight does resolve the need to quaff mana potions like crazy just to remain combat effective!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can take a guess at what is killing you--a lack of resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Council Members love to spam Hydra, which means you will be getting pelted with a lot of firebolts very fast.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since you are a Sorceress, you normally aren't fighting up close, so you *usually* could get away with suboptimal elemental resistances since most enemies won't focus fire you and you could cast spells from a safe distance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want to have an easier and better time, I suggest equipping gear that will boost your lightning and fire resistances to maximum (75%) since these are the most common elemental threats. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd also argue that lightning is more important, mostly due to Gloams and Lightning Enchanted enemies.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, consider your stat allocation--as a Sorc, you don't need dexterity--you aren't using a bow or even bopping things with your staff past Act I normal, so you don't need attack rating.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You should be fine with at most 48 strength (43 would suffice); maybe 10\~15 points in Energy, and the rest in Vitality thereafter.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having too little life is another cause of common deaths.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Against the Council (or really any tough mobs), try to lure them out one by one--don't just yolo in and try to burn them down.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The monsters' AI in this game is rather simple (and easily exploited), but one thing they are coded to do is surround you whenever possible--and that will get you killed fast.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, have you been collecting rejuvenation potions (purple ones)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If so, start cubing them into Full Rejuvenation Potions (3x in the Horadric Cube).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These will *instantly* heal 100% of your life and mana.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_215_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When going into tougher areas, save one belt column for these in case of emergency.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_216_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm sure you already know this, but you can have teleport as well even if you are nowhere near being able to make an Engima runeword.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_216_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just buy a staff with teleport charges from Ormus in Act III normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_216_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may need to shop around a bit before you get one, but it's the poor man's option before Enigma and it makes such a huge difference for just about *every* build to have access to teleport, if just for the convenient shortcuts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_217_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Guest monsters aren't always bad, though--if you got a bunch of Zakarum Zealots or Skeletons instead of Blood Lords in a particular zone, I'd consider that an improvement!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_217_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, it's a mixed bag--you could also end up with Scarab Demons (the lightning spewing bugs from Act II) or Gloams.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Glad to be of some help :) The funny thing is that cold resistance isn't *quite* as important as it may initially seem: yes, getting slowed to a crawl when you are chilled is annoying, but there aren't too many enemies that have long-range cold attacks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fire damage, however, is much more common, and against Big D himself, you won't have a good time without decent fire resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, read [this](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) for more information about the Horadric Cube--it's more than just an extra storage space or quest item!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whenever you find three rejuv potions, toss them in the cube (be sure to clear out everything else first), and transmute them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Save those full rejuvs for tough boss fights.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can and should be cubing those chipped rubies into higher grade gems.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The rubies will grant fire resistances *but only in a shield*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_218_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>An easier way to get fire resistances is to put Ral runes in your gear--or to create an Ancient's Pledge runeword shield (Ral + Ort + Tal in a **grey** shield with three sockets (if the name is blue, it cannot become a runeword!).You can typically buy a non-magic 3 os shield from Fara in Act II, although you may need to check back frequently--just exit town and re-enter it to refresh a vendor's inventory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_219_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's a very clever idea :D. Granted, I usually couldn't stand to play through all of normal without some source of teleport (and my first character wasn't a Sorc), so I just had to keep bugging Ormus until he finally had one in stock, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_220_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is true, especially if you use that staff to spam teleport across the map.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_220_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I usually use the staff of teleport sparingly--to take a shortcut here and there, for pulling my Merc out of trouble, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_220_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've found that it can cut down on *perceived* repair costs if you always top up the repairs when you return to town, rather than allowing your items to get into the 'yellow' state (i.e. when the warning icon appears on screen).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_220_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The lifetime repair costs are probably the same, but it doesn't feel as bad to pay 25k whenever you return to town several times vs. paying one 250k repair bill.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_221_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why would I pay a recurring fee for a game that *already* had a base price tag?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_221_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now if D2R were free to play with a monthly subscription fee that unlocked the full game, that would be a different story.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_221_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why are you so eager for companies to nickel and dime you even further?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_222_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One suggestion I can offer is that you *don't* need to find a 4 os Paladin shield for Spirit: remember that you can Larzuk or cube sockets into a white base that you find.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_222_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd suggest using the cube recipe (Tal + Amn + Perfect Ruby) since you probably have plenty of those runes, and if you are on Hell difficulty, just about every Paladin shield you are finding would have enough ilvl to roll 4 os.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_222_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that this formula doesn't work with *superior* shields.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_222_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, if I were you, I'd just pick up the best/most desirable non-magic/non-superior Pally shield that drops, and try socketing it in the cube.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_223_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That sounds like an interesting build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_223_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I haven't seen too many summonmancers hybridize into poison and bone skills, but your build does sound like something worth respeccing into at higher levels when you have the skill points to work with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_223_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'll have to give your build a try once I complete NM on my Bonemancer who works well enough as-is, but it would be nice to have some spooky skeletons for company, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_224_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Np\~ Just remember that that those [Horadric Cube](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) formulae for socketing items are a bit of a gamble--they are not guaranteed to give you the max number of sockets</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's the death explosions of those Undead Fetishes/Stygian Dolls that are chunking your health like that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The best thing would be to not bother with farming NM Mephisto with your current build, since those Stygian Dolls are a hard counter to melee characters However, if you absolutely must run NM Mephisto on this character (and you don't want to level another character), there are three things you can do (not necessarily in this order, of course!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stack as much %DR as possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The post-mortem explosion inflicts physical damage, so some %damage reduction could help ease the pain a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Lead them to your merc and let him kill them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Not exactly a reliable solution, given the hireling AI, but the post-mortem explosions don't seem to hurt hirelings or summoned minions that much.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Use a staff of teleport on weapon switch, and just teleport around/past them until you lose aggro.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can buy a staff with teleport charges from Ormus in Act III Normal, but pretty much any staff  amp; potion vendor on NM can sell them, in theory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't be afraid of parking your Barbarian at a certain point if you find that you just don't have the gear to progress efficiently.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_225_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can readily create another character just for farming, and use that one to find decent stuff for your double swing barb to help him progress once again.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No, you are not the only one to feel that way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm guessing you are also on the younger side--perhaps you were born long after D2 had passed its heyday?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be honest, a lot of the reason many of us love D2R and classic LoD so much is really nostalgia--those of us who grew up playing Diablo II associate it with our childhood and youth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D2R is a *quite* faithful remaster of the original game, but with all of its quirks and features that many would rightfully consider antiquated for a 2021 ARPG.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo III, for all its flaws upon launch, is a much more modern ARPG.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm somewhat in the opposite boat from you: I loved Diablo II and played it from when it first came out to when Diablo III was released.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I played Diablo I over 20 years after it was released and enjoyed it as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I played Diablo III upon launch, found it extremely boring and lacking in that Diablo-esque atmosphere and charm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D3 remains to this day the only game I have ever refunded in my life.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Opinions are like assholes--everyone has one, and they all can stink at times.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As others have suggested, check out PoE if you want a similar game to Diablo II but with more modern features.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other games you may like are Grim Dawn and maybe even Last Epoch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep in mind that the latter is still in Early Access, though, so your mileage may vary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_226_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, I don't think either Grim Dawn or Last Epoch are available on console or Switch, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_227_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It was *always* this way since the first release of LoD. It's more of a convenience thing than a balance issue, in my opinion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_227_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's also worth noting that there are no locked chests in Act IV--or at least I have never seen one in the past 20 years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_227_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apparently, theft isn't a concern in hell: it is a gated community, after all!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_227_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, you don't need keys for any character when in Act IV--you may want to buy a new set before heading to Act V, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apropos of points 1 and 4: Using mods is *not* banned **offline.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm not sure of what mods you are referring to, but the mods I use (QoL and visual mods) have caused zero issues--no warnings from Blizzard, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I've never tried playing D2R online, but as I bought this game primarily for single-player, I'm happy with how things are.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It would behove someone who plays both offline and online to remove any mods before playing online, though... That said, there are apparently a number of Korean streamers who use loot filter mods online and haven't run into issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I would not advise doing that just to remain on the safe side.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for character redesigns, again, there are mods that fix that... if you are playing offline.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm currently running a mod that more or less recreates the Assassin's original appearance (so that she no longer looks like the ugly sister of the Imperial officer from Star Wars: Squadrons wearing a burlap jumpsuit)--and again, zero issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_228_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do concede that you do have a point about the servers, and I have heard that console players have been having their own troubles (even offline), but if you are buying the game largely for single-player on the PC... well, there are worse things you could spend $40 or the equivalent on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_229_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will get another respec after completing the Den of Evil on NM difficulty, and one more on Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_229_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you use all three, you can farm Act bosses for essences that you can cube into a respec token.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_229_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The drop rate for those is pretty low, though</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few tips about runewords: This is a list of all the runewords currently in-game: [https://d2.maxroll.gg/items/runewords](https://d2.maxroll.gg/items/runewords) You can also find the rules for runewords here: [http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml) One should always keep in mind that runewords can only be made in grey items--not blue, yellow, green, or gold (magic, rare, set, or unique).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the name isn't grey, it isn't ok (for a runeword).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, note the requirements for the runeword carefully: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spears are *not* polearms 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sceptres, clubs, warhammers, and mauls don't count as maces.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorceress orbs don't count as staves 4.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wands don't count as staves 5.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Necromancer shrunken heads *are* considered shields 6.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Druid pelts, Barbarian helms, and circlets *are* considered helmets In terms of farming/progression, remember that on NM, your base resistances are decreased by -40, and on Hell, by **-100**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, as a Trapsin, you usually shouldn't be that close to the fight, but having negative resistances in Hell can be painful... especially lightning since there are a lot of long-range lightning attacks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't farm Normal except to run the Countess a few times for basic runes for runewords like Ancient's Pledge and Cows for a suitable crystal sword in which you can make a Spirit runeword.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_230_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That runeword will carry you through nearly all of NM until you can find some suitable +skills or +traps claws.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Trapsin, I'd stick with Spirit for now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The +2 skills from Spirit is quite nice to have, and the runes are easy to find.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Getting a 4 os base in Normal may be a bit tough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically any white crystal sword that drops in Act V Normal past the Arreat Plateau *should* be able to have 4 os, but your safest bet is to just get one from Normal cows as that one is guaranteed to receive 4 sockets from Larzuk's quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Later, you may want to upgrade to a Heart of the Oak (HoTO for short), but you won't be finding Vex or Pul runes before Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'd also want to have a Call to Arms (CtA) weapon on switch for buffing yourself with Battle Orders and Battle Cry, but again, all this is endgame stuff.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of armour, Stealth is a good runeword to start with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd upgrade to Smoke for the extra resists as soon as you can.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Treachery is ok, but having the chance to cast Fade overwrite your Burst of Speed can be a bit annoying--it's a better runeword for your Merc than anything.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, you should stick with the Act II merc--he is excellent for tanking and for aura support.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could replace him in NM Act II with a Holy Freeze (defensive) merc if you like for more crowd control.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And yes, you should *definitely* be using the Insight runeword on your merc--not yourself!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By using a 2h weapon, you are forgoing a lot in terms of resists and other bonuses that you could get from going dual claws (with appropriate +skill mods) or sword and board.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_231_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keeping your merc alive isn't tough--you can use teleport (buy a staff with teleport charges from Ormus in Act III; he sometimes sells them) to pull him out of trouble, and shift + potion hotkey will give potions to your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_232_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They just edit some texture files and some of the .bin files.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_232_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I haven't seen any mods that edit the .exe for this or LoD classic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_232_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most Diablo II mods (and for D2R) will have new .mpq files.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_232_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even mods that change the drop rate don't edit the .dll files--the changes would be made in the treasureclassex.txt if I'm not mistaken.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_232_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, it's generally a good idea to not run any mods when playing online.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think any of the really big overhaul mods (e.g. MedianXL, Eastern Sun) are available for D2R yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The lack of TCP/IP play has made those mod developers reluctant to work on anything for D2R, last time I checked.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, there are ways to play the game offline without connecting to [battle.net](https://battle.net), if I'm not mistaken.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It may not be a 1:1 match, but this whole situation reminds me a bit of Escape from Tarkov and the SP Tarkov mod.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically you are *not* supposed to mod Tarkov (it's explicitly forbidden to mod the files), but many people use the SP Tarkov mod (for offline play with progression) without problems.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They just create a copy of the game installation folder and run the mod from there, and run the online version from another folder.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, have you heard of anyone getting banned for using a D2R mod *offline*?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't be surprised if a similar solution would work here--but again, I haven't seen (or tried) any D2R mods that change .dll files.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are that worried about Blizzard somehow checking what you do with your offline characters, then don't use any mods.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Somehow, I imagine that Blizzard's main concern is people doing dodgy stuff **online**, like maphacks, bugged items, dupes, etc--because that was an issue with LoD classic back in the day.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_233_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The whole Diablo Clone event was inspired in part by efforts to fix the economy by clearing out all the duped SoJs, as you know!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just wondering, what do you have against teleporting?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do understand if it seems a bit silly to teleport your way through an entire zone (as many MF Sorcs do).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Eschewing the use of teleport altogether--whether that be through items with teleport charges or Enigma--seems a bit self-limiting, especially given the maze-like design of some maps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically *every* character gains access to teleport by level 24 (when you can equip a staff of teleport).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorcs just get it as an innate skill at lvl 18.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you really hate teleporting, though, your best areas to farm would be cows, Pindle, and Shenk/Eldritch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>None of these areas require you to traverse vast distances, for one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The cows *will* come to you (you don't need to go far to start the barbecue).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_234_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And all of these areas are easy to reach, with Cows potentially being the most tedious as it potentially requires a trip to Tristram to get a new Wirt's leg, and finding the Cairn Stones can be either quick or it can force you to explore most of the Stony Fields before you find those darn stones were just a bit southwest of the WP (but you went East, North, and South).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_235_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It isn't as bad as you think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_235_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For one, act bosses are immune to knockback.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_235_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, knockback on your weapon can clear some breathing room if you get surrounded by monsters, as unique packs will often try to swarm you from all sides.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At this point, you should ideally be using a Spirit runeword (Tal + Thul + Ort + Amn) in a 4 os sword, usually a crystal sword for the lower stat requirements.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For a shield, you can't go wrong with Ancient's Pledge (Ral + Ort + Tal) for extra resistances, although Rhyme (Shael + Eth) is also quite good.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Until you get to NM, you probably aren't going to come across many claws with +skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, stick with a Spirit runeword until you can get at least one claw with more +skills to your relevant abilities (e.g. +traps, + lightning sentry, +assassin skills, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>that exceeds the +skill bonuses from Spirit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That will carry you until hell... which is where you'd need to learn how to deal with frequent lightning immunes that often feel a bit arbitrary (Dark hunters are cold immune, but dark lancers are lightning immune?)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Until you can get an Infinity runeword on your merc (Ber + Mal + Ber + Ist), you'll find yourself having to choose between teleport so you can run away from lightning immune monsters (and generally get around faster), or cursing them with lower resist and slowly whittling them down. *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some* immunities (but not all) can be broken by Conviction or Lower Resist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_236_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It depends on how high the monster's resistance is, since Conviction and LR function at 1/5 effectiveness when breaking immunities (e.g. If your Conviction reduces enemy resists by 75%, it will have 15% effectiveness against an immune monster--it just needs to reduce the resistance below 100% to "break" the immunity).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some uniques are useful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some rares (yellows) are useful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, since belts, gloves, boots, and of course jewelry can't have sockets, you'll want rares or uniques for those, usually.. although some set items can be quite powerful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In addition, throwing weapons can't be socketed so the BiS for those tend to be uniques or powerful rares.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But when it comes to items that can have sockets, the best do tend to be runewords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't say that the 'hot loot' are necessarily the runeword bases themselves, although certain bases can have surprising value for a plain, unenchanted item (e.g. 4 os Monarchs do have some value to some people, as would superior 5 os Phase Blades with perfect 15% ED).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But keep in mind that many runewords also have stat rolls that can vary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, Call to Arms (CtA) can roll anywhere from 2-6 on Battle Command, 1-6 on Battle Orders, and 1-4 on Battle Cry--this will become apparent after you socket the runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A CtA with max values in each of those skills would definitely be more valuable than one with minimum rolls!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for your Trapsin, one tip I can offer is to start working on Fire Blast once you've maxed Lightning Sentry (LS) and Death Sentry.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't make the mistake that I did and exclusively focus on LS synergies (Charged Bolt Sentry, Shock Web), because being a solo, single-element player in Hell is not fun at all if you don't have an Infinity runeword on your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>20 points in Fire Blast and some +skills will give you about 1000 damage that you can spam at lightning immunes (LI), which is more than enough to help your merc take them down faster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Without this, your only recourse is to run away, or spam Mind Blast repeatedly to try to keep them stunned... the conversion chance is more of a hindrance than help, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>2.6k LS damage is good enough throughout Act I Hell--remember that you have up to 5 of these zapping at once, and your real killing factor against crowds is the Corpse Explosions from Death Sentry.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The LS is just to get the party started.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your LS damage will get better with more +skills and synergy bonuses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, don't expect a Wand of Lower Resist to reliably break most Lightning Immunities in Hell--the spell granted by the charges is too low-level to affect most of them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having this wand on switch *is* useful when fighting bosses, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_237_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whilst none of the Act bosses have immunities, they **do** have very high resistances in NM and Hell, and lowering these can help you take them down faster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oh, they definitely *are* evil.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cattle shouldn't be able to walk on their hind legs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, if you look closely, you can find some dead Rogues bound to pillars.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Hell Bovines are definitely in league with Diablo and co. My headcanon is that they were being trained as a sort of fifth column to infiltrate among normal cows before standing up on their hind legs, pulling out poleaxes and halberds, and slaughtering hapless farmers before converging on the larger cities to commit genocide and pillage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wirt was the only one who found out the secret, and no one believed him (since he was a greedy little bastard in D1 anyway).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The cows killed him in Tristram well before things went south there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He hid some notes in his peg leg, hence why you need it to open a portal to the Cows' staging grounds to prevent the Three from having the last laugh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_238_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I'd argue that you killed Baal just in time before he could have the Bovine Blitzkrieg begin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_239_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I always used to be amused whenever I saw unique monster names like Puke Rot the Dead and Star Head--especially when the former was a Corrupted Rogue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_239_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It makes me wonder what that gal must have been like to earn a demonic name like "Puke Rot the Dead."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If by "magic-based damage" you are including elemental damage, I'd strongly suggest a Orb/Firewall Sorc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, you get teleport as an innate skill; you have Static Field to whittle down dual cold/fire immunes as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, dual cold *and* fire immunes aren't anywhere as common as single elemental immunities.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Another option could be a Lightning Trapsin--you don't *really* need teleport from Engima, as you can make do with an item that has teleport charges.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, you don't need teleport at all, but it's nice to have for taking shortcuts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than merc resurrecting, recharging your teleport charges will be your only gold expenses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With a Lightning Trapsin, you can rely on Fire Blast + your merc to deal with Lightning Immunes... usually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If this doesn't work, you can just Mind Blast them till they convert and/or run away.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want pure magic damage with *very* few immunes--and don't want to need Enigma for maximum effectiveness, a Bonemancer could also work, although your primary clearing skill will be Corpse Explosion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If there aren't any corpses, things can be a bit slower, but on the upside, the number of magic-immune monsters in game can be counted on one hand.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I can only think of three: \- Wailing Beasts in Act III \- Plague Bearers in Act II \- Baal's Unravellers in Act V (summoned by Baal in the 2nd wave... but their skellies aren't magic immune ;) ) Some might argue that a Hammerdin can fill the same role as the Bonemancer--and even better, with higher damage, but due to the way that Blessed Hammer works, you generally *do* need a source of teleport to get in range.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And since Paladins in general benefit greatly from shields, this means having the teleport not on a staff, ideally.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_240_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hope this helps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_241_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, if you had fun and enjoyed the ride, you got your money's worth.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_241_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't see this as a bad thing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_241_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Every game has its end point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_241_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope that Diablo IV meets your expectations, because it seems like Big D needs some more killing even after the 4th time around :D. Those damn demons never learn... you'd think they would have gotten the hint after the third time--even gender-swapping didn't save Diablo from us, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_242_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>*Impossible*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_242_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also note that you cannot change the number of sockets on a grey item--there's no Horadric Cube formula to re-roll the sockets on a grey socketed item, unfortunately.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_242_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So that lovely,15% eth Thresher that dropped, but with three sockets instead of four... well, Charsi is always hungry.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_242_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only way to re-roll sockets is on magic weapons: 3 chipped gems or 3 flawless gems + magic weapon = socketed magic weapon with 1\~2 sockets *and* completely rerolled affixes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's a *Shard of Identify*?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, what does "Merc Slots" mean--that you can have multiple mercenaries active (and can freely choose among them), as opposed to our current system, in which hiring a new merc will overwrite the previous one?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The endless dungeon based on the Tristram Cathedral does sound interesting, but the biggest issue I can see with this is that it wouldn't be very fun if you cannot stash your loot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the endgame, your inventory is 95% charms, often with very little inventory space.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What you are looking for is primarily loot, and if, say, a Tyrael's Might drops there but you already picked up a nice Stormshield, well, that's no bueno if you cannot drop a couple charms, stash the Stormshield, then get the Tyrael's.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It goes against the spirit of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, a better design would be to have checkpoints every few levels or so--a shrine of town portal that doesn't block your return.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This would force the player to make some hard decisions *and* to choose wisely what to pick up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It would also prevent the player from cheesing tough fights by giving the boss a few whacks, TP-ing back to heal to full, then rinse and repeat until it's dead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_243_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add that levels which have been completed cannot be revisited on that run and that the checkpoint locations are random within each level, and are usually guarded by something nasty... and you have yourself a nice Diablo II rogue-lite.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_244_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It doesn't affect your summons' health.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_244_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, keep in mind that your best skill--Corpse Explosion does *not* scale in damage with increased monster health at higher /players X values.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_244_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The damage inflicted by a CE will be at most 100% of that monster's health on /players 1, even if you are on /players 8.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_244_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This doesn't make CE useless on higher player counts, but it does make it somewhat less brutally effective.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_244_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than skill point investment and +skills, the only thing that affects your summons' health is difficulty changes--they get significant boosts to their base health in NM and Hell compared to Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_244_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This makes Summonmancers actually feel much more capable in higher difficulties compared to Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hell Countess worth running?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It could just be that I have terrible luck, but I've noticed on my past few Countess runs on Hell difficulty (approx.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>20\*) I have not gotten *one* single rune above Dol--and that Dol rune was dropped by a Ghost on the way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The bloody lady herself seemed to always have a pocket full of Iths, Orts, and Tals.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even her quest drop consisted of a single Tir.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For the record, I'm playing offline on /players 1, with a level 76 Trapsin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, Hell Countess should be able to drop up to Lo, but what I find most disconcerting is that the results of these Hell Countess runs have been no better than what I'd get from doing the same number of runs on NM--and with ***considerably*** lower risk as well!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All I'm asking for are a few Kos and Lums, and maybe a Lem or two, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm curious about how everyone else's Hell Countess runs have been going, because that was my main reason to move on to Hell with my Trapsin, as opposed to sticking around in NM a bit longer to farm Baal and Mephisto for some decent kit for my other characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd like to think that my Trapsin is just the unluckiest gal this side of Kurast, though... when I completed the NM Countess quest, I didn't get a single rune drop.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, my Bonemancer got a Dol and Io from that quest, which I immediately used to make a White wand :D. Are the rune drops from Hell Countess really that skewed toward the lower end of the table?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NM Countess seemed to have the most advantageous drops out of the three, whilst not being particularly dangerous overall.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_245_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\***I know 20 runs is statistically insignificant**, but compared to what I've gotten from an equivalent number of runs in NM and even Normal, the results were much better in those difficulties!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_246_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's true.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_246_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I did get a key from her on one of those runs, so I didn't leave completely empty-handed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do have access to teleport on my Trapsin (Gnarled Staff of Teleport works fine for now), so mobility isn't an issue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for Spirit, Lore, and Ancient's Pledge, I have the runes for all those--I just wanted a Lum to make another Smoke for my Paladin, and the Lem and Ko for things like Melody (I have a Amazon parked in Act III NM).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, I was hoping for am Um to make a Crescent Moon for my Paladin as well--as something to look forward to once I get him past Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's just a bit disappointing to find that the Hell Countess doesn't (or at least hasn't) been offering anything more exciting than her NM counterpart.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I might just move on with my Trapsin and start running Hell Andariel, because at least she should drop something decent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I am working on reaching Hell with my Sorc though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_247_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I definitely appreciate the recommendation on NM cows on /players 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_248_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I envy your luck, and hope that it may continue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_248_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep running a train on that wench, mate!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sadly, you cannot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, if I recall correctly, 4 os weapons won't drop in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However... you can use that cube recipe to turn a white polearm into a 4 os one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A white poleaxe that drops in Act V Normal can receive up to 4 sockets from the cube recipe (or Larzuk's quest reward).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd use the Horadric Cube formula, however, and save Larzuk's quest reward for adding sockets to something that *must* have the maximum number, e.g. a runeword in a 6 os superior Phase Blade later down the line Keep in mind that the Cube recipe doesn't work with this on superior items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It *does* work on ethereal items, though... so consider saving an ethereal poleaxe (or even Voulge) that drops in Act IV or V. However, if you really need Insight for mana issues, I'd just make it in the first 4 os polearm base you can find.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The runes for it are relatively common, so you can always make a new one if you find a better base.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And remember that spears are not polearms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_249_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That 4 os Lance or Pike you found won't work for this recipe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_250_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Something I'm curious about (but not currently in a position to test) is if the bonus from Edge applies when it's on your merc (Act I merc, of course).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_250_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm pretty certain that it doesn't--but in the odd chance that it does, it could be a valid reason to retain an Act I merc if your build doesn't need a hireling for aura support or help killing things.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_251_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that I wrote in my original post *I know that 20 runs is statistically insignificant*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_251_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also edited my post to make it bold for emphasis, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_251_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was just curious about whether anyone else's luck on their first few runs was as bad as mine--seeing the same things you can get from NM or even Normal Countess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_251_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I'll probably keep at it for a few more runs, since these go pretty fast and they at least keep me on my toes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_251_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, I got a Wizardspike from a random mob on one of these runs, so I'm not always leaving empty handed :D</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_252_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a "bug" or feature that has been in the game since D2 classic, I think--flying enemies that die above non-passable terrain won't drop any loot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_252_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's especially annoying in the Arcane Sanctuary, but it's manageable if you reposition carefully via teleport to pull back your over-eager merc before he pokes a ghost to death over the void.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_252_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of all the quirks they carried over from the original LoD, this is one I wish they had fixed, i.e. having the loot drop at your location or at the closest edge to where the mob died.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_252_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fixing that issue won't even give unfair advantage to ranged builds either, since at least a few flying enemies also have ranged attacks (e.g. Gloams and Doom Casters in Act IV) and they love to attack you whilst floating over bottomless pits.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_253_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_253_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In addition, I can also re-roll the maps by changing difficulties.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_253_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The one I've gotten is pretty good (not too far from the WP and levels 1, 2, and 3 have very short paths to the exit).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_254_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I am not expecting high runes to drop like candy, friendo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_254_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was just a bit surprised that Hell Countess hasn't felt like an upgrade in terms of drops when compared to how NM Countess definitely seemed like an upgrade from Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_254_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know how RNG works.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_254_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I am sure that if I did 1000+ consecutive Hell Countess runs I'd have those Lems, Kos, and Ums that I'm after--or at least enough runes close to those so I can cube them up to what I want.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_255_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That idea of people only using 10% of their brain is an even more aggravating myth than the notion that it's better to wound an enemy combatant than kill him outright, or that it's illegal to use .50 BMG ammunition for anti-personnel purposes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_255_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All of these are patently false, but the 10% of brain idea is so much easier to debunk that I'm surprised that it is still kicking around.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_255_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The fact that Facebook is helping keep that silly canard alive is reason no.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_255_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>2738 why that platform is a cancer on society, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_256_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't say that any set item is "worthless garbage" as even Civerb's Cudgel could be handy for a level or 2 whilst levelling a new character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_256_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although once all your characters are past, say, level 20, I wouldn't bother picking up any green unidentified rings.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_256_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>9 times out of 10, they are Cathan's Seal, and you probably already have an Angelic Halo ring in your stash somewhere.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_256_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for uniques that are worthless trash, well, The Diggler comes to mind.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_256_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't imagine how that thing would be useful for any build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_256_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think the devs added it in as a joke.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Best/Worst Designed Areas of D2/D2R Per Act?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For something a bit different (other than griping about queues or whinging about drop rates), I was curious as to what everyone thought were the best and worst levels of each Act in Diablo II (or Diablo II Resurrected) in terms of aesthetics, gameplay, or overall feel.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This doesn't include the towns themselves.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, they are as follows (mostly in terms of aesthetics): **Act I** Best: **The Jail.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>its design feels surprisingly logical, like what one would expect a prison to look like. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I'm neither a correctional officer nor do I take illegal drugs, so I've never seen the inside of a real-life gaol or prison).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The narrow corridors and Gargoyle Traps near the exit to each level make sense, as it would be designed to funnel prisoners into narrow chokepoints and hinder escapes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runners Up: The Catacombs, Inner Cloister, and Cathedral.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Worst: **Stony Fields**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nothing is really wrong with this zone, but if I had to pick my least favourite zone of Act I, it would probably be this area, since it doesn't particularly stand out visually or aesthetically from the Cold Plains or Black Marsh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, finding the Cairn Stones can sometimes be a bit of a pain. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act II** Best: **Arcane Sanctuary.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's visually distinct from any other level in the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, it can be a bit annoying for Summonmancers without access to teleport... and mercs seem to have a hard time keeping up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runners Up: The Harem, Palace Cellar.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Worst: **Maggot Lair**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nuff said. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act III** Best: **Travincal.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oddly enough, this zone actually looked slightly better in D2 Classic than in D2R. The skulls in the Blackened Temple where the Council hang out were more disturbing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In D2 Classic, they seemed to be laughing with glee, and the skull on the left side was splattered with blood.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It makes me wonder what they were doing in there to get the blood to spray that high up... in D2R, they just look like generic skulls--the sort of thing that wouldn't be out of place in a Warhammer 40K setting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is probably my favourite zone in all of Diablo II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runners Up: Kurast zones (Lower, Bazaar, Upper); Durance of Hate (when there aren't too many Stygian Dolls) Worst: **Great Marsh**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Gloams; no actual quest objectives here; nothing to distinguish it visually from the Spider Forest and Flayer Jungle, and the same irksome jungle navigation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hopefully you have some source of teleport to speed getting across the rivers... and hopefully you don't need to go through here to reach the Flayer Jungle. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act IV** Best: Three-way tie among **Outer Steppes, Plains of Despair,  amp; City of the Damned**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_26</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These zones resemble what I imagine Hell to look like: dark, barren, scorched plains full of suffering.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_27</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They actually seem *more* hellish than the River of Flame Worst: **River of Flame**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_28</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Again, nothing wrong with this area, but it just feels a bit archetypal (Hell = fire), when compared to to the preceding zones.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_29</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's also a bit hard on the eyes late at night! **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_30</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act V** Best: **Arreat Summit.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_31</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The view is impressive, but it's a shame the remaster couldn't improve upon the visuals.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_32</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Runner Up: Glacial Trail Worst: **Frozen Tundra**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_33</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Again, nothing wrong with this area, but it feels like a copy-and-paste of Frigid Highlands and Arreat Plateau.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_34</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Overall, for me, Acts III and IV have the best-looking areas in the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_257_35</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Acts II and V are the least remarkable visually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_258_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Couldn't you technically make Venom in a three-socket Sorc Orb since the recipe just specifies "3 socket weapons" and orbs do count as weapons?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_258_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Orbs of the Jared's Stone class can get up to three sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_258_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I cannot imagine why you'd ever want to make a Venom runeword orb, and Venom itself isn't a particularly good runeword overall.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I found your guide to be quite helpful :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You've earned an upvote from me and another subscriber on YouTube.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If people don't welcome your guide, that's their loss, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, that 10% ctc Bone Prison when you are hit seems quite dangerous, as I imagine that it can potentially box you in with something nasty, e.g. an aura-enchanted (with Fanaticism or Might), extra-strong, cursed monster 0\_0.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I did notice, though, that you weren't using full rejuvs (and you didn't pick them up when they dropped).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Any particular reason for that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I personally tend to hoard full rejuv potions, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm also quite impressed by how tanky your merc is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I need to force-feed mine purple drank just to keep him alive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_259_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On a random note, has anyone ever told you that you look a bit like Mr. Scratch from Alan Wake's American Nightmare?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_260_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yep, I definitely agree with you on the mood and soundtrack in the Harem and Palace Cellar.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_260_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I really wish those zones were a bit bigger, since it's always a very short run to the Arcane Sanctuary.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_260_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, as much as I like the dark, horrific setting of the Durance of Hate, I wouldn't mind if it were made *a little bit* smaller... on a bad seed, you can end up running all over the damn place just to find the waypoint, then the stairs :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_261_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There has to be *somebody* out there who actually **likes** the Maggot Lair.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_261_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe someone who works as an exterminator for his day job, perhaps?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_262_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is either a wealthy person (equivalent to the sort who hand-rolls ciggies in 50 euro notes) or someone who was very bored.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_262_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or both... especially given that Mal runes aren't exactly common and they are needed for a lot of useful runewords like CtA. Or I hope that was done with an offline, edited character, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_263_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, I can't imagine any case in which you'd want to make the Venom runeword in any weapon--its bonuses are just bad overall and there are much cheaper runewords which provide far better stats, as well as there being far better uses for a Mal rune.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_264_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now that you mentioned that... I can't unsee it, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's even worse about those Stygian Dolls is their death explosion... especially if your merc pops one right next to you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were Mephisto, I wouldn't even bother with 99% of the other demons/undead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd just create an army of those speedy little bastards and overrun Sanctuary single-handedly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What I like about your guide is that you are using kit that is reasonable for most people to obtain through playing the game normally.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, your video has inspired me to dust off my Summonmancer and continue levelling him.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For some reason, Summon Necros in D2R initially didn't feel quite as fun to me as they did in LoD classic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, it might have been because I was much younger back then, and had a very different definition of fun.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Back then, I wouldn't have even touched a Trapsin... and now my level 77 Trapsin is my highest-level character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_265_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Offline, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_266_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely... and it makes you feel like you need a long shower afterward, and an evening off at Atma's Tavern, then the Harem to relax.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_266_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Except that the Harem's closed, and Geglash is permanently living at Atma's... and he will bore a hole into your skull with his thumb if you touch (or even breath) on his drink, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_267_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Through all these years, I never knew that it was ever possible to cheese Diablo clone like that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_267_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only time I faced him in LoD classic, I ended up spawning him in the Blood Moor... and ran away like a little bitch because I wasn't prepared for the fight, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_267_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even though it isn't possible to cheese him like you describe in D2R, I still upvoted your post for teaching me something new.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_268_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's pretty damn clever, I must say!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_268_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However... I'm guessing your preferred MF character is not a Hammerdin, or a Summonmancer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_268_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, the Maggot Lair isn't *really* that bad for most Sorc builds (assuming you aren't focusing on lightning damage), most Amazon builds, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Leapers... for some reason, I hate those damned things more than any other enemy in Diablo II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I even prefer Stygian Dolls to the leapers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not that the leapers are dangerous, but they are just annoying--and the sounds they make are even worse, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It makes killing them rewarding, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if you're an Amazon with Guided Arrow or just about any sort of Sorc build, leapers aren't annoying at all, since they can't leap far enough to dodge a guided arrow or avoid getting zapped by chain lightning, blizzard, frozen orb, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The fact that the leapers come back in Act III and Act IV though is a bit much.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd honestly rather have the buzzards.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Speaking of the buzzards, I recall hearing many years ago that you could force them to land by casting a necromancer curse on them when they were flying.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_269_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't remember if I ever actually got that to work in D2 classic, but I'm wondering if this is (or was) actually true, or was just some BS and maybe confirmation bias, i.e. a Necro casts a curse *just as* the buzzard decides to land, and he thinks that the curse forced it to land.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_270_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, Firewall is cast parallel to the direction you are facing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_270_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So if you are facing the wall (and not straight down the corridor), you should cast a firewall that stretches *down* the hall, and not across it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_270_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even so, barbecuing Coldworm the Burrower with Firewalls never gets old, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_271_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now I know what I'll be doing when my Firewall/Orb Sorc reaches Hell, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pardon the long response, but I tend to be rather verbose in my explanations, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The auras that you *really* need to watch out for are the following: 1. [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Conviction](http://classic.battle.net/images/battle/diablo2exp/images/skills/conviction01.jpg) (looks like a green circle on the floor).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Lowers your resistances as long as you stay in range.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also lowers your physical defence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Kill the main unique that has this ASAP.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It isn't shared with the minions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But this can be *extremely* deadly in an area with Gloams, because if you don't kill the thing with Conviction, you and your merc will ride the lightning... repeatedly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Might](http://classic.battle.net/images/battle/diablo2exp/images/skills/might01.jpg) (looks like a small set of narrow yellow triangles flashing in a clockwise direction).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Boosts physical damage substantially.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It *is* shared by minions... and other non-affiliated monsters in range Might + corrupted rogue archers (or any sort of ranged physical attacker) = firing squad.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will be shot at dawn... repeatedly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Kill the main unique that has this ASAP.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And with fire (if it's not fire-immune).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fanaticism](http://classic.battle.net/images/battle/diablo2exp/images/skills/fanaticism01.jpg) (looks like orange waves radiating out from the target's feet).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Think of Might... but on steroids.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Slightly less physical damage boosting, but significant bonuses to attack rating *and attack speed*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is shared with other monsters in range, too.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Kill the main unique that has this *post haste*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And nuke it from orbit, just to be sure.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fanatacism + Death Lords in Act V = run away like the Rabbit of Caerbannog has its incisors inches from your family jewels.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Except that the "rabbit" in this case is a Frenzied, unchillable, 2m tall, dual-wielding berserk minotaur who brought his entire extended family to greet you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The same holds true of Aura Enchanted Stygian Dolls in Act III... except that those are *even* scarier than the Death Lords, because at least the minotaurs don't come with the "Martyrdom" perk, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd give an honorable mention to (un)Holy Freeze--it's what Duriel uses to slow you down.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's more annoying than dangerous, especially for a Sorc since you shouldn't be that close to the monsters anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here's a link explaining what all the (offensive) auras do: [http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/skills/paladin-offense.shtml](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/skills/paladin-offense.shtml) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_26</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of curses, there are only two you really need to worry about: 1. [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_27</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Amplify Damage](http://classic.battle.net/images/battle/diablo2exp/images/skills/amplifydamage01.jpg) (looks like orange glowing haze over your head).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_28</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is a joke on Normal, but it becomes truly frightening on Hell, especially with archers... and it lasts *forever*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_29</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The duration on this is insane (I've seen it persist for close to 45 seconds), due to the monsters' high skill levels.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_30</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This will cause you to take 100% extra physical damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_31</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The best way to avoid it is to kill Cursed monsters from a safe distance ASAP, and to go back to town to remove it once the unique is dead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_32</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is the only curse you'll encounter before Act IV.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_33</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, the unique's minions can also inflict this if they hit you or your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_34</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Lower Resist](http://classic.battle.net/images/battle/diablo2exp/images/skills/lowerresist01.jpg) (looks like purple dots dancing over your head).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_35</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Only cast by Oblivion Knights in the Chaos Sanctuary... or anywhere they show up as Guest Monsters in Act V. Does what it says on the tin--lowers your resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_36</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Higher monster levels in Hell mean higher level curses, which in this case increases duration and potency.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_37</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It can take your resists into the negative if the curse is potent enough and your base resists are low enough beforehand.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_38</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A list of the rude words in the Necromancer's vocabulary: [http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/skills/necromancer-curses.shtml](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/skills/necromancer-curses.shtml) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_39</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that Lower Resist and Conviction can break monster immunities, but they function at 1/5 effectiveness.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_40</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A lvl 1 Lower resist lowers resistances by 31%, but against an immune monster, it will only take 6 off the resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_41</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the monster has 100 resistance to fire, a level 1 LR can break this immunity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_42</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the monster has 110 resistance, it will have no effect, as its resistance will still be above 100.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_43</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As you know, curses override persistent shrines, and vice versa.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_44</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So it could be a good idea to save that Shrine of Experience until you've cleared out the Cursed monster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_272_45</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And keep in mind that Corpse Explosion inflicts 50% fire and 50% physical damage, and Fire Enchanted monsters cast CE on death... so keep your distance from Cursed, Fire Enchanted uniques!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_273_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Due to the current "meta" of pumping vitality for just about every build and the bugged Mana Burn monsters that wipe out your entire mana pool *in one hit*, most people will probably never be on the receiving end of Blood Mana, since there's usually no reason why you'd want to have more mana than health.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_273_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I really hope they will fix that Mana Burn bug some day, as it makes Energy Shield a very dubious skill investment.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were you, I'd get in close (be careful, of course), and Static Field his arse until he's at 33% health (that's the minimum you can reach on NM and Hell), then rain Blizzard on him until he's dead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just watch out for the skeletons, and have your finger next to your hotkey for Teleport to get out of there if you are taking too much damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Radamant *is* cold-resistant, and with Magic Resist, he will gain another +40 Cold resistance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm not sure if that would make him Cold Immune, but even if it does, it would only be at most 80 or so cold resistance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you can get a Bone Wand of Lower Resist, even a level 1 lower resist should be enough to break his immunity (if there is one).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And if he's not immune, again, level 1 lower resist (from the wand charges) will help a lot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you check Drognan's inventory every time you return to town, he might be selling one of those wands (level 36 minimum requirement).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, if you are playing exclusively solo, offline, or SSF, you may want to consider a dual-element build as there are *a lot* of Cold Immunes in Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_274_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if you have a couple of Bers and an Ist sitting in your stash, you should be just fine!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_275_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stone Skin on a unique monster can stack with its innate physical damage resistance to result in a PI monster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_275_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've seen PI goatmen in Hell because of Stone Skin, for instance, and goatmen aren't innately PI, unlike Ghosts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_275_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thankfully, that immunity can be readily broken by Amplify Damage or potentially even Decrepify.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_276_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still... isn't the effect for completing the full set identical for every class other than for Assassins (with Natalya's set) and Necromancers (with Trang Oul's)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_276_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree with the OP (and you as well) that it would be nice if each class got something that would make them look truly unique--perhaps with these sets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_276_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, if Natalya's set looked like the D2R Natalya's armour, that would be quite nice!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_276_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, each class does have some nice visual customisation to its armour, although I did prefer the original Paladin armours (from Plate Mail and up) to the D2R version.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_276_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I miss having that shiny armour with the large moline cross on the cuirass.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_276_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The D2R rendition does look more like real-world armour, but it doesn't quite have the same appeal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_277_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Countess doesn't even drop any HRs... and in my experience (see my downvoted post on this, lol), her drops have been no better than what I could get from running her on NM, and with considerably less risk.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_277_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, a good reason to run Hell Countess is for keys, and other nice items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_277_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was lucky enough to get 2 keys, a Wizardspike, and a nice 2 os Dusk Shroud (which I made into a new Smoke for my Trapsin) from her.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_277_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've heard that Lower Kurast is "best" for high runes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_277_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I'm just looking for mid-runes to make runewords for my up-and-coming characters in NM and at the end of Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_277_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>None of my builds *really* need an Enigma, Exile, or even Grief to make it through the game, although having an Exile would be nice on my Zealadin when he reaches Hell--though I could easily respec him into a Hammerdin if necessary since I have an extra Spirit Pally shield sitting around (from when I got bored with my hammerdin and re-rolled him from scratch as a Zealer).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Indeed; I tend to do that even on SC as I generally prefer *not* to die, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even Cleansing or Fade Assassin skill don't help much.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Shaving 40% off a curse duration of almost a minute still means close to 24s of being stuck with Amplify Damage on you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for Fade, I've noticed that it seems to have no effect on curse duration unless you already had Fade active **before** you were cursed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you had Burst of Speed on, got cursed, then switched to Fade, it doesn't seem to reduce the curse duration at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, I guess ideally one should switch to Fade when encountering a Cursed unique, or just when fighting Oblivion Knights.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, both of those skills seem to reduce the duration of beneficial shrines as well--I believe this was the case in LoD classic, and I'm not sure if it's just an unresolved bug or working as intended.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In short, curses are no joke on Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_278_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even the humble Amplify Damage that every Necro has access to at level 1 becomes quite dangerous!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_279_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are definitely correct about that--each of those sets has a class-exclusive item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_279_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What I meant though was that isn't the effect you get from a full Mavina's set on your Amazon (the cosmetic aura) the same as you'd get from a full Griswold's set on your Paladin (same aura)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_280_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorry to hear that happened to you, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_280_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, as shitty as scammers are, they aren't violating the ToS or Code of Conduct in the game, technically.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_280_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They aren't hacking or cheating.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_280_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, if you did file a report on that player, nothing would happen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_280_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, if you had evidence that someone who PK-ed you was hacking or cheating in some way, then yes, you'd have a valid report to file, and action would probably be taken... in due time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_280_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope you have better luck with future trades, and will be more circumspect when trading with random players whom you don't know and have absolutely no reason whatsoever to trust any more than they have any reason to trust you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_281_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are right... that post-mortem Frost Nova can be quite nasty on Hell difficulty... especially since most folks tend to prioritise maxing out Lightning and Fire resists over cold since cold damage isn't *that* common in D2 compared to fire and lightning, and thawing potions are a cheap and healthy source of +50 cold resists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_281_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The fact that the freeze length lasts a lot longer on higher difficulties is also quite annoying as well!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_281_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you get tagged by the Frost Nova whilst cursed with Lower Resist (in the Chaos Sanctuary), or whilst there's something else with Conviction still alive, that would be painful, to say the least.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I didn't include Decrepify in my original list since my post was getting too long, and it's not quite as common a threat compared to Amplify damage... but since you mentioned, it why not? :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, the same could be said of Lower Resist (only Oblivion Knights use it). \--------------- [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Decrepify](http://classic.battle.net/images/battle/diablo2exp/images/skills/decrepify01.jpg) (looks like a blue glowing haze over your head) is really only encountered in Act IV and V from two sources\*: Oblivion Knights (the ones with two glowing hands, not the chaps with sword and orb or just swords) in the Chaos Sanctuary (and as guest monsters in Act V) and Baal in the WSK.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It will debuff your physical damage by 50%, slow down your movement and attack speed (including cast speed, I believe) by 50%, *and* cause you to take 50% more damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are caught in a bad spot by Decrepify (e.g. surrounded by a group of Venom Lords or Minions of Destruction), it may be GG for you--especially if you are playing HC.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fortunately, Decrepify is *somewhat* easy to avoid.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've noticed that Oblivion Knights preferentially tend to cast Decrepify on targets in melee range.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can use this to your advantage: get close to an OK to get him to overwrite that nasty Lower Resist with a Decrepify, which is unpleasant, but not as inherently threatening if there aren't any melee mobs within range.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, even at higher skill levels, Decrepify's duration is nowhere as long as that of Amplify Damage or LR.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For reference, lvl 20 Decrepify has a duration of 15.4s.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Lvl *4* Amp Damage beats this at 17s and Lvl **1** LR beats this at 20s.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think monsters on Hell difficulty have level 20 skills per se, but they do gain +7 to their base skill levels in Hell (and +3 on NM) compared to normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for Baal's use of Decrepify, the easiest way to avoid it is to lure his minions away from him when fighting them (e.g. pull them toward the entrance to the final chamber in the Throne of Destruction).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This can be a bit tough to do with the Unravelers in the 2nd wave, as they aren't very mobile, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, if I'm not mistaken, having a high enough IAS or FCR can more or less negate the slowing effects from Decrepify.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_282_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\*I was considering that Putrid Defilers in Act V also cast Decrepify, but I may be remembering that from the Hell Unleashed mod, rather than vanilla LoD, and I've never seen them use it in D2R. So for all intents and purposes, Decrepify is only used against you by Oblivion Knights and Baal... and PK-ing Necromancers or other characters with runewords like Lawbringer :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_283_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I like these changes you suggest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_283_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The whole point of crafting is supposed to be like gambling guaranteed rares with some known mods, but as you point out, most of those fixed mods aren't particularly great.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_283_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, the fact that there are *zero* weapon crafting recipes for bows, crossbows, or javelins means that Amazons are somewhat left out in the cold when it comes to crafting options.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_283_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Making crafted items (including weapons and armour) a viable alternative to runewords for endgame gear would really bring some much-needed diversity to the kits that people want, trade for, and use.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_284_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wait... unless there's something wrong with my eyes, the Necromancer has *always* had white hair!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_284_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or did you mean "if only the necro's hair was black instead of white..."?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It depends.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Leaf is a good runeword if you are running a build that relies on Fire skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is great starting out because it is bloody easy to make--you can get the base *and* the runes in Act I normal well before you say hi to Andariel.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Akara sells regular 2 os staves.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stealth is also liked because again, you can get the runes for it *in Act I* as well as a decent base there... although I personally tend to prefer to make Stealth in 2 os chainmail which you'd really only find in Act II (Fara sells them).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The bonuses are also quite nice, especially for casters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Steel (not Steal, heh) is a decent runeword early on because you'll probably come across the runes and a suitable base well before you even reach the Countess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Its runes (Tir + El) are truly cheaper than dirt--so if you find something better, you won't feel bad about feeding that Steel runeword weapon to Charsi.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In general, what you should look for depends on your build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are a caster, you want likely want +skills, faster cast rate, and resistances (especially fire and lightning; without these, you'll get smoked fast).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are a melee build, you'll need damage, attack rating, crushing blow (ideally), life/mana leech, and resistances (fire + lightning especially).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that in both examples, what I've stated is *not* an exhaustive list--just some of the stats you would likely desire for those build archetypes (caster or melee)!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There really isn't any "meta" for Normal difficulty, since just about any combination of skills can be good enough to defeat Normal Baal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, you can probably kill him using your normal attack (as opposed to things like Whirlwind, Zeal, Frenzy, Guided Arrow, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>if you're running a physical damage build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't recommend ignoring yellow (rare) armour in Normal... or ever, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As you know, your boots, gloves, and belt can't be socketed, so these would either need to be rares, set items, or uniques, or at worst magic items with some nice mods (like magic find and resistances).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if by "armour" you meant *body* armour, then yes, you could technically ignore rares once you have a decent runeword armour, but that would likely be well into NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And even then, your merc needs good kit, particularly with +resists, +life, and life steal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stealth isn't the greatest runeword for Mercs, in my opinion--a decent rare armour with fire and lightning resists, bonuses to life, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_285_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>is generally better starting out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Take a look at the set items here: [http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/sets/](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/sets/) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The list of valuable set items on [d2.maxroll.gg](https://d2.maxroll.gg) is helpful, but more so in the long run--a lot of those "low value" items will still be pretty damn valuable to you when levelling, and especially as a solo player!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, that "value" tier is also based on trading value, which is somewhat irrelevant if you plan to exclusively play SSF (solo self-found) or single player.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to sets, consider whether the *individual* item or the parts you have provide good enough bonuses, rather than what you'd get from the complete set.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, consider that some blue items--regardless of utility--are usually worth picking up as an easy way to earn gold.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Staves, wands, and sceptres can spawn with +skill mods at any quality level (normal, socketed, magic, rare).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Items with +skill mods tend to sell for at or close to max value at vendors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will need gold for repairs and gambling items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_286_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just don't bother trying to sell ethereal items, as these will almost always have greatly diminished value at vendors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_287_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_287_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, part of the issue with crafting is that it was also intended largely for higher-level characters, I think.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_287_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, isn't the range of mods you can get tied to your character level to some degree?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_288_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Breast Plate is best plate :D. All jokes aside, given your HP... I'm guessing this was a Hell Mephisto run?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_288_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have my sympathies for those utterly shitacular drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_288_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish you the best of luck on your subsequent runs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_288_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>May the Durance 2 WP be within a couple teleports of level 3, and may the Stygian Dolls remain locked up in Hell's cupboards (as opposed to chasing you around Chucky-style).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_289_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, that makes me wonder about the hypothetical D2 hardcore player who's also a vegan, a Crossfit fanatic, and a Harvard graduate :D. Would he/she even be able to figure out what to tell you first within 5 minutes of any conversation, lol?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_290_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oh... now you make me wish there was a level in Act IV on the scale of the Bloody Foothills--in which we would *literally* storm the gates of hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_290_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Accompanied by both mortal soldiers and archangels... although if the archangels are as useless as the Barbarian NPCs in the Bloody Foothills, it's no wonder that Tyrael is getting us to do his dirty work, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_290_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If Diablo IV has a finale on that scale, it would be a definite buy from me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_291_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now I have to see a screenshot of that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_291_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm really curious about what a brunette Amazon would look like, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_292_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This one works well enough: [https://d2s.dschu012.dev/#](https://d2s.dschu012.dev/#) .</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_292_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've used it for experimenting with wacky builds (since I don't have the time to level a Holy Fire, bow-using Paladin to lvl 90, for instance!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_292_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However... it is quite limited in its functionality (you can't, for instance, add gems to a character, and a lot of the lower-level uniques are not included).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_292_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, if you are working with a D2R savefile, it works just fine for editing stats, waypoints, skill points, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This made me laugh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You earn an upvote.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's just so brazen and dickish as to be hilarious... when you're not on the receiving end.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Especially since that fellow did it for a bunch of yellow and blue *normal* quality items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, 80k gold is 80k gold, and Charsi (or Larzuk, perhaps) is hungry.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was just going to ask what SLPT stood for, but I decided to save you the trouble and look it up for myself: "Shitty Life Pro Tips".</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_293_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A very apt description, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_294_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yo do raise a good point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_294_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, the strongest socketed light armour available in Normal would be a Light Plate, but you aren't going to be able to buy a non-magic one from vendors or even see one drop before Act III, I believe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_294_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, Breast Plates do have lower strength requirements than Chainmail.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_294_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With a non-magic Light plate, you'd either have to hope for a 2 os one to drop, or use the cube recipe (Tal + Thul + Perfect Topaz) on a non-superior one and hope for the best.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_294_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I tend to go with Chain Mail largely because I think it looks better on most characters than Breast Plates, but if you really wanted to get the best performance, a breast plate would be the far superior option.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_295_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Check out ([https://www.nexusmods.com/diablo2resurrected/mods/63?tab=posts](https://www.nexusmods.com/diablo2resurrected/mods/63?tab=posts) ) for something that more closely matches her original appearance and artwork.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_295_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's also another mod on the Nexus which also approximates the original starting armour look for the Amazon and Assassin (search for "Assasin and Amazon Outfit changes"\[sic\] on the website... yes the mod author misspelled "Assassin" in his mod title).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_295_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That one does have a few bugs, but they are being worked on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_295_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Combine that one with the Assassin Retouch mod and you can enjoy playing your Assassin as she was meant to be--not as the uglier sister of the Imperial officer in Star Wars Squadrons, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_295_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that even though these are purely visual mods, Blizzard's ToS seemingly forbids the use of any mods in online play.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_295_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So don't use these if you are playing online, or do so at your own risk.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_296_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No, you don't need to sit through the queue, my friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_296_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What you need to do is launch the game through the Bnet launcher once, then exit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_296_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After that, start it with Bnet closed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_296_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will see the queue pop up, but you will have an option to hit Esc to play offline.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_296_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is what worked for me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_296_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope this helps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_297_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why does teleport even need to be nerfed, though?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_297_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it were affecting PvP negatively somehow, I could see your point, but even then, I think that PvP-focused changes should not affect the majority of the game (or the majority of players) who play largely for PvM content and slaying demons, not other players.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Could you post this again, but in coherent English?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you saying that Enigma is "mandatory" for PvP, or that it is mandatory in general?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I will try to decipher your drivel and explain my point simple terms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>First, Engima is not "mandatory" (in terms of PvM)--never was, never will be.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Does it make things a lot easier?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But having an armour with 1000+ defence, 8% DR, +14 life per monster kill, level-based bonuses to strength, +2 all skills, +45% FRW, and MF bonus equivalent to your level *would still be a game-changer even if it didn't provide a +1 Teleport oskill*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The other bonuses from Engima are still damned good overall.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, if they replaced the +1 Teleport oskill on Enigma with +75 resist all, it would still be a desirable armour for just about every build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, that would make me covet it more since to me, resists are life... and I have other ways of getting access to teleport (see my second point).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Second, Enigma is not the only source of teleport for non-Sorcs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm getting by just fine in Hell with a staff of teleport.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is my clearing speed a bit slower than if I had an innate teleport that didn't rely on charges?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But am I having trouble clearing areas on my lightning Trapsin?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No, I am not.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Teleport *is* useful for nearly every class as certain zones (e.g. Maggot Lair, Act III pre-Kurast jungle maps, Kurast Sewers, Act V maps after the Bloody Foothills) can otherwise be tedious to navigate, since you will spend a lot of time running around to find specific bridges or doors past barriers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But Enigma is not the only source of teleport for non-Sorcs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My comment about PvP was not directly based on experience with it (I've never been much into the dueling scene other than some dabbling in low level duels years ago) but a general principle.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If some game element is giving certain players an unfair and uncounterable advantage over others **in a competitive environment** it bears reexamining.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't consider the majority of the content in DII (PvM) to be a "competitive environment." (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I guess you could argue that the Ladder system is if you cared about how you were ranked against other random strangers on the internet.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But to me, it isn't a competitive environment in the sense of any PvP scenario where inability to compete = you dying repeatedly and potentially being a burden on your team.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Edit: If any runewords are "mandatory" past a certain point in D2, I'd argue that Infinity or Insight would fit that mould better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't going to have a good time as a single-element Sorc without Infinity once you reach Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_298_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And caster builds tend to have mana issues until you can equip your merc with an Insight polearm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_299_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hmm, I never accused you of lying, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_299_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't speak for the others, but I noticed that 30 day message and did what I wrote--and no more issues.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_299_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, if I recall correctly, I did do one more thing I neglected to mention--when launching the game through BNet, I did hit escape to skip the queue and reach the character screen, then exited, closed BNet, and launched the game via a shortcut directly to the .exe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_299_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I should have mentioned that latter part (launching the game with a shortcut or directly from the .exe) as that's what I have been doing for a while, rather than using the default launcher.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That Gothic Plate isn't very good at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For one, it doesn't provide any resistances (other than a piddly +5% poison resist).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Second, it only has one socket, so you could at most put a single Ral or Ort in there for some more resists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, your Stealth runeword provides some very nice bonuses *if you are a caster*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+25% FCR = being able to pump out spells much faster, which entails higher overall damage output.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+25% FRW = more mobility.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that medium armours--which the Gothic Plate is considered--will slow down your character's movement slightly and have increased stamina gain compared to light armours.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And +25% FHR means that you are less likely to get stunlocked by incoming damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+15% mana regeneration is self-explanatory as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only good thing about that Gothic Plate is its high(er) defence. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That only matters if you are being attacked physically**, and as a caster, you shouldn't be anywhere near melee range 95% of the time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add that the Gothic Plate requires a whopping 70 points of strength to equip, and it's a pretty poor choice for a caster build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe you could give it to your merc if he doesn't have anything better, but even a non-magic, 3 os Splint Mail socketed with Ral, Ort, and Tal (or Ral, Ort, and a Perfect Ruby) would probably serve him better by providing resistances and even *more* life than that rare gothic plate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>TL; DR: Physical defence rating isn't a priority for caster builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Armours that require high strength investment are no bueno.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+FCR is great for casters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stealth is not so ideal for non-casters, but is still ok.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_300_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Stealth uses such cheap and common runes that you can always "upgrade" the base when you find something better since Tals and Eths are very common drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_301_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ah, but Tyson could really just be trying to offer you an Ith legit... he could be trying to scam you knowing that you may be fooled by his lisp, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_301_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And if you complained about it afterward, he'll chomp off your ear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_302_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Indeed, it would help.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_302_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just make sure that you can still clear those cows efficiently even at higher player counts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_302_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't raise the player count so high that it drastically slows down your clearing speed, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_303_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, as a Hammerdin (or any sort of Paladin) you have access to Holy Shield which can massively boost your physical defence and blocking.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_303_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add that Vigour is one of the synergies for Blessed Hammer *and* you will have at least one point in Defiance to unlock it (since Defiance is a prequisite for Vigour)... and you have many ways of boosting your physical defence as a Hammerdin if it's really suffering for some odd reason.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_303_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, considering how cheap Stealth is, if the low defence of that leather armour is really bugging the OP, he can readily remake it in a better armour (e.g. a 2 os Breast Plate, or better yet, a 2 os Light Plate) that will invariably drop somewhere along the way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_303_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, I believe you can buy that 2 os Breast Plate from Fara in Act II Normal, but I may be mistaken--I do know that she does sell 2 os non-magic Splint Mail and Chain Mail, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_304_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mage plate is definitely a good idea--very low strength reqs and since it counts as light armour, no run/walk or stamina consumption malus.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_304_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, it can only have a maximum of three sockets, so even if you Larzuk-ed a superior one, you won't run the risk of getting 4 os (By contrast, the Archon Plate can have up to 4 sockets).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_304_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, every Mage Plate from ilvl 1 can have up to three sockets, so start cubing those white mage plates (Tal + Thul + Perfect Topaz) you find and hope for the best.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_304_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, you could presumably "fix" a low quality mage plate (El + chippy) then try socketing it with the cube--even at ilvl 1, it can have up to three sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't missing anything--I didn't switch back to dual claws until the very end of Nightmare, actually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason for this is that you won't start finding claws with the +skills you want until around Act III at earliest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What you want from your claws is +skills--either +Assassin skills, +Traps, or +Lightning Sentry bonuses.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, 2x Witch-hunter's claws (+2 to Assassin skills) with +2 Lightning Sentry would outperform your Spirit runeword (and whatever shield you are using) at the expense of the resists and mana bonuses you get from the runewords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, the claws will likely have much higher strength and dexterity requirements.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Trapsin, you are essentially a caster, so there's no shame in sticking with Spirit runeword for even longer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will get one more free respec in Hell, but I'd save that largely as astat respec just in case you do find any claws with more +skills that you need, especially if your strength and dex are too low.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since I don't have an Enigma on my Trapsin, I ended up raising my strength and dex to 80 base apiece--definitely not ideal, but with 1.1k life and max lightning and fire resists, I don't feel *particularly* squishy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if you're playing HC, you'd probably want to do things differently!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to claws, I wouldn't go for anything higher than Greater Talons--these exceptional-tier katars can spawn the +skills you need (even as white items), and require only 79 strength and dex to equip.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, your endgame claws might actually be 2 blue (magic) claws with +3 traps, +3 LS, and +3 DS!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can technically buy those from Anya in Act V supposedly on NM, but definitely in Hell--so keep checking.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Before you finish NM, try to max out Fire Blast (but not at the expense of LS and DS)--you'll need this alternate damage source to deal with the abundant lightning immunes in Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Once you're done with Fire Blast, you can continue working on LS synergies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also get *very* used to making ample use of Cloak of Shadows--this will save you from getting perforated by packs of lightning-immune archers in Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I tend to open most fights with CoS before tossing out the traps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, remember that curses are much more problematic in Hell--your basic Amplify Damage from a cursed unique monster feels like it lasts forever (and Amp Damage can be **extremely** dangerous when facing ranged physical attackers).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Fade does reduce curse duration, but in my observation, it only applies if you have Fade active *before* you are cursed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_305_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are cursed, *then* activate Fade, it won't do anything other than boost your elemental resists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The good thing about Hammerdins is that you face very, very few magic immune enemies.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only ones I can recall are the Wailing Beasts in Act III, Baal-summoned Unravellers in the Throne of Destruction, and the Plague Bearers in Act II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Two out of these three are undead, which means they can be taken down with Holy Bolt... which gets massive synergy bonuses from Blessed Hammer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, since you probably already have some ample FCR and +skills, you could probably just spam Holy Bolt to take down those undead magic immunes--which leaves the Wailing Beasts as the only impediment... and they only appear in *some* of the temples in Act III.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I tried a Holy Freeze zealot once, and whilst the slow is nice, I wasn't particularly impressed by the damage output.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also had major issues with attack rating as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, since a large part of your damage output comes from the added cold damage from Holy Freeze, you'll lose a large chunk of killing power in Hell where cold immunes are *very* abundant.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, even in Act V NM, a lot of things have pretty high cold resists--which means even less damage (although Crushing Blow can help).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The physical damage Zealot (using Fanatacism) is the better option, in my opinion--but to really thrive by the time you reach Hell, you need a good weapon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also find the stat allocations for melee Paladins to be much more complex than with Hammerdins--you need strength (and often dexterity) to equip decent weapons; dex for max block... and you may have AR concerns after a certain point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Hammerdin, you don't need strength above, say, 60--any armour you'd want to use for most of the game is likely a runeword that you can make in a Light or Mage Plate, since you don't need physical defence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You only need enough dexterity for max block (and maybe not even necessarily).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And you don't have to care a fig about AR, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I re-rolled my Hammerdin as a Zealot largely because I enjoy the zeal playstyle more than that of the Hammerdin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do have a few higher level characters (a lvl 79 Trapsin in Hell, and a level 54 Sorc in NM) which I can use to farm gear for my Zealot, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Farming for gear directly with a Zealot can be tough.. unless you are specced to run Ubers, perhaps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for aiming Blessed Hammers (in case you decide to press on with your Hammerdin), here are a couple tips: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The hammer originates from your Pally's left shoulder, then circles across his front before spiraling outwards.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So try to position yourself slightly south-east of monsters to guarantee hits.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you absolutely must fight monsters coming from the bottom of the screen (and repositioning isn't an option, try to position yourself so that the monster is close to your weapon hand.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This will usually guarantee the hit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But ideally, fight monsters so that they are above you, not below you whenever possible 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Before Engima, your easiest Teleport option is a (Gnarled/Battle/War/Long) Staff of Teleport.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ormus can sell the first three variants in Act III normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_306_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd stick with a Gnarled, Battle, or Long Staff of Teleport (and not a War Staff), largely because if you are switching out the staff for some last hit MF hopes, the War Staff takes up way too much space in your stash or cube!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People just downvote for the sake of it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Perhaps they are just envious that you have the runes for Fortitude and are *still* in NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm currently in Act II Hell with my Trapsin (lvl 79)... and based on the way my Countess runs have been going, I starting to doubt if I'll ever see another rune above Hel before the end.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In short, the wench has never dropped anything better on Hell than she would have on NM or even Normal, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But my Trapsin probably just has bad luck when it comes to runes--with her, I've managed to get two zero-rune drop Countess kills... I've never seen that happen with any other character even once.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, the Hell Countess seems to have her... pockets stuffed with El and Orts whenever my Trapsin comes to visit, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I'm happy for your good success to have the runes to make a Fortitude, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope you get a good roll on the resists and that you can find an ideal base for it soon :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just remember that if you find a nice superior armour (e.g. a perfect 15% ED Archon Plate or Dusk Shroud) that doesn't already have 4 os, you can't socket it yourself--you'll need to Larzuk that thing.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_307_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Given the area levels in which those armours actually drop, it would be very unlikely for it to end up with less than three sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_308_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, a Dusk Shroud or Archon Plate would be even better, but if you need that Bone runeword *now* (and you aren't in an area where Dusk Shrouds or Archon Plates drop reliably), then I'd just go with the Mage Plate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_308_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do keep in mind that the Archon Plate requires somewhat more strength investment (103 vs. 55 for the Mage Plate), so that may influence your choice as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_308_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is needing to put 48 more points in Strength to get around 200 extra defence worth it as a caster?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_308_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's debatable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_308_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Dusk Shroud only requires about 22 extra points in Strength compared to the Mage Plate... but if aesthetics are also a factor in your choice, Necromancers look better in Mage Plates than Dusk Shrouds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_308_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, the fact that the Mage Plate can have **at most** 3 sockets means fewer chances for unwanted results with Larzuk or the cube, whilst both the Dusk Shroud and Archon Plate can roll up to 4.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is true... provided that the charm dropped from areas like WSK on Hell difficulty ;).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Otherwise, the ilvl likely won't be high enough to have a good chance of rolling +skill tab *and* a desirable affix. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, grand charms from late NM can apparently roll + skill tabs as a prefix.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, the chances of actually rolling either of those desirable affixes are damned low.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So hopefully you have a lot of perfect gems to spare and nothing else to use them for (e.g. upping uniques, crafting, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Perfect Topazes, Amethysts, Sapphires, and Rubies are also needed for [Horadric Cube recipes](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) to socket items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_309_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This can be a handy way to get nice runeword bases as opposed to using one of the three Larzuk quest rewards or hoping for an item with the required number of open sockets to drop.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, the dexterity thing is somewhat axiomatic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No kit you'd really want to use on a Summonmancer past level 6 requires dexterity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Once you get access to Corpse Explosion, the days of you mixing it up alongside your bony brigades are long past.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, that scythe you are using (Grim's Burning Dead) probably isn't the best option for your Necro in the long run.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I consider Grim's Burning Dead and Pus Spitter to be kind of non-standard options for Necros, as those weapon types are best suited to other classes!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\+3 Necromancer skills may sound nice but you're actually foregoing even *more* \+ skills and resistances that you could have enjoyed with a sword and board (or rod and gob) setup.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could be using a wand with +2 Necromancer Summoning Skills and +2 Raise Skeleton, and a shrunken head with +2 Raise Skeleton for *more* bonuses than you get from that scythe--and the option of extra resists from perfect diamonds in the shrunken head.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or perhaps you could be using a white shrunken head with +3 Raise Skeleton and turn it into a Rhyme or Splendour runeword for more bonuses (and +1 all skills in the latter) Yes, you do need resists as a Summonmancer--especially lightning.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Otherwise, Burning Souls in Act IV will make you ride the lightning--especially in coordination with Oblivion Knights and Lower Resist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And even the Gloams in Act III will ruin your day if your resistances are poor.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For a summon Necro by level 55, I'd have base dexterity (no points invested), maybe 60 strength (enough to wear a plated belt), about 20 points invested in energy, and everything else in vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This will enable me to wear a Stealth runeword light plate, Spirit runeword crystal sword, Ancient's Pledge runeword kite shield (if resistances are a concern, otherwise I'd be using the best shrunken head I find), and a Lore runeword crown (because crowns look great on Necros).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only things that would require more strength are an Archon Plate (103 strength) and a Spirit runeword monarch (156 strength).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only reason I would consider investing in dex as a Summon Necro is *maybe* to approach max block with a Homunculus (unique shrunken head which has an absurdly high block chance for its item type).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_310_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But even that isn't really necessary in most cases.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Considering that nearly everything looks homemade, you both did very impressive job!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those costumes speak of some real talent especially since it seems that you made them yourself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm still wondering what sort of roll was on that tube that Deckard is using as his staff, though, as I've never seen a spool that long.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You two make me long for the days of glory... when I actually gave a shit about Halloween, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe in a couple years' time I'll go as a Paladin--I even look like the original Paladin, but with spectacles.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So I'll either need to wear contacts (which is something I've never done in my life), go as the only Paladin in history wearing specs, or just go blind and hope that Akarat will guide my steps, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, I've always wanted an excuse to wear a crown helm, or to have one custom-made; I've been in love with that sort of helm since 2000.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have a set of plate armour (I got it as a display item) that looks pretty close to a Field Plate in-game... but I'd need to get that Crown Helm custom-made somewhere.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unlike you and your mate, I don't have the time, patience, or talent to make anything on my own.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_311_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And if I tried to make my own Crown, it would probably end up looking somewhere between something you'd see a bandit in Mad Max wearing and something that wouldn't look out of place on a Cenobite.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_312_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think you mean "ethereal," because eth items are anything but eternal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_312_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, they can be considered *quite* transient... unless you put them on your merc, that is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_312_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If that Monarch has 4 os, you could technically make a Spirit in it and use it for yourself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_312_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The runes for Spirit are dirt cheap and common, and since you probably aren't a melee build, you aren't blocking (or getting hit) that often which means minimal durability loss on your shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_312_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time your ethereal spirit shield breaks, you will likely have found a normal 4 os Monarch (or a white one you can socket with 4 os).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_312_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spirit itself doesn't convey indestructible or durability repair, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are lvl 55, this means you are in NM, right?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If so, you will start seeing 4 os Crystal swords drop--you can use one of those to make a Spirit sword which is much better than the Scythe in many ways.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will lose +1 Necromancer skills, but you'll gain a lot more utility with the Spirit runeword.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>4 os weapons don't drop in Normal... although you can socket a crystal sword that drops in Act V to have 4 os.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the offhand, pick up and examine every shrunken head that drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are looking for heads with +skills to your relevant skills (e.g. raise skeleton, skeleton mastery).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want a wand, check the vendors--they tend to sell good ones with +skill tab for Necromancers and +specific skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that the best items in game are often runewords--and this means finding a good base.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If given the choice between an Enigma runeword Archon Plate and a Templar's Might, I'd choose the former, as it would be much more useful to all of my characters than the latter. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_313_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NB: I'm playing offline, so the trade value of Templar's Might is irrelevant to me, lel)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_314_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nice one.. you must have invested a lot in Dexterity to carve that pumpkin so well :D. Enjoy your Halloween and stay safe out there :)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_315_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Both of those runewords involve very cheap and common runes, so the base doesn't matter that much--just use whatever you have available.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_315_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, as a general rule of thumb, for runewords, you ideally want to use the lowest attribute requirement bases.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_315_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't usually make Ancient's Pledge in a Tower Shield as that requires 76 strength... but if your character *already* has 76 strength and you have the runes to spare, why not?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_315_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will get free Tal, Ort, and Ral runes threefold just by playing through the game (for completing the Rescue on Mt. Arreat) quest, so you don't lose anything by making a new Ancient's Pledge when you have a better base.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ah, CoS is a one-point wonder... it will save your pasty arse against archers, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, you shouldn't ever need to engage in melee combat as a Trapsin--your AR isn't good enough to really hit anything.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I tend to go with Fire Blast on left mouse, and actual traps on right.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your merc with Insight will solve almost any mana issues :D. NM Anya *might* sell the claws you are looking for, but if she doesn't, don't worry--that Spirit sword will serve you well for a long time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only reason I upgraded was because NM Diablo dropped Bartuc's Cut-Throat, and Jamella also happened to sell a Witch-Hunter's Scissors Katar (+2 to Assassin skills).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep checking those vendors, and remember to get some MF gear, but not so much that it has a detrimental effect on your kill speed, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With MF, remember that your merc's MF only matters if he lands the killing blow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At lvl 48, you should gain decent experience in Act I NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Immunities are rather rare in NM (at least the ones that should concern you).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At this point, I'd finish DS, then work on another synergy for LS.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Use Fire Blast to help whittle down mobs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since your LS should be inflicting at least 1k damage per shot, you'll tear through NM like a bear on crack, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If resists ever become an issue, consider making a Smoke runeword armour (Nef + Lum).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's what I'm using on my lvl 80 Trapsin in Act III Hell, and so far, it's working decently.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And since the runes for Insight are relatively common, look for an ethereal, exceptional polearm for your Merc to upgrade his weapon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In Act II, it may behove you to switch to a Holy Freeze merc (Defensive) for extra crowd control.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_316_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Good luck, and have fun!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_317_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is a useful tip.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_317_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I lost my cube due to a game crash... and had to go back to Normal to recover a new one (since I hadn't reached Act II NM on my Paladin by that point).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_317_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My issue was on PC, so we of the "PC master race" aren't immune either, eheh!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_317_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That sucks that you had reached Hell and lost your cube then, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_317_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope that they fix this bug soon!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_318_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Aye, I've noticed that as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_318_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Usually, reloading the page seems to fix the issue... but I'm not sure of what's going on with the Arreat Summit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_318_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, it's been my preferred go-to resource for D2 information for years now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are managing to kill things at a decent rate (and aren't getting hammered), I'd just continue onward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did you invest heavily in Lightning Sentry, Shock Web, or Charged Bolt Sentry?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Trapsin, Lightning Sentry and Death Sentry will be your primary skills... and all of the Lightning traps synergize LS, so you aren't doing too badly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, by Hell, you probably would want to max Fire Blast just to deal with Lightning Immunes (which are quite common).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason why most guides suggest going with fire before lightning is that the fire traps scale *a bit* better with skill investment early on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I think you should be fine.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that as a Trapsin, you are essentially a caster, so having +skills (overall, or to your relevant skills, i.e. LS  amp; DS) is vital for your kit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Resistances (especially fire and lightning) are also quite important.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't need physical damage from your gear as you aren't going to be hitting anything with your claws (or other weapons) past the single-digit levels.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_319_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can't go wrong with a Spirit runeword sword and Insight on your merc, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_320_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep in mind that your summons get a notable boost to life on NM and Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_320_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Normal Diablo is rough for summonmancers... but it gets a lot better from there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_320_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In addition, remember that speed is life in D2, and slowing effects are brutal... for you and the enemy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_320_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Clay golem + decrepify = slowing any target to a crawl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_320_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With Iron Golems, be careful about the desummon bug if you get too far from them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_320_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Buy a staff with teleport charges from Ormus in Act III normal to help manage your army better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You're talking about D2R (and not Diablo III)?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>No, you aren't an idiot at all, friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wands, staves, and sorc orbs in this game *don't* offer ranged auto-attacks like they do in some other ARPGs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason why you use one is for the bonuses that they provide to your skills, cast rate, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, there are some very combat-oriented staves (e.g. the unique Ribcracker Quarterstaff) which are *not* meant as caster weapons... although I'm sure there's a Swole-ress (often an accidental creation after a botched respec) or two out there who could give Friar Tuck a run for his money with one of those, as Enchant **does** boost your attack rating, eheh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Necro, though, you won't be bonking demons on the head with your wand past level 6 at latest--by that point, you should have enough summons and a merc to kill things whilst you stand back, turn corpses into IEDs (Corpse Explosion), and cheer them on with rude words (Curses like Amplify Damage, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is the way as a Summon Necro, because you really aren't suited for melee combat... at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, there are late-game melee builds for Sorcs that **can** focus on melee (e.g. the [Werebear Sorceress build](https://d2.maxroll.gg/guides/werebear-sorceress)).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But that requires some very expensive, rare, and specialised gear, such as at Jah, Ber, and Ist runes (at least one of each).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It can inflict crazy amounts of damage, due to the fact that the Holy Shock aura you get from your "Dream" runeword helm *is* a lightning skill... and it thus benefits from Lightning Mastery, eheh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I can tell, there isn't anything similar for high-level Necromancers, sadly--not even Poison Dagger scales that well and it's a single-target skill to boot -\_-. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_321_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, if Poison Dagger worked a bit like Plague Javelin, it could be more viable, I think).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hmm... I don't think Diablo was ever meant to represent *the* devil (i.e. satan or lucifer) in the literal sense.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He is a demon and a powerful one, but unless I'm mistaken, he wasn't necessarily the ruler of hell itself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, think about it--how can the devil be *killed* by a mortal?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo is Spanish for "devil," but keep in mind that even in the Bible various lesser demons are referred to as "devils" (in the plural), such as the evil spirits infesting the man who gave his name as Legion (Matt.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>V: 1-13), and the other unnamed evil entities possessing various people whom Jesus and His disciples encounter.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, the religion in the Diablo world has trappings *similar* to that of real-world Christianity, but it isn't a 1:1 match.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For one, if I recall correctly, none of the characters ever mention God or Jesus directly in Diablo I. Moreover, people even in the world of Diablo I were quite tolerant of magic and mages... Christianity in the real world has **always** frowned upon those who claim to possess magical powers, as you are well aware. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Something-something Salem Witch Trials, Malleus Maleficarum, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, I think the direction that Diablo II took was intended from the beginning--the ending cinematic of Diablo has the hero jamming Diablo's soulstone into his/her forehead, thus setting up the sequel.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_322_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If any game took a stark direction away from the fantasy world-building, it was Diablo III--the very atmosphere of that world has little in common with that of the previous games, and not just because of the art direction (there were various other questionable retcons).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wouldn't Dracul's procced life tap work against skellies?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your tip 1 is what I use with my Fury Druid (Fury on left click, Feral Rage on right).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, the way you put that "let Fury be your left click" sounds like something a Magos of the Adeptus Mechanicus would say :D. Gave you an upvote for making me chuckle after a long day at work, and also for the excellent advice--I'll need to consider this when my Fury Druid *eventually* reaches Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm a bit concerned about how I'll fare with far worse kit than the OP has, though (no Angelic ammy, no runes for Oath, just a regular Ribcracker, Rockstopper, and Smoke armour along with some assorted rares).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm already starting to worry about attack rating and physical defence a bit in Act I NM--I don't have trouble killing things or surviving on /players 8 so far, but I do worry it will only get harder going forward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One other tip I can have is to consider putting Werewolf on a hotkey *outside* your normal skill rotation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By lvl 80, you probably have a maxxed Lycanthropy, which will mean a long duration so you don't need to transform every minute.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't be like me and have Werewolf on F1, and accidentally transform *out* of form in the middle of a fight, lol. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm probably going to move it to F8 or F9).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, I've been thinking about the ideal stat allocation with Fury Druids.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_323_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Many potentially desirable weapons for this build require *a lot* of strength... which means less available for Vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Interesting, I didn't know that!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I award you an upvote for teaching me something new today.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, I ended up playing Diablo I *years* after it had been released (via the GoG edition)--and after I had played Diablo II for years.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I actually enjoyed some aspects of D1 more than D2, since it seemed like Blizzard put a much greater emphasis on story and atmosphere in D1 vs. gameplay loop in D2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The cathedral actually felt intimidating in D1, whilst none of the areas I visited in D2 really had that same sense of dread... even though I was around 13 when I first played D2, and 31 when I finally played through D1. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only area in D2 that really came close was Act IV, largely because the blasted, scorched Outer Steppes matched my impression of hell exactly.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_324_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Both are great games in their own right, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_325_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, Life Tap works on everything, regardless of drain effectiveness.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_325_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's part of the reason why a source of life tap is so vital for people running Ubers, since Uber Diablo, Baal, and Mephisto have zero drain effectiveness (regular life leech won't work on them).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_325_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, I greatly appreciate your tip about aiming for the str/dex requirements for a Thresher--152 base strength and 118 base dex (assuming no other bonuses, and non-ethereal) isn't an insane amount.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_325_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That really gives me a specific benchmark to work toward with my Druid :D. I did already pick up a Fal rune somewhere, and maybe I'll get lucky eventually and the Countess will drop a Ko rune for my Trapsin (who's currently lvl 80 in Hell), or I'll pick up one elsewhere.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_325_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The requirements -20% from the Hel rune makes it even more accessible :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_326_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How do all of you manage to carve those pumpkins so impressively?!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_326_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't doing that with just a standard cake knife, I'm guessing... Is there a class where you can learn how to do this?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_326_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Because this, and just about every other pumpkin carving I have seen on this sub are some serious works of art.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_326_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, that Dark Wanderer looks *exactly* like the one on the original D2 box art.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_326_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Truly outstanding work!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of resistances, if you can only pick two, make sure you have max lightning and fire resists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cold resistance is nice to have, but there aren't too many long-range cold attacks (just stay far away from Cold Enchanted mobs when they pop).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The same goes for poison.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that the duration of consecutive antidote and thawing potions stack, so you can just chug a bunch of them before dealing with something you know will output a lot of cold or poison (e.g. Andariel with her long-range poison bolts and sprays).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, if you just plan to use this blizzard Sorc to farm Mephisto, you'll need to just teleport past anything cold immune as you make your way through the quests to Act III.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If something you absolutely must kill is Cold Immune (e.g. Corpsefire), hopefully he isn't lightning immune, so you can just static him down to around health, then have your merc finish the job.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I wouldn't run a single-element Sorc solo in Hell because of the abundance of elemental immunities.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A dual-element Sorc (e.g. Orbwall or Meteorb) wouldn't have as many issues, but this comes at the expense of overall damage output which means slower clearing speed compared to a Blizzard sorc... against things that aren't immune, that is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also be very careful around packs of archers--they can and will perforate you *fast*, especially if one of them is a cursed unique.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd usually go back to town to remove the curse, because Amplify Damage feels like it lasts forever on Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_327_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, remember not to neglect your merc's resists and gear--you'll rely on him a lot to help deal with things that you must kill and that are immune.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_328_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One thing that really turns me off to Iron Golem is the despawn bug--get too far away from your minions under certain conditions, and it will just vanish.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_328_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you use a more expensive item (e.g. a Beast runeword) to create that Iron Golem and it randomly despawns... That's why I wouldn't use anything I couldn't replace to create an Iron Golem.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_328_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, if it was the case that the item *wasn't* consumed upon golem creation, then it would be worth the skill investment.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_328_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course if you have a reliable source of teleport, that *should* solve any despawn/desummon woes, since your golem will always be with you as you telestomp enemies, like any good summonmancer would.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sounds like you are doing well, then!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With Insight on your merc, you shouldn't really need mana potions very much.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I still carry one column of 'em on caster builds for three reasons: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If something with Mana Burn touches me, it will delete all my mana in an instant. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's an old bug from LoD classic that was **never** fixed).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sometimes, I may need that mana to deal with the situation fast.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If my merc dies, and I need to finish the fight alone, mana potions are vital.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I switch to my MF kit (Gull dagger + Rhyme shield), my mana pool will be miniscule... since most of my mana bonuses come from my main weapon set.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having mana potions is helpful if I need to throw a few more traps/spells/whatnot to finish the target Also, in terms of potions, Full Rejuvs are your panic button, but a lot of time, you may want them for your Merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In Hell, he is vital to help deal with lightning immunes, and you want to keep him alive as much as possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that you can heal your merc by shift+potion hotkey.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Rejuvs of any sort will heal him instantly; regular health pots will take a bit of time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I ended up with so many full rejuvenation potions that I use them exclusively on my Trapsin--I'm trying to empty the stash, but enemies keep dropping more, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's normal for you to bypass a lot of loot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I only pick up the random blues (mostly wands, sceptres, and staves) to vendor them for gold (which I then spend on trying to gamble an Angelic Wings amulet or a +3 LS claw).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But in terms of upgrades for your actual kit, I'd advise looking for the following stats on your belt/gloves/boots: \+Resistances (especially fire and lightning) \+Magic find \+Life (because you can never have enough) \+Faster run/walk (on boots) \+IAS (increased attack speed) As for runes, I'm frankly surprised you haven't seen a Nef rune by now.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are *very* common in Normal and even NM!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, remember that you can [transmute](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) lower runes into higher ones--so turn that growing pile of Els, Elds, and Tirs into something you need.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, I would pick up and identify all charms you find--some of them *might* have some useful stats (like +1 to trap skills on Grand Charms) or +resists, but a lot of them will generally be rubbish.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I didn't find any significant weapon upgrades until Act IV NM (Bartuc's Cut-throat from Diablo), but you could run NM Mephisto a bit to see if he drops anything good.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just be *very* careful in the Durance of Hate, though--those Stygian Dolls got a **significant** buff to their post-mortem explosions on NM, and they are fast AF. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are even worse on Hell.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If your merc or your traps kill one near you, it can shave off over a third of your health.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One additional point--the speed at which you toss out Lightning Sentries is based on IAS, not casting speed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I believe this also holds true for Fire Blast as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>IAS + FRW on your kit can make Fade a more desirable option compared to BoS (Fade is also safer to use).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_329_26</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that Fade will also reduce shrine durations.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_330_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've heard a lot of people claim that Bowazons are not in a good place compared to classic LoD. My own experience with a Bowazon in D2R also felt quite underwhelming compared to LoD (1.10 version).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_330_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I am curious, though as to exactly *what* has changed to make Bowazons feel so lackluster?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_330_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know that Guided Arrow will no longer loop around to pierce targets again, but there seem to be other, subtle things that feel a bit off compared to what I remember from LoD 1.10.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_330_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know I could just look up the patch notes since then, but I'd appreciate any insights that all of you could offer!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those are some odd bugs you describe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never tried using a Prayer merc past Act II NM (I always replace him with a Might or Holy Freeze Merc asap and stick with that into Hell), but in Normal and early NM at least, the life regen seems to work fine for both me and the merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Did you hire your Prayer merc in Normal or Hell difficulty?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or did you bring that same merc from Normal, through NM, and to Hell difficulty?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for your merc taking increased damage with your trapsin vs. your hammerdin or light sorc... part of me wonders if that could be influenced slightly by monster targetting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At least with your Hammerdin, you are usually up close and personal with monsters, whereas your trapsin is generally going to be farther back--relying on the merc to take all the heat.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, your lightning sorc would *also* be hanging back and relying on your merc to take aggro, so that that couldn't be it alone--unless your lightning sorc is killing things so much faster than your trapsin that your merc isn't getting his armour scratched!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, are you using a Prayer merc on **all** three characters?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do all those mercs have the same exact armour, helmet (including runeword/unique/set item rolls) etc?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_331_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I apologise if this sounds like a stupid question, but to me, "Infinity setup" implies the polearm, not necessarily the armour and helmet!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I feel your pain, mate, but that's HC for you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, in the original Diablo II manual, they even included a disclaimer warning that they would *never* restore a deceased hardcore character no matter what it was that caused its death: *acts of God, power outages, your little sister... la la la la, we're not listening.*</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Things haven't changed in the last 20 years in that regard.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>With Hardcore, you take the risk that you **may** die bullshit deaths due to things entirely beyond your control and lose your character and all his/her items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hate to be 'that guy,' but if you aren't prepared to deal with that, don't play HC--especially not on a game that has notoriously poor server performance at the given moment. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or stick to HC offline, where you don't need to deal with server shenanigans and can play the game like a very lengthy rogue-like.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish you best of luck on your next run, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One tip I can give you, though, is that when popping the last seal, stay completely out of sight of the pentagram (i.e. stay near that seal until Big D has delivered his line).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't need to see him spawning (there's no special cinematic effect--he just... appears).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_332_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can then approach him at your convenience and lure him off the pentagram to have more room to manoeuvre during the fight.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Like I said, I sympathise with you, friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It does suck and it is indeed a bullshit death that your Paladin suffered.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if you had hung back near the seal, the same thing could have happened when you were approaching Diablo--a freeze *just* as he decides to give you a double helping of the ol' lightning hose... and the game would register his hits, but not your movement away from the sparky snake.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nevertheless, deaths due to server lag have *always* been part of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In an ideal world, this sort of nonsense wouldn't happen and the **only** reasons you'd die as a HC character would be your own mistakes (i.e. taking too many risks or biting off more than you can chew).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But we don't live in an ideal world.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, we can hope that they will improve the servers to make that sort of thing *a bit* less common.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_333_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Combined with the weird issues people have had with rollbacks and losing items, I do salute you for having the patience and audacity to play hardcore online I personally don't have that sort of patience, so I don't bother with it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_334_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That makes a lot of sense: thank you for the succinct, but informative answer!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_334_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I did notice that multishot felt... anaemic in D2R, but I couldn't quite place my finger on why.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_334_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those nerfs make me very sad, as I always enjoyed the Bowazon gameplay more than that of any other Amazon build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_334_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To me, Bowazon = *the* Amazon more than Javazon builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_334_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Yes, I know that the 'zon starts with a Javelin, but I always liked bows and crossbows more.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_335_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There's one small issue I can see with this idea--trading.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_335_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do you want to make it even easier for unscrupulous and dishonest individuals to scam the unwary and/or newcomers?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_335_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can imagine that people will use this system not as an "endgame grind," but simply to copy the artwork from desirable unique items to trash-tier kit, which would make it even easier to pull off last-minute switcheroos when trading.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_335_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if the transmuted art was only client-side (other players wouldn't see it), that would avoid that issue, but it would also more or less defeat the purpose.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_335_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why 'grind' for looks if you're the only one who can see it?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_336_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Sorc's field plate armour looks fit for a queen.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_336_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pair that with a crown and even Drognan will show you some proper respect, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_336_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Looking at those images more closely, I never realised that the Necromancer apparently spends his free time doing sit-ups with Urdar skulls as weights.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_336_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The old fellow looks in better shape than the Barbarian!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_336_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm currently running a mod (or combination) of mods that restore the original appearance for the Assassin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_336_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm still hoping for a mod that will give us a bald Paladin (like the original artwork)--as a proud member of the 8-Ball/Shaved Skull Club myself, I feel a bit slighted that they gave the class that looks most like me a full head of hair, lel.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_337_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are playing offline, there are visual mods that approximate the original appearance for the Assassin and Amazon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_337_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Look on the Nexus.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_337_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm still hoping that someone will create a mod that restores the original Paladin's appearance, though, although the new Pally doesn't look *that* bad.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_337_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I don't get why they had to give him hair--monks often shave their heads.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_337_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's the beauty of PC gaming, though--if the developers take a direction you don't like with character designs, you can bet that modders will usually remedy the issue in due time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_337_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're playing on console and don't like the artwork/character designs, well, best of luck (as Greiz would say).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_338_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Exploding pots are common as dirt in Normal Act I (and in Act II).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_338_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, Exploding Shrines (encountered randomly) are a guaranteed source.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_338_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, though, rings with fire res are also quite common.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_338_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just pick up and identify every ring that drops, and you'll find one with fire res.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_338_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Alternatively, cube 3 amulets and you may get a fire res ring, or put 6 perfect gems (one of each type, excluding skulls) in the cube along with a magic amulet to get a Prismatic Amulet, which can have up to +20 resist all, which is usually more versatile than just a single Garnet ring.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_339_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On a more macabre note, the spiked pits in the Durance of Hate now have flowing blood as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_339_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I wish VV had kept the original design for the skulls in the Blackened Temple--the OG designs looked more disturbing than the generic death's heads in the remaster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_339_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Overall, though, they did a fantastic job with detailing the environments.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_340_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only issue with Holy Freeze is the chance of shattering chilled enemies on kill.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_340_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, it can be pretty handy for crowd control.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_340_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The chance isn't *that* high, but if your merc goes on a roll of shattering chilled enemies, this can be a bit irksome.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_341_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Can't unique cows spawn with Cold Enchanted?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_341_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As others have pointed out, getting chilled by a post-mortem Frost Nova can be annoying--the chill length on NM and Hell last significantly longer than in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_341_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, a thawing potion will get rid of it right away... but what are the chances of you carrying thawing pots with you all the time?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This one](https://www.nexusmods.com/diablo2resurrected/mods/49?tab=files) approximates the original starting armour (a la the LoD classic) for the Amazon and Assassin Due to Nexus mods' policies, you may need to have an account to see it, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It does currently have some bugs with some helmets and other armours for the Assassin, but the author is working on those.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, Crowns, Helms, Full Helms, Great Helms, and Circlets (as well as their exceptional and elite variants) display properly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Leather, Hardened Leather Armour, and Breastplates (as well as their exceptional and elite variants) have a bit of a visual bug with this mod, though. [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This mod](https://www.nexusmods.com/diablo2resurrected/mods/63?tab=posts) changes the Assassin's face to look closer to the original artwork, instead of VV's rather curious (and dubious) reinterpretation, which, in my opinion, looked a lot like the ugly sister of the Imperial officer from Star Wars: Squadrons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you just want a better looking Assassin, use the second mod.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want your Assassin to look like she did in LoD classic, use both.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You would need to overwrite the files in the first mod with those in the second, if I recall correctly so you can get an Assassin with the original look *and* original starting armour (i.e. no burlap jumpsuit).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd honestly be fine even if only the 2nd existed, as that face remodel matches the voice actress for the Assassin **much** more than the different character model that VV designed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_342_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But that's just my opinion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This would indeed be very nice to have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, I would be happy to have a kill counter per character, but I understand that would be difficult to implement (due to resurrecting enemies).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if there was a way to have an out-of-game tool keep track of this, that would be great!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, I sometimes wonder if there was ever any stat tracking of the total number of monsters players have killed in LoD over the last 20 years, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Again, this would be difficult (if not impossible) to calculate due to resurrecting enemies... but even if we could see the number of times that Baal has been killed by all the online LoD players since release, that would be interesting!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wonder if the number of Baal kills would come anywhere near the global population of 7.9 billion (or whatever it is).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_343_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It would be a useless statistic, but still would be amusing to note that if there have been 7.9 billion online Baal kills from LoD's initial release up through D2R, that means that on average, every man, woman, and child on this planet has completed at least one Baal run, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is correct.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For those who are curious, however, [this table](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets_by_Number) provides a list of the sockets each item can have based in ilvl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is *not* organised alphabetically (despite the description), so you may need to ctrl + F to more easily check a specific item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For reference, the columns are arranged (from left to right) ilvl 1\~25, ilvl 26-40, ilvl 40+ As I recall ilvl of an item is based on the [area level](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level) of the zone in which it drops. [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Here](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level)is a list of the area levels in Diablo II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, if you wanted a 5 os Partizan from Larzuk (for whatever reason), you'd need to give him one that has dropped at earliest in the Forgotten Tower level 4 (on NM), but to be safe, I'd only use Partizans that drop from Act II NM onwards.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_344_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you wanted a 4 os Partizan (perhaps to give your Merc a slightly better Insight runeword base), I'd make sure to use one which dropped early in Act I NM (before the Forgotten Tower).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_345_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, this makes me wonder what class/build is **most** reliant on their merc?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_345_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd say Summon Necros, with single-element Sorcs being a close second and Trapsins coming in at a distant third (since Trapsins at least have access to three damage types out of the box/town gates).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_345_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Summonmancers need *some* way to get that first corpse.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_345_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although I guess you could always go pay Pindleskin a visit to use some of his mates taking a nap to raise your army or for CE to create more corpses, unless the ability to raise skeletons or Revives from pre-placed corpses was patched out?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now, people would criticise us for our preferences... and in rather scurrilous ways to boot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But is it too much to ask for the character designs to be faithful to the original artwork?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I definitely agree that there is more work to be done, and that what these modders have had to do from scratch *should* have been in the original game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I do salute the them for their fine work thus far, given the limited resources they have to work with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apparently, with the first mod, the author had to test out just about every hex editing combo (or something) to get it to work!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just remember, of course, that you should **not** use even these texture mods when playing online... or do so at your own risk.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Blizzard's ToS has a strict "no mods" policy for online play.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_346_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They may not ban you instantly, but they do execute "ban waves," so be careful, mate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_347_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Given that the real BiS items tend to be runewords (at least in terms of weapons, offhands, and body armour), the fact that rune-finding isn't affected at all by MF does help balance things out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_347_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, MF itself is balanced by two things: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_347_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It has diminishing returns at a rapid rate (i.e. past 250\~300%, if I recall correctly) 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_347_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One often has to balance MF and survivability/combat effectiveness The only issue I can see with MF is that it greatly favours caster builds over melee (or just physical damage) builds, since casters are not dependent on weapon damage or chance to hit, whilst melee/physical damage builds are.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_347_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But the caster vs melee dichotomy runs **much** deeper than just magic find, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_348_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You do have a good point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_348_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It wouldn't be impossible to only count the first XP-granting kill, on say, a Fallen or a Burning Dead, and to discard the additional kills on the resurrected mob that don't grant experience.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_348_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was thinking that if a player killed a Fallen once, then killed it again after the Shaman resurrected it, that could throw off the count.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_348_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But since resurrected monsters don't grant XP, that could be used to track the actual kill count.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_348_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, using XP as a marker for kill counting could run into issues if a player is getting *first* kills on monsters that are way under or over his/her level, since those kills would also grant almost no experience.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_348_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you go back to the Cold Plains with a Blizz Sorc on Normal difficulty and kill Bishibosh and his lads at level 50, I don't think you'd get any experience for those kills, even though you probably would one-shot the entire lot of them before they could resurrect anything... although I could be wrong about this (maybe they may grant 1 or 2 points of experience per kill?)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, it depends.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are a Hammerdin (and I assume you are), having dual Spirit early would be ideal for extra damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The runes for Spirit are so common (you'll probably find them all on *one* NM Countess run, heh) that you don't lose anything from using that 4 os Akaran Targe for a Spirit runeword.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you find a better base with more resists (and it is **not** superior), you can transmute it with a Tal, Amn, and Perfect Ruby to potentially get a new 4 os shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, this is a gamble, since you aren't guaranteed to get 4 os with the cube recipe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if your resists are really suffering and you are getting hammered by elemental damage, then Ancient's Pledge may serve you better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I'd personally go for the Spirit shield, since you can make up the resists with other items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_349_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that if the wench in the Forgotten Tower keeps giving you Orts and Eths, you'll need a chipped Topaz to cube up to an Amn (3x Thul + 1 chipped Topaz).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to charms, resistances, +life, and +traps (you probably won't see those for some time, though) are what you want... and maybe MF (magic find) 1-4 damage charms do **not** benefit you (unless that is from a suffix, with a resistance prefix) since you aren't inflicting weapon damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the charms in your inventory just things like "Forked Large Charm of Dexterity" (+2 max damage, +3 dex) throw those things away, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They don't benefit you whatsoever!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But if you had a "Coral Large Charm of Quality" (+11% Lightning Resist, +2 max damage) that is worth holding on to for now, since that lightning resist can help keep you alive against things like Gloams and Burning Souls.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Take a look [here](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/charms.shtml) for the magic affixes that can spawn on each charm type.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that you can re-roll charm affixes with 3x perfect gems, but I do not recommend doing that except on charms that drop in late NM or Hell difficulty, as only these would have the ilvl to roll some nice stuff (like +1 to Traps).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for your merc, do you have a staff with teleport charges in your alternate weapon slot?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That can help keep him alive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If he's getting hammered, you can just teleport to a safe location, and he will port with you, which allows you to pull him out of combat, then heal him.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since you don't spend money on weapon repairs, recharging the staff shouldn't be too expensive, and having a source of teleport is always nice for taking shortcuts!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, try to get him a helm with life leech--unfortunately, the best options are either uniques like Undead Crown, Wormskull, or Vampire Gaze, or the set item Tal Rasha's Horadric Crest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>None of these are *exceedingly* rare, but they aren't the sort of things that would be dropped by every monster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And do try to make sure his resistances are close to maximum so he doesn't get shredded by elemental damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, watch out for Stygian Dolls in the Durance of Hate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those fast little bastards are *nasty*\--their post-mortem explosions can really chunk your health if your traps zap them too close to you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, if you don't have one yet, try to get a wand with Lower Resist charges (check Ormus' shop frequently).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This will help against act bosses, which can have some decent elemental resistances on NM and Hell, although they will never be completely immune to a particular element.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that if you are using a wand of lower resist, you'll need to forego your staff with teleport charges (since you want the +skills from your Spirit runeword weapon).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And remember that MF only applies if the weapon set is equipped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_350_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, if you have a [Gull dagger](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/normal/udaggers.shtml) or some other MF weapon, make sure to switch to it when the boss has only a sliver of life left for best effect.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_351_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is a good point, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_351_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can imagine that a Summonmancer and his Merc probably have a closer relationship than any of the other heroes do with their hired meatshields... and when that merc finally retires, he will tell his kids about the admirable Necromancer he accompanied all over Sanctuary--even into the burning hells.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_351_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe they will grow up realizing that Necromancers have nothing in common with the mummies in the sewers (other than the fact that they both like dank, dark places like tombs and can raise skeletons).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_351_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, it might help lessen the prejudice against Necromancers that everyone (except Alkor) seems to have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_351_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's truly a heartwarming story, if you think about it :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, unlike the One Ring, Cathan's Seal doesn't try to escape you... you try to escape Cathan's Seal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But it truly is a cursed ring just like the Ring of Power.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That makes me wonder who this Cathan fellow was, and why his (or her) ring seems to drop just about everywhere?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I bet Cathan must have been a seller of cheap knockoffs who went to hell, and continued hawking his crap there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hence why every notable demon seems to drop one at least every other run.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I bet that Andariel has at least a few boxes full of those damn things, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All jokes aside, it's a shame there are aren't any other set rings in the game (other than Cathan's and Angelic Halo), and that Cathan's Seal is so damned common.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What makes it even more curious is that the set is made for a Sorceress... but why would any Sorc even want 6% life leech at level 11?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_352_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By that point, you would probably be past bonking things on the head with your staff, and even if you are, you probably aren't doing that much damage!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_353_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The OP was asking about **shields**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_353_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Paladin shields aren't weapons or helms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_353_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The socketing transmute formulae that use Ral runes are for helmets and weapons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_353_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is listed that way on what you linked as well as on [the arreat summit](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_354_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Let Haseen go to his well-deserved retirement, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_354_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, if you're feeling extra-generous, you can let him keep one of the items that you equipped him with if you have something better in storage for his Might-using replacement (e.g. Haseen was using a random magic helm, but you have a Wormskull which NM Andy was kind enough to drop).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_354_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do that sometimes, but most often in Normal, when going from Act I to Act II--I have no use for the blue longbow socketed with a couple of chipped sapphires that Eliza or Paige was using.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_354_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It won't sell for enough gold to Fara to make it worth clearing 8 inventory spaces, and she can hang it over her hearth and tell visitors about the time she spent the fight against Andariel mostly unconscious, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are correct that Akara can sell +Fireball staves.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What the OP would need is one with *more* \+skills to Fireball (the screenshotted one has +1 to Fireball).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I believe Akara can sell up to +3 to fireball, but at least a +2 is good.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Generally, though, you won't be using the Leaf staff for *that* long, since you can potentially have a Spirit runeword **sword** by Act V Normal--crystal swords that drop in Act V from the Crystalline Passage onwards can be socketed with up to 4 os by Larzuk or Horadric Cube recipe (Ral + Amn + Perfect Amethyst).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that 4 os items will not innately drop in Normal difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Getting *two* Amn runes in Normal isn't impossible, although it may take a bit of work (i.e. plenty of Countess runs and cubing up through Thuls).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you are a Paladin, you won't get access to a Spirit runeword **shield** until Hell difficulty, as the earliest non-Paladin shields that can host 4 sockets are elite items, with the Monarch having the lowest requirements (at 156 strength).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Be careful when respeccing, though--**never** use shift+click to assign stat points.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_355_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ctrl+click is how you add 5 at a time, but if you are tired/inattentive, just do them one by one--clicking 140 times in succession rapidly and precisely isn't hard if you enjoy using semi-automatic weapons in FPS, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_356_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, at least, that would be one of the most desirable items: **especially for Countess runs**, eheh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_356_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the 50 life-drain, that wouldn't stop me from using it. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_356_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it's a weapon, I'd just switch to it right before the Countess dies. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_356_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it's a body armour, I'd just stuff a 3 os Helm with Dol runes and hire a Prayer merc in Act II (neither my Trapsin, nor Sorc, when she reaches Hell, relies on the Merc for more than tanking, Insight aura support, and dealing with immunes) Unless it had crazy stat requirements like 244 strength and 180 dex, because the Countess only wants swole eunuchs in her bathing chambers, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Three things to note about the Merc auras: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Availability is tied to the difficulty level.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In Normal (and Hell), you'll only have a choice between Blessed Aim, Prayer, and Defiance mercs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In NM, you can hire Might, Holy Freeze, and Thorns mercs 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There is often a visual bug on the Merc screen when you take a merc from one difficulty to another.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A Defiance merc hired in Normal may show Holy Freeze on his stat screen when you are playing NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>His *actual* aura, however, will still be Defiance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_357_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mercs can take a bit of time to activate their auras (they don't switch them on immediately).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few things worth noting: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't going to find an innate 4 os drop in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't need to use Larzuk's quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There is a Horadric Cube Recipe (Ral + Amn + Perfect Amethyst) that can add sockets to white items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They cannot be superior, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is a gamble, since it can roll anywhere between 1 and the max number of sockets for that item's ilvl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason to use Larzuk is if you could only find a superior crystal sword, and if you want to be guaranteed 4 sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>An item's ilvl is generally tied to the [area level](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level) in which it dropped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For a crystal sword to have 4 sockets, it must have an ilvl between 26 and 40.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The areas in Normal with levels between 26 and 40 are all of Act IV, and all of Act V between the Crystalline Passage and WSK level 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Technically, any crystal sword that drops here can be socketed to 4 os.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's how I got my Spirit runeword on my Sorc (I used a crystal sword that dropped in the Crystalline Passage... rather fitting, I think!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You aren't going to get a Spirit runeword shield until Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only non-Paladin shields which can host 4 sockets are elite items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason why people suggest Normal cows is that it has a fixed area level of 28, and very high mob density--which guarantees *a lot* of items dropped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you can spare the Amn runes, I wouldn't use Larzuk's quest reward just for creating a Spirit runeword weapon, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Save it for something else, e.g. socketing a unique item you plan to hold onto, or for something down the line that you want 6 sockets in.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_358_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Try to gather normal (not low quality or superior) crystal swords you find, and try cubing them with that formula.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_359_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The strength requirements of the runeword are entirely dependent on those of the base you use.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_359_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's just that 4 os shields are rare outside of elite items except for Paladins.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_359_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I get the feeling that this runeword was designed with Hammerdins in mind, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just wondering, how would a Stealth runeword benefit your Merc, though?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is it just for the FHR?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only mercs who would benefit from FCR are the Act III hirelings... and we don't talk about those here, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The other stats from Stealth (FRW, +6 dex, mana regen +15%, poison resist +30%) don't seem particularly beneficial to hirelings either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The poison resist might help, but even then, there are better options for resist all on your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I definitely agree that Treachery, Shaftstop, Duriel's Shell, and Smoke are all great armours for mercs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_360_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, many of those are good enough that I'd be tempted to use them on my character (I especially like Smoke runeword for the +50 resist all)!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_361_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_361_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Tal and Eth runes are indeed common enough that one wouldn't need to worry about "wasting them."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_361_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It would be all but impossible to come across a Lum rune in Normal, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_361_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For one, that would entail finding a minimum of *nine* Dol runes at the most efficient rate... I guess you could also obsessively cube up every lower rune toward Dol and do hundreds of Normal Countess runs... but the time you would spend doing that could have been better spent advancing toward NM, where you may just get a Lum from the very first Burning Dead you kill in Act II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_361_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Smoke is a great runeword, but it isn't so great as to justify lingering in Normal for days, if not weeks just to try to get it earlier.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_361_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And chances are that you won't find a decent 2 os armour in Normal that you'd really want to use it for, either--especially since that Lum rune you worked so hard to get won't have a spare for some time!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_362_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you 100% sure that you got that particular crystal sword from Normal cows, and not somewhere else?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_362_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, you said that you "gave up" looking for a 4-slot sword in normal cows, and decided to Larzuk "one of the 0 slot I found" Also, remember that 4 os items will \_not\_ drop in normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_362_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were you, I'd just use the Horadric Cube [recipes](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) for runeword bases like Spirit and save the Larzuk quest rewards for things that must have six slots.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_362_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, don't feel too bad about "wasting" your final Larzuk.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_362_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not hard to rush a character or 2 to Act V Normal, then save that quest reward for something you really need max slots on.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have a *very* odd definition of "toxic," then.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People not agreeing with your **opinions** and expressing that disagreement through downvotes is not toxic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People disagreeing with you politely and explaining why is not toxic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People hurling abuse at you just for voicing your opinions ***is*** toxic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you can show abundant evidence of the third (and your linked image does not), I don't think you can say this subreddit or any is particularly "toxic."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Take this from someone who has zero tolerance for toxicity: I deal with enough arseholes when I leave my flat that I neither have the time nor patience to engage with them in my leisure time at home as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So people don't agree with your ideas like including a transmogrify system (you've created at least two separate posts about this, if I'm not mistaken) or nerfing teleport (if this one wasn't you, I apologise).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How is that toxic for them not to share your beliefs?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are certainly entitled to your opinions just as everyone else is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are ideas I have for D2 that most people here, including you probably wouldn't agree with.;</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, I think the Hell Unleashed mod was close to the perfect Diablo II experience--better drop rates, rebalanced skills (Vengeance and Poison Dagger were actually good out of the box) but *much* more dangerous bosses, many of which had telegraphed insta-kill moves, and would regen to full health if not damaged for 15s.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But again, to repeat, everyone is entitled to their opinions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_363_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, expecting everyone to immediately and enthusiastically agree with your proposals--because to you, these ideas represent the pinnacle of ingenuity--is potentially a toxic and rather narcissistic mindset.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This sounds like an interesting approach.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, what did you do about attack rating until 40+ especially since it sounds like you didn't put more points into Zeal than were necessary to get the full five hits?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest issue I have with melee builds is that AR starts to become an issue well before caster builds run into problems with enemy resistances and immunities.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Against act bosses (which typically have very high physical defence), you can just batter them down with Smite + CB, but if you have a low hit rate against normal monsters or even some unique packs, that could be problematic.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hopefully you have an Angelic ammy and ring set.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for using Holy Freeze against physical immunes, just hope they aren't also Cold Immune (or have very high Cold Resist).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_364_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have seen dual fire and physical immunes in Hell, but I can't recall seeing a dual cold and physical immune, although I do imagine some may exist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Upvoted for excellent advice.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think it's possible to encounter a *triple* immunity (fire + cold + lightning), thankfully!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of magic immunities, the only ones in the game are: \- Wailing Beasts in Act III temples \- Plague Bearers in Act II \- Unravelers (greater mummies) summoned by Baal in the Throne of Destruction and *maybe* the Greater Mummies that can spawn in the Kurast Sewers (a worse place than even the Maggot Lair, in my opinion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's just so big, mostly empty, and tedious to navigate if you don't have access to teleport).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of these, only the Wailing Beasts may be an issue for Bonemancers and Hammerdins, since they are neither undead, nor do they always hang out with non-magic immunes (which the necro can detonate with CE).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's also worth noting that when breaking immunities with Lower Resist or Conviction, these skills function at 20% effectiveness (rounded down, I think).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So if your level 1 lower resist--commonly available as a charge on wands--does -31% to enemy resistances, against an immune enemy, it will only remove 6% of that resistance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That **will** break a Fallen's or a Ghoul's fire immunity (they both have 100 fire resist), but it will **not** be sufficient to break the immunity on an Act I zombie--those zeds have 120 cold resist, so Lower Resist, even at lvl 20, should never break their immunity (- 62% at lvl 20-- gt; approx.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>12% when breaking immunities).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'd need a minimum of level 16 Conviction to remove a Zombie's cold immunity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The short version: if a monster has above 99% elemental resistance, it will be immune.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You need to drop that resistance to below 100% to remove the immunity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a *real* shame that Cold Mastery no longer breaks immunities--even at 1/5 effectiveness.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish they would patch it back in.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_365_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd be happy with it working even at 1/8th or 1/10th effectiveness!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_366_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_366_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A 15% Scintillating Ring of... whatever would be a preferable choice, for me, at least.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_366_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Rare rings with resist all can only go up to 11%, if I'm not mistaken, and since crafted items are essentially rares (with some fixed mods), I imagine this holds true for crafted rings as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_367_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For that level, no.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_367_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time you reach level 65, you probably already have access to better sources of life leech--either from your weapons, Dracul's Grasp (5% chance to cast Life Tap on hit), or a Wand of Life Tap (with charges of lvl x Life Tap) in your alternate weapon slot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_367_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd either vendor that ring, gather two more and cube them (to hopefully get a decent amulet), or use it for crafting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_368_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just wondering, what killed your lvl 47 HC Sorc, and where did it happen?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_368_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it was NM Andariel, well, I'd go slaughter Hell Andy a few hundred more times to avenge her death, and hopefully get some more good drops, whilst wearing that Shako :D. And even if it wasn't NM Andariel which killed your Sorc, well, you should still kill Hell Andy some more to see what else she has in her pocketses... although given the way Andariel dresses, I'd rather not think too much about *where* she actually keeps those items, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_369_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Static field definitely doesn't affect drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_369_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only way it *possibly* could is indirectly--you static the target down to the minimum, and your merc lands the killing blow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_369_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And in that case, it would actually *help* you if your merc has any MF since his MF will be added to yours if he gets the killing blow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_369_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, we all have our Diablo II superstitions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_369_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mine is to never let my merc get the killing blow on the Countess--whenever he does, her rune drops seem to be even worse.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Something about using a Ribcracker on a Zealadin makes me chuckle, for some reason.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe it's because I can imagine the demons laughing at your Pally: "Look at that poor Paladin!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He spent all his gold on that shiny armour and only had enough money for a stick!"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I imagine that Baal wasn't laughing for long when you introduced that staff to his noggin at 5 times a second, with 40% CB :D As I'm also playing offline, I'll definitely give your build a try.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It might revitalise my interest in my Zealadin, who's currently parked in NM at lvl 47--not because I can't progress, but because the gameplay feels a bit... repetitive compared to my Orbwall Sorc or my Lvl 80 Trapsin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As I do share gear between characters (I even treat certain items as "loaner kit only," lol) equipping my Pally shouldn't be *too* much of a challenge, although I still have never found an Angelic ammy on any of my characters yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_370_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've always liked the slow from Holy Freeze, and I haven't used my NM respec, so I'll probably go with your build :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_371_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On Hell, you can only static **any** monster down to 50%.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_371_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The minimum on NM is 33%.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_371_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the player's Merc did the majority of the damage after the target was at 50% health, it could still land the killing blow, in theory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_371_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still I understand that the way I phrased it made it sound like you could static Hell Baal down to a sliver of health.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As others have pointed out, none of those items are really worth making runewords in--especially if you **already** have Lore, Stealth, and Ancient's Pledge among your gear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I can suggest the following: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>~~If you had a Shael instead of a Dol (and you can easily get one from NM Countess), you could make Rhyme (Shale + Eth) in that shrunken head.~~ ~~I'd only do this if it had desirable +skill mods for your Necro build, though~~ **Edit: You'd be much better served with a Splendor runeword (*****many thanks to Twkd88 for pointing this out!*****)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For that, you'd need a Lum rune, which you won't get from NM Countess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if the bloody wench is generous to you, you can get enough Dol, Hel, and Io runes in a reasonable amount of runs to transmute into a Lum.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The same tips about existing +skill bonuses apply, of course.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You want +1 all skills** ***on top*** **of existing skill bonuses provided by the head.**</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You could make an Edge runeword (Tir + Tal + Amn) in that 3 os crossbow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just transmute those Orts into a third Thul, then cube the 3x Thuls + chipped topaz into an Amn.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You wouldn't use this Edge crossbow in the field--it's just for the 15% reduction in vendor prices to save money when gambling and on repairs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, a 3 os short bow would make a **much** better base for this runeword, because it can be equipped by even a naked level 25 character without a single point in dex.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, an Edge longbow wouldn't facilitate gambling for Gulls at lvl 11, since the Amn rune pushes its equip requirement to level 25.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, you should take a look [here](https://d2.maxroll.gg/items/runewords) for a list of runewords, and note which ones look desirable (*and* feasible for you to strive towards).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't pay *too* much attention to their "recommendations" on which runewords to make, however.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may be following a build that isn't linked to one of their guides and which may work well for you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or you may have need of a non-recommended runeword for whatever reason.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But when it comes to runeword bases, it helps to keep the following in mind: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Choose the lowest requirement item that can support the number of sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A Spirit crystal sword is always preferable to a Spirit long sword for this reason.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ancient's Pledge is better made in a kite shield than a tower shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If using a wand or staff, choose an item that has +skills relevant to your build.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A +3 bone spear, +2 CE 2 os Bone Wand would be a very good find for a Bonemancer!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For melee weapons, you want the fastest, highest damaging, and easiest to equip item that can have the requisite number of open sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Read the [rules](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/runewords.shtml) for runeword bases **carefully**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sometimes, your best bet of getting a desired base is to find a white item, and socket it using the Horadric cube.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_372_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If this is a superior item, you'll need to have Larzuk do it (once per difficulty).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Wasn't there a better place you could put that soulstone shard than your forehead, Your Highness?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, humans *do* have at least one naturally occurring and much less conspicuous orifice suitable for inserting soulstones, you know.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Barring that, you could have just stuck the stone into Wirt, stuffed him in a sack, then tossed him down the deepest well you could find.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not like anyone would have missed the little bastard, and it would have been a kinder fate than what befell him.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And if Diablo decided to rear his ugly head again, at least we'd have Your Highness, Blood Raven, and the Vizjerei whose name everyone forgets to kick his scaly hide back to hell again!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As any of us adventurers who visited Tristram since Your Highness' departure can attest, Wirt now lies unburied on the Western side of town.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>His prosthetic leg has become somewhat of a macabre keepsake among our community, since when transmuted with a Tome of Town Portals, it opens a portal to a realm of pure chaos, terror, and bovine belligerence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The enraged mooing and bellowing of its most murderous, innumerable and unnatural inhabitants still haunt my dreams, but at least the riches I recovered from that bizarre demesne are some comfort.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Do not trust what the Creators told you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_373_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Secret Cow Level **does** exist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Countess is indeed a stingy wench.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My advice for doing Countess runs is to just view it as a guaranteed rune drop, *not* a guaranteed drop for that difficulty level. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And even then, it's quite possible for her to drop **zero** runes--even on the first kill for the quest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've seen it happen twice.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd be satisfied with anything from Amn upwards on NM or even Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My experience with the Hell Countess runs has been that she has *never* dropped anything I wouldn't have found on NM or even Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The highest runes I've found thus far (a Fal and a Mal) were obtained near the end of Act V NM, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>On the upside, I did manage to find a 2 os Dusk Shroud (for a new Smoke runeword for my Trapsin) and a Wizardspike on the way to the Countess... and the bloody lady herself was kind enough to give me three Keys of Terror over the course of about 50 runs thus far.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In short, run Hell Countess for Keys of Terror, and view the runes as an additional bonus.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NM Countess *is* good for runes, though, since reaching her is not anywhere as dangerous as on Hell (no immune monsters, and unique archer packs with Amplify Damage aren't quite as deadly).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree that the Angelic ring + ammy is *very* useful for a Frost zealot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, you don't really need the sabre since the ring + amulet alone gives a substantial AR bonus per level and you can use a much better weapon to add physical damage to your cold damage from Holy Freeze.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_374_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Attack rating is one of the many additional requirements that make melee builds somewhat more challenging to manage than casters... who don't need to worry about chance to hit, block rate, or even weapon damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One weapon you shouldn't sleep on is the Butcher's Pupil unique cleaver.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is fast, and hits quite hard with 35% Deadly Strike (chance to inflict double damage).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is also not an uncommon item drop and is a great weapon for clearing trash mobs against which you don't need Crushing Blow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It certainly *isn't* an endgame weapon, but it can carry you quite decently throughout the end of Normal and most of NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It can drop in late Normal and definitely early NM.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't like to use the Black runeword weapons outside of Act bosses as the knockback can be a bit annoying in open areas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act bosses, by contrast, are immune to knockback.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also hold onto Goblin Toe unique light plated boots--these also give CB.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, Blood crafted gloves can add up to another 10% CB--all this will help for dealing with bosses, whilst your Holy Freeze slows them to a crawl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_375_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can just Smite them until they are almost dead, then switch to Zeal to finish them off.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_376_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope you at least got some decent runes for your trouble, and not just a huge pile of Orts and Eths!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_377_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I fail to see how removing what is clearly a **bug** (and not a very hidden or hard one to exploit... Google documents all, as you know!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_377_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>would "coddle the casuals out there."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_377_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If anything, the fact that *you* seemingly need to rely on this exploit and that you are whinging about the 'waste' of a Perfect Topaz, Tal, and Thul runes certainly doesn't seem very hardcore at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_378_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since Blizzard North (the company that made the original Diablo, Diablo II, and Lord of Destruction expansion) is no more, I wouldn't trust the current Activision Blizzard to make any additional content for this game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_378_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The current Blizzard is the company that brought us Diablo III on launch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_378_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo III is one of the only two games I have refunded in over 25 years of gaming.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_378_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine that a group of dedicated modders could do a better job *for free* creating an expansion for D2R than Activision Blizzard could.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_379_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's a very good point--I've edited my post to acknowledge this and have given you credit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_379_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>\+1 all skills from Splendor is great to have on a Necro.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_379_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cannot be Frozen from Rhyme is not really necessary as no Necro build should be standing that to something that can freeze him... and CBF doesn't apply to your skellies, of course!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_380_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Indeed... but I have no idea of what the mage's original name was.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_380_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or if he even had one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A few things to consider: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You don't **need** to find socketed gear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can find white items without sockets, and add sockets to them using the [Horadric Cube](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/items/cube.shtml) or Larzuk's quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd save the latter for things that must have 6 sockets, or for adding sockets to uniques that you plan to hold onto, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The item's ilvl influences the [number of sockets](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets_by_Number) it can get.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can generally consider this to be tied to the [area](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets_by_Number) in which it dropped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance: you want a 4 os crystal sword for Spirit (Tal + Thul + Ort + Amn, all runes readily obtainable in Normal difficulty).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You will need to use a crystal sword that drops in Act IV, or anywhere in Act V between the Worldstone Keep level 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or in Normal cows.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are getting slaughtered by monsters in short order, it could be that your resistances are poor.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To remedy this, use an Ancient's Pledge shield in your offhand (Ral + Ort + Tal) in a 3 os shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can buy a 3 os shield from Fara in Act II.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that you get a second free respec in NM after the Den of Evil.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are no immunities there (at least not on NM), and it should actually be as easy as on Normal, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, remember that as a Trapsin, you are basically a caster... although your trap throwing speed is linked to IAS (increased attack speed), not FCR (faster cast rate) if I recall correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Max Lightning Sentry, max Death Sentry, max synergies for LS, and I'd strongly recommend maxing Fire Blast before you finish NM to deal with abundant lightning immunes in Hell *if* you are mostly playing solo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have friends to play with, then you can just focus on lightning damage, and have your friend deal with the frequent lightning immunes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Keep CoS ready to blind archers (because they *will* perforate you), and have fun.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oh, and for the sake of Natalya's pale buttcheeks, make sure to get a staff with teleport charges and a wand of lower resist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can buy the former from Ormus in Act III normal, and the latter usually from Malah in Act V Normal, although vendors in NM will likely have both.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having teleport on switch will greatly facilitate navigating tedious zones like the Kurast Sewers and jungles in Act III.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And Lower Resist, even at Lvl 1, will make your LS traps hurt Act bosses *a lot* more since most of the Act bosses have pretty hefty elemental resistances, but they will never be completely immune.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Level 1 LR *might* break some immunities in Hell, but don't count on it--most lightning-immune monsters will have at least 110 lightning resistance, and lvl1 LR won't be enough to break that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll likely use a Spirit sword as your main weapon through most of NM until you find some good claws with +skills relevant to your build (e.g. +3 traps, +3 LS). *</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_24</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Supposedly* you can buy these from Anya in Act V NM, but I have never seen her sell anything like that--most of her claws tend to be rubbish whenever I checked, but I imagine that if you are more persistent, you may find something.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_381_25</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a bit like finding a +3 bone spear wand at Drognan in Act II: it takes patience and persistence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_382_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There already are cube recipes for socketing, but unlike Larzuk's quest reward, they aren't guaranteed to roll the maximum number of sockets for the item type and ilvl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_383_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Very interesting; I never knew that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_383_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Upvoted for teaching me something new :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_383_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, it's not likely that I will put this into practice... unless it's to create my own mini overhaul mod.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_383_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But that won't happen until I no longer have to spend 12-hour days at work, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Add more skulls to it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>SKULLS FOR THE SKULL THRONE!!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All jokes aside, I'd give that helm to your merc--the crushing blow will help him take down bosses faster... if he survives.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, it isn't really good for your build at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>None of its stats would really benefit you at all as a Bonemancer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I guess you could put some resistance jewels or Ral and Ort runes (if you don't have any Um runes) to boost your resists, but there are other ways you can boost your resistances.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These include: \- Using an Ancient's Pledge shield (sadly no shrunken heads, as they can't have 3 os IIRC) in your offhand \- Smoke body armour \- Rare belt and gloves that give nice resistances... especially fire and lightning.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can get by with poor cold and poison resistances since there are very few long-range cold or poison attacks, and you have antidote and thawing pots to temporarily boost your resists against those anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even for your merc, though, a helm with life leech would probably serve him better, especially if he's using an Insight polearm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However... if you do have a point in Life Tap (ideally from your kit), then he technically doesn't need life leech--you can just life-tap whatever he's fighting to heal him quickly in addition to the usual method of force-feeding him purple drank and teleporting him with you to a safe spot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, as a Bone necro, the only things you won't be able to kill directly are: \- Plague Bearers in Act II (mostly in Ancient Tunnels) \- Wailing Beasts in Act III (mostly in the Kurast temples, but some could ostensibly show up as guest monsters in Act V) \- Baal's unravellers in wave 2 or 3, although their skellies aren't magic-immune I'm curious about how your damage output is in Hell, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One thing that made me temporarily shelve my Bonemancer is that my damage output, even by mid-NM, doesn't seem *quite* high enough to be truly effective in Hell--even with all of Bone Spear's synergies maxed, especially when compared to other builds like a Firewall/Orb Sorc (which is nowhere near the most damaging Sorc build).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_384_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I'll probably need to press on and see for myself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_385_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your wife is a lucky lady... and you are lucky to have a partner who enjoys Diablo II as much as you do... and who would give you a Ber and a Jah with no strings attached (like mowing the lawn, eheh).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_385_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>May RNG bless both of you in future cow runs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_385_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wish I could give you more than one upvote, since your post brightened what had otherwise been a truly awful day for me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are already mods which do this for D2R. Unfortunately, these aren't usable online.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, there are a couple issues I can see with this. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cold Mastery**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not difficult to get up to -150% to enemy cold resistance, and with no immunities, your 95% Cold Resist, HP-buffed monster would still be a tasty gelato to even a naked Blizzard Sorc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you would also want to rework Cold Mastery to work like Fire and Lightning Masteries (just a straight damage boost), then your proposal would make Blizzard Sorcs reign supreme *everywhere* and would be highly detrimental to build diversity. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Static Field**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If nothing is immune to lightning, *everything* and everyone can taste the static shock.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Which again means a field day for Sorcs--static anything tough down to half health, then just whittle it down with your 10k damage spells.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In addition, you can always curse it with a Wand of Lower Resist if you don't have the runes for an Infinity on your Merc to make the target ride the lightning or give it some heat!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I think the best solution would be a compromise--maybe have fewer trash mobs that have immunities, ***but*** allow uniques and champions to spawn with immunities.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do agree with your general principle--for those of us playing alone or offline, the fact that almost everything in Hell has some sort of immunity is not much fun at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_386_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But just giving them high resistances and health wouldn't quite solve the issue, although I do concede that it would make the game more enjoyable for solo players who don't have Ber and Ist runes filling up their stash, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I honestly have no idea.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>People can be... odd like that, friendo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for your issues with cubing a 4 os flail, keep in mind that the [ilvl](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets#Sockets_by_Number) of the flail makes a big difference.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are using flails that dropped in Hell, there's a good chance they could roll 5 os.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Likewise, the normal flails that Fara in Act II Normal sells likely won't be able to roll 4 os Your best bet would be to use a flail that you got in the following [areas](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level), as these all have area levels between 26 and 40: \- All of Act IV Normal \- Act V between Crystalline Passage and Worldstone Keep Level 2 \- Normal Cows (probably the best bet, due to the sheer enemy density.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just make sure to go in with low MF.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if you Larzuk a flail from those zones, you will get 4 os, but I think that's a bit of a waste of the quest reward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd usually save it for a 6 os base, or adding a socket to a unique that you plan to hold onto for a while (e.g. socketing a Shako).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_387_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I apologise if all this is old news to you, though... but I hope it may be of use for someone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_388_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd like to do that, but given how messy my desk is, and my cat who often insists on "helping" during Countess and Pit runs, it would be a very, very bad idea for me to have open flames anywhere near my computer, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_388_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, and I'd be tempted to use the flames to light my cigarettes whilst playing, which my landlady wouldn't like. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_388_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I have a smoking room on my flat's balcony instead, which works just fine.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_388_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Worse yet, I'd end up filling my keyboard with ashes, or burning myself badly when I get jumped by a group of Extra Fast, Extra Strong, Aura Enchanted Stygian Dolls in the Durance of Hate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you struggling to kill things with your Trapsin?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you are playing offline with /players 5 or up, five lightning sentries dealing up to 2.2k per shot plus your merc *should* be enough to produce a few corpses... which you can then detonate with Death Sentry.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In my (limited) experience with Trapsins (mine is lvl 81 in Hell Act III--I've been taking it very slowly!)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>a lot of the killing power comes from Death Sentry's corpse explosions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Lightning Sentries are just there to produce corpses to start the chain reaction.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The bigger issue I have faced with my Trapsin are lightning immunes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if you had 10k LS damage, it wouldn't make a difference if your preferred farming zone were chock full of lightning immune monsters, and you didn't have an Infinity on your merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Against those, I just bombard them with Fire Blast until one dies, then drop Death Sentries to detonate the corpses whilst my merc pokes at them with his Insight polearm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act bosses will never have elemental immunities, although their resistances are pretty high.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even then, it's not hard to just toss down a bunch of Lightning Sentries, hit them with lower resist (from a wand with lower resist charges), and run around dodging their attacks as the sentries whittle them down.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just be sure to switch to your MF kit when they have a sliver of health left.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, I wouldn't say that CBF (cannot be frozen) is really a must for your Trapsin--you should never be close to anything that can freeze you, and you have Cloak of Shadows to blind most ranged attackers anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One other tip I can give: don't be afraid to upgrade your Insight base.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The runes for it are cheap and common enough that if you find something better, try to cube it for 4 os, then make a new Insight.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just don't use spears... because those aren't polearms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for Treachery, it's a good runeword for +skills, but I actually prefer to give it to my merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having the chance to proc Fade overwrite your BoS can be a bit annoying.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_389_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you already have enough IAS (and the armour itself gives a substantial 45%), that chance to cast Fade can actually be a great boon, as it's probably a higher level Fade than whatever you've skilled into.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_390_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>An upped Death's Guard sash would be a nice way to get CBF, and being able to up the other items might actually make it worth using that entire set.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_390_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Same goes for Cleglaw's Brace.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_390_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One problem I have with some of those original sets (e.g. Death's Disguise, Berserker's Arsenal is that the items are kind of all over the place in terms of attribute requirements.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_390_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time you have enough strength to equip a War Sword, you certainly won't be using a regular, 8 slot sash anymore.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_390_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In the very least, being able to upgrade set items could give them far more utility in the long run.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_390_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As things stand, a lot of the original set items aren't really useful for more than a level or two in Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your results from those 50 runs are better than anything I've gotten from the Countess on my Trapsin.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd be happy with those Mals, Puls, and even the Dols.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, in the equivalent number of Countess runs, the highest I've gotten is a Dol... and not from the Countess herself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also got 3 keys like you did over that same course of runs, and a Wizardspike.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, I'll try keeping track of my runs as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm curious about your Trapsin's MF, though--with my normal gear (not seeking to maximise MF), it's usually sitting around 149%.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_391_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Would a lower MF help in any way for Countess rune drops, since if she drops fewer magic items, this could mean greater likelihood of dropping runes instead?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_392_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Indeed, that is a *very* fortunate drop :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_392_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are correct that MF doesn't affect rune drops, but I still do wonder if it affects the Countess' drop tables.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_392_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Probably not.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_392_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do believe, however, that the only way MF can truly factor in on Countess runs is when killing things on the way to the 5th level, and if it requires you to give up survivability or combat effectiveness.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_393_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was actually thinking about this build this morning on my way to work--going with Chain Lightning/Orb or even Chain Lightning/Firewall instead of Orb/Firewall.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_393_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, Cold + Fire immunes seem somewhat more abundant than Fire + Lightning ~~or Fire + Cold.~~ (edited to fix redundancy, lol).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_393_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, what puts me off this (when compared to Orb + Firewall) is that Lightning or Chain Lightning seems to need a lot of boosting from synergies *and* Lightning Mastery, whilst both Orb and Firewall can get decent damage from just the main skill and corresponding mastery.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_393_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it's not too much to ask, would you care to share your skill allocation?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_394_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Max Fire Blast with a Trapsin can definitely help you get by--you just need the Fire Blast to get the first corpse (and to help out your Merc) so you can throw down Death Sentries and clear the rest of the trash with corpse explosions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_394_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have a free respec left (or a token available), I'd consider using it to max Fire Blast--it gets synergy bonuses from your lightning sentry skills anyway, so with a few +skills, you'll be able to chuck out 1k damage Fire Blasts at decent speed--not face melting damage, but enough to help your Merc deal with them whilst you toss out Death Sentries from a safe distance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_394_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just watch out for Gloams in the Great Marsh--they are extra-nasty on Hell... especially if you encounter a unique pack with Conviction aura.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_394_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The more annoying enemies are those that are Fire *and* Lightning Immune, but that sort of immunity only tends to appear on the unique monster itself, not its minions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Act V Mercs can definitely get auras... provided that the weapons which grant auras allow for swords as bases.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, most of those runewords which do grant auras (and can be made in swords) tend to be somewhat more expensive than Insight, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were you, I'd stick with an Act II merc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The lack of variety is a bit unfortunate, but the Act II mercs provide so much more utility with their base auras, and the fact that many of the most powerful runewords which grant auras can be made in polearms as well (e.g. Infinity).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note that Act II mercs can also equip javelins, but they will **never** throw them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And they definitely can't use Amazon javelins (so no Titan's Revenge) for obvious reasons.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_395_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Though I honestly cannot think of any circumstance in which you'd want to give an Act II merc a javelin instead of a polearm or even a spear!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd say you are 62 years young, friendo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope to have your energy and enthusiasm when I reach your age in 28 years!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I think that you would indeed be deserving of the record.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never followed streamers much for any game, but I'd definitely be interested in following your D2R streams.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm guessing I could find your channel if I searched "RoninAU" on Twitch?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you aren't beginning each stream with "Stay a while and listen," you should be--because most of us are young enough to be your kids--and ot just because you made some bad life decisions (as I often joke with the high school students I teach and mentor).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_396_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although if *I* were your son, well, you'd **definitely** have made some bad life decisions, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_397_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>[This drop calculator](https://pairofdocs.github.io/d2-dropsim-web/) and [Silospen's Drop Calculator](https://dropcalc.silospen.com/item.php) can be pretty handy for figuring out whether you should farm on NM or Hell for a particular item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_397_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, apparently NM Andariel has better drop rates for SoJs than Hell Andy, although farming for a *particular* item is a bit of a fool's errand, in my opinion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_397_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In general, though, I believe that farming in NM is *much* safer and easier, but with lower rewards.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_397_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Farming in Hell is **potentially** (but not guaranteed) to be more lucrative, but with higher risks.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_397_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, if you can farm in Hell, you should do so.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_397_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you struggle in Hell, stick to NM to gain more levels (and hopefully) items that will help you survive in Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_398_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>LOL... you are right.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_398_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was very tired when I made that post.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_398_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thanks for pointing that out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By "level 20 blood magic" do you mean that skills/spells will cost life equivalent to their mana cost to cast?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If so, that isn't much of a drawback at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Remember that Vitality stacking has been the "meta" for a long time, and that even Sorcs (who have little use for Engima) tend to put very few, if any points in Energy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Engima already gives +14 life on kill, so having your skills/spells fueled by life instead of mana would balance itself out whilst fighting since anyone who can afford an Enigma (by trade or finding the runes) already has great trash-clearing speed.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only thing your "drawback" would do is make people spam teleport *a little* more slowly, but even then, they can just pop a Super Healing Potion or rejuv every now and then in between jumps.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, your proposed drawback is actually great in one regard: it makes Mana Burn uniques much less annoying and/or dangerous!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want to add some **real** drawbacks to Enigma, consider things like: * %x slower cast speed * %x slower run/walk * Requirements +x% (similar to the Unique Giant Axe, Humongous, which has 20% increased equip requirements) * %x **lower** chance of finding magic items (Nadir has a malus to gold find; so it might be possible to have a malus to magic find).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe make this one around -70 to 80% * x% chance to cast lvl 50 Delirium when struck (similar to Delirium runeword, but with double-digit proc chance) * x% chance to cast lvl 1 Teleport when struck (higher proc chance than Oculus) * \-x% to all resistances Now, if your lvl 20 Blood Magic meant that spells would cost 500% (or more) their mana cost (but in life) to cast, then that would indeed be more of a drawback.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I'm not sure how nerfing Enigma would improve your gameplay experience at all, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_399_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you think the item is overpowered, don't use it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree with you 100%, as a fellow D2 vet of some sort (I've been playing the game on and off since D2 classic was released).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, I personally don't *enjoy* immunities one bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I just deal with them, using those three things you named (build knowledge, item knowledge, and enemy knowledge).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd personally be happier if immunities were a lot rarer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For instance, if they were limited to unique monsters (and maybe their minions), as opposed to every trash mob and its mother having some sort of immunity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd also be fine with trash mobs having immunities that were more consistent--for instance, Horror mages that use Charged Bolt would be immune to lightning; Preserved Dead being immune to poison, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I do believe that the current system works fine... if you know what to expect.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_400_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If there were no immunities, Hell would be stupidly easy for any Blizzard sorc to faceroll, and you'd see 99% of builds being MF Blizzard Sorcs... which was definitely not Blizzard's intention, despite the company name, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of all your game suggestions, I think this is your best yet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, you'd need to either have the spell levels fixed (say, lvl 30 spells from a particular pool), or the chance to proc fixed at a decently low percentage (and levels variable).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having *both* variable would result in odd effects if you have different Inifuss Tree Seeds socketed in one item.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also wouldn't raise the proc percentage as high as 50%.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd cap it at, say, 15% maximum.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, it would be an interesting touch to have this item have the greatest chance to drop in areas that are **not** commonly farmed, e.g. the Swampy Pit in Act III.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I visited that area for the first time in over 20 years yesterday, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_401_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I didn't get anything good, but it was an interesting excursion off the beaten path.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Does Feral Rage's life leech work on enemies with 0 leech effectiveness, such as skeletons, NM and Hell Mephisto, and Hell Diablo?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't recall whether it does from my Fury druid (currently parked in NM at level 49).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If it doesn't... then you'll need to get a pair of Dracul's Grasp gloves to proc life tap for those sticky situations, since you cannot cast curses in wolf form (so no wand of life tap on switch).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for resistances, Fire and Lightning are what you really need--especially in Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think any amount of life leech will save you against focused fire from Gloams/Black Souls if you don't have decent lightning resistance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Likewise, good fire resistances are vital against Diablo (or his fire nova and fire storm attacks will really hurt you badly).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can generally get by ok with mediocre cold and poison resists; just make sure they aren't negative!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also have a plan to deal with physical immunities--decent chance to cast amp damage or Decrepify on hit (from you or your merc), or enough elemental damage to burn them down regardless.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ghosts and wraiths are the most common physical immunes in Hell, but those awful Blood Lords (frenzy minotaurs in Act V) *also* have a physical immune variant, too.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And just about any unique Blood Lord that spawns with Stone Skin could also end up physical immune, as they all get at least 66% damage reduction in Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_402_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can outrun ghosts, but if the Crystalline Passage is chock full of those bastards, I'd just consider making a new game, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_403_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That synergy between characters and builds was probably the rationale behind ubiquitous immunities in Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_403_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think the devs were giving solo play as much consideration at that point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_404_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is definitely a crude cave painting of a Tainted One/Misshapen, those demons that spit ball lightning at you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_404_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It isn't a dinosaur.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_404_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Note the blue/white thing in front of it (that depicts its ball lightning attack).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_404_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although if it makes you feel better, Diablo certainly *does* look rather reptilian (in both Diablo 1 and Diablo 2)... and there are some very large fossils in Act II's deserts that could have belonged to very large reptilian species, i.e. some type of dragon or dinosaur.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_405_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Countess is a stingy, high-maintenance wench.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_405_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll need to pay her *many* more visits if you want to get some good stuff from her.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_405_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never gotten anything from Hell Countess (over probably close to 50+ runs by now; I'm not grinding them out) that I wouldn't have gotten from NM or Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_405_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I'd keep at it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_405_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you can do those runs fast and safely, keep trying, and hopefully you'll get something above a Dol :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_406_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why do you say that?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_406_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd personally rather have the Ral or Tal--they are at least a bit closer to the mid runes (marginally so), and they are useful for socketing items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;What happened to the mage clans, amazons, barbarians, the entirety of westmarch, sorceresses and especially necromancers This is one of the biggest issues I have with Diablo 3's story.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, I guess the Barbarians are in it, but what exactly happened to the original heroes from D2?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D1 to D2 covered this nicely--each of the original heroes ends up as a nasty boss you have to face.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Rogue becomes Blood Raven in the graveyard; the Sorcerer becomes the Summoner in the Arcane Sanctuary, and the Warrior ends up as the Dark Wanderer, who becomes Big D himself.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, in Diablo 3, I guess the Sorceress decided to mentor some Asian students from Hogwarts (Wizards); the Druid smoked some bad mushrooms and died; the Paladin and Amazon decided to bugger off to who knows where; the Assassin order decided to start admitting men and turned into complete edge lords (Demon Hunters); the Barbarian just got old (and recruited his sister too), and the Necromancer went full Heart of Darkness and decided to rule over some indigenous tribe in the jungles, and send them out to do his bidding (Witch Doctors).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And to top it all off, Diablo himself decided that a sex change was *really* what he needed to enact his evil plans, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the Sisters of the Sightless Eye, the denizens of Lut Gholein, and the residents of Kurast?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Who knows, or even cares what happened to them, as far as Diablo 3's story is concerned?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_407_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You or I may want that sort of continuity, but the people working on Diablo 3 definitely didn't care a fig about the previous games.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_408_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest issue I can see with energy shield is Mana Burn monsters--wouldn't one hit from one of those bugged mobs wipe out your entire mana pool, thus leaving you extremely vulnerable?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_409_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I never noticed that texture pop-in before, but I'm guessing it's to save on visual memory?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_409_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At least I learned three new Polish words today: "Kozsmar" = Nightmare; "Zdrowie" = health... and "Mana" = Mana! :</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_409_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D. Now I'm tempted to reinstall D2R in Polish just to improve my vocabulary and impress my Polish girlfriend's parents, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_410_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I didn't like the new look for the Barbarian, but it grew on me over time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_410_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Same for the Paladin, Necromancer, and Sorceress (whom I now think looks better than the original Sorc, especially in plate mail and a crown helm).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_410_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Amazon looks unfortunate, but since I haven't found a zon build I enjoy playing, that's a non-issue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_410_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the Assassin... that's a travesty, but like I mentioned above, there are mods to fix the Assassin's look.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_411_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Assassin indeed looks awful, and the voice doesn't match the new look for the character one bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_411_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you are playing offline, there are mods on the Nexus that will restore her original look to some degree.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_411_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Search for "Assassin retouch" and "Assasin and Amazon Outfit Changes" on there.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_411_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although those are both visual mods, I wouldn't use them if playing online unless Blizzard oks visual mods that do not affect gameplay in any way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_412_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'd need to have *extremely* bad (or good) luck to have 20 consecutive no-rune drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_412_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, or you'd need to be playing on classic, eheh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_412_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's worth noting that the Countess has a chance to drop zero runes even on the first quest kill (this happened to me with my Trapsin on NM and Hell), which is a bit disappointing, since her quest kill rune drops have a higher range of potential runes than subsequent drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_412_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I find it best to look at Countess runs just as a (near) guaranteed source of at least *one* rune.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_412_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But since her rune drop table spans the gamut from el to ral in normal, el to ko in NM, and el to Lo in Hell, there's no reason why Hell Countess can't give you a nice bag of Orts, Eths, and Elds on several subsequent runs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_412_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I can tell, her drop table *isn't* significantly weighted toward higher rune drops based on difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_413_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>How much time did that take you to gamble that dagger, though?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_413_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, worse than the gold loss would be the time spent hanging out with Gheed clicking daggers until that identifying sound makes you want to puke, ech.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_413_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You have my sympathies, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_413_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope you can find another Gull soon!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Personally, I would be reluctant to use a Larzuk quest reward just to punch 4 os in a Paladin shield.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd use the Horadric Cube formula (Tal + Amn + P ruby) and hope for the best.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd save Larzuk for something that **must** have 6 os, or for putting a socket in a unique.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that the cube formula is a bit of a gamble, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is how I got my 4 os monarch for my Sorc's spirit, however!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And do remember that it does **not** work with superior items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, if you don't want to waste a near-perfect base, or the base item you found is superior, go with Larzuk to get the max sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To avoid screwing up future Larzuk quest rewards on unsuitable bases, take note of [sockets and ilvl here](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And compare that to [Area Levels](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For a 4 os crystal sword, you'll need an ilvl between 26 and 40.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This means that any white crystal sword that drops in Act IV normal, Normal Cows, and all of Act V between the Crystalline Passage and WSK 2 would work.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wouldn't try using a low-quality item (e.g. cracked, crude, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_414_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>since those have a lower ilvl, if I'm not mistaken.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_415_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I always just assumed they were skeleton keys.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_415_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, or every lockbox in Sanctuary uses a similar pattern.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_415_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, for a pre-industrial society, the kingdoms of Sanctuary show a surprising level of standardisation. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_415_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All vendors (even those in an angelic outpost on the shores of hell) accept the same currency \- Everyone, from the healers of Khanduras to the alchemists of Lut Gholein to the mages of Kurast follows the same bottling system for potions to avoid confusion or accidents among adventurers (e.g. someone drinking an Exploding Potion that was packaged similar to a Minor Healing Potion) It's also interesting that there are no locked chests in Act IV, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_415_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apparently, theft isn't a major concern in the Burning Hells (even though some of its unfortunate residents were certainly thieves in their lives).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_415_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But then again, the Burning Hells are a gated community, so I guess the demons and the damned trust one another enough to not need locks on their containers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_416_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That would depend *highly* on where you plan to wear that hoodie, and the company you associate with.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_416_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have to deal with pearl-clutching Karens (or the German equivalent) on a daily basis due to your occupation or line of work, then a hoodie with that design wouldn't be a good choice to wear when on duty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_416_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But in your free time, I don't see why not... unless you again have the misfortune of living among said pearl-clutching Karens.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_416_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But to be fair, that type seems to be unique to the USA, at least in my experience.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_416_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I imagine that most people who see you wearing such a hoodie on the street would either not think anything of it, or they might ask which band it is from, because it looks metal AF.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_417_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Dzieki :D. I appreciate the correction.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_417_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Polish is a very hard language, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_417_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I remember that when I was studying German at uni, my classmates would always complain about the spelling... but Polish takes the cake when it comes to difficult spelling. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_417_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I unfortunately don't have any diacritic marks on my keyboard.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_417_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know the "e" should have a diacritic on it.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_418_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also make sure that the item isn't low quality either (i.e. no cracked, crude, low quality, etc.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_418_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's worth noting that "normal" in this context just means non-magical or non-superior.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_418_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It doesn't refer to the item tier (viz.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_418_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>normal, exceptional, or elite)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The town portal scrolls aren't quite the "get out of gaol free card" that you are thinking.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The monsters' AI is coded to try to surround your character whenever possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, it is quite possible for you to not be able to reach your portal even if you open one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, if you TP out of a nasty situation without putting a bit of distance between you and the monsters, they will be still waiting for you at the entrance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not uncommon for people to die instantly after returning from town to monsters camping the TP (also potentially due to unscrupulous or foolish party members who threw down a TP in a bad spot like right next to Pindleskin's resurrecting minions, lol).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for what you should pick up, it depends on what you are looking for.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want gold, pick up and sell staves, sceptres, and wands with bonuses to Sorc, Paladin, or Necro skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These will usually sell for the max amount for that act and difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pick up and identify blue and yellow amulets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At higher levels, some will have +skills and other nice mods.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When it comes to rings, the only desirable blue ones I can think of are rings with dual-magic find affixes and maybe some rings with high +lightning or fire resistance when starting out.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Other than that, the rare rings are what you'd want--especially those with lightning and fire resistance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't bother picking up cracked, crude, or low quality items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pick up and check all grey items to see how many sockets (if any) they may have.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some may provide good bases for runewords you want to make.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pick up and identify charms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Before Act IV Hell difficulty, I'd recommend just dumping the charms that don't have affixes you want.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_419_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After Act IV in Hell difficulty, it could be worth holding onto some of the less desirable grand charms to try rerolling them for +skills and +life affixes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason why most people suggest (and prefer) crystal swords is the low stat requirements.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Crystal swords require 43 strength *and 0 dexterity*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Broad swords require 48 strength *and 0 dexterity*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Long swords require **55** strength **and 39 dexterity**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you're a caster build, you usually have little use for dex.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The nice thing about the Long sword and Broadsword is that both can only have a maximum of 4 os, so there's no risk of "oversocketing," heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I were you, I wouldn't use Larzuk's quest reward for this unless you have a bunch of other unused quest rewards from other characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just find a couple of crystal swords that drop in the following zones: \- All of Act IV Normal \- Normal Cows \- Act V: from Crystalline Passage through WSK 2 And use the Horadric Cube recipe Ral + Amn + Perfect Amethyst.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_420_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This won't guarantee 4 os, but it has a pretty good chance of rolling them (around 50% chance).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_421_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Dimensional blades look identical to crystal swords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_421_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The dimensional blade does have much higher stat requirements than the crystal sword, though hence why it isn't as popular a base for Spirit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_421_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I did once make Spirit in a 4 os Dimensional blade on my Hammerdin, as I had the runes, and one dropped for me in Act I NM with 4 os already on it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_422_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Never played PD2 or PoD, but I do agree that it would be interesting if Holy Bolt, Sanctuary, and FoH's Holy Bolts could also damage demons in addition to the undead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_422_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, those skills should ideally remain harmless to animals (monsters that are not demons or undead), as this would make sense from a lore/immersion perspective.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_422_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I'm not mistaken, Sanctuary already allows you to ignore physical resistance or even immunity on undead monsters (although it doesn't apply for crushing blow calculations).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_422_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This makes me wonder if it could be worth investing a point or two for a Zealadin to deal with PIs like Ghosts and Wraiths.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_423_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You do raise a good point--the beasts (non-undead or non-demons) you face in game are all corrupted forms, to some degree.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_423_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The original D2 manual mentions this, in fact.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_423_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What if Holy Bolt were to affect those monsters like the Assassin's Mind Blast does--some damage + stun and chance to convert?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_423_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>From an immersion perspective, it would make sense, since one could imagine the holy magic temporarily driving out the evil from the creature.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_423_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Against undead and demons, however, it would do direct damage + stun with no chance to convert, since those things are pure evil anyway, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_424_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Aye, normal, exceptional, and elite items all look identical.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_424_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only change in artwork is with certain unique and set items vs. their non-unique or non-set equivalents.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As much as I'd like to see a Diablo live action adaptation, I am also extremely sceptical about the ability of any contemporary studio to produce something that would remain faithful to the source material without unwelcome changes for the following reasons: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To inject contemporary politics 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To pander to certain consumer groups 3. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Artistic licence" to "update" or "modernise" certain elements deemed "outdated" or "unsuitable in 2021+" Moreover, if you compare live action adaptations of things like Wheel of Time and The Witcher, both of those did have computer games associated with them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But they also had an abundance of well-written novels and literary source material.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never read any of the Diablo novels, but with no offense to their authors, I can't imagine they are anywhere as well-written as Sapkowski's books.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If this idea were proposed, say, 8 to 12 years ago, I would have confidence that studios like the one which produced the Spartacus or Game of Thrones series could pull it off.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They could portray the Diablo universe in all its bloody, brutal, and dark glory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I shudder to think of what they'd do with a live-action Diablo to match 2021+ ways of thinking--especially if Activision Blizzard has any significant input in the creative direction.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, Activision Blizzard is the company that gave us Diablo III's story.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The sad and ironic thing is that a faithful representation of D1 and D2 *would (*and *should)* already appeal to everyone who enjoys that genre.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It has diversity, strong female and "minority" characters (without a hint of tokenism), and equal-opportunity arse-kicking.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are no helpless damsels in distress or offensive stereotypes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_425_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But Diablo was a product of an earlier time, when people thought differently than they do today, and when people did not take offence quite as easily as they do today.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_426_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is an excellent point.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_426_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I do recall that on my very first character in D2R, amethysts in general were surprisingly elusive... until I found myself drowning in them with my second character.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_427_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They can be helpful in early Act I Normal, until you reach around level 6, as the throwing potions will generally inflict more consistent damage than whatever weapons or skills you may have access to.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_427_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For some builds, e.g. fledgling Summon Necros, strangling gas pots can be useful to create more victims for the ever-growing army of the undead.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_427_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They are mostly obsolete, however, by the time you reach Normal Countess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_427_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By the time you can equip Rancid Gas potions, there's no reason to ever pick one up.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_428_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This +100. "</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_428_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Quality of life" is a highly subjective and vague term.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_428_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To some people, creating a separate charm inventory would be a "QoL" feature, but to me, it would be a significant change to the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_428_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Same goes for replacing immunities in Hell with super-high resistances, or adding melee splash damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_428_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm not saying that these changes would be positive or negative, but they aren't simple tweaks that would not significantly change balance or alter gameplay when compared to things like automatic gold pickup, for instance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_429_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As someone who has always loved Act III since the release of D2 in 1999, I'm glad you have come to see the Light, brother (or sister).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_429_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now do you have a moment to hear the word of Zakarum, and maybe purchase this Towering Spire?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That's expected.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Against Hell Cows, there are just so many cows that they can easily hack your merc to death if you aren't killing them fast enough to prevent him from being surrounded.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the Council Members' Hydra, I'm not sure if those are bugged or something, but the damage seems to stack very rapidly if you stand around to get pelted by the firebolts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, Merc AI is somewhat... special, so they don't tend to move out of the way of the hydras.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Mercs take a bit of babysitting if you want to keep them alive in situations like that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may need to teleport around to pull him out of danger (until the hydra expires), or to keep him away from Hell andy in the same way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Speaking of Andariel, though, what's your merc's poison resistance?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you can kill the Council, clear Cows, and put down Andariel without your Merc's help for aura support or tanking, I'd just resurrect him afterward if babysitting him proves too much of a hassle.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think it's a gearing issue you have with your merc but rather the poor AI.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The hirelings tend to bumble around a lot and they actually spend a lot of idle time standing in one spot--which means eating a ton of firebolts.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_430_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, you don't get killed by Hydra spam because you are actively moving to not catch 20 firebolts in the face.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_431_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some of those mods change the gameplay quite a bit from vanilla.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_431_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Like I mentioned, it's not necessarily in a good or negative way, but it is different.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_431_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I would personally welcome those mods for D2R, because they would definitely add to the longevity of the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_431_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest improvement I would like to see to **vanilla** D2R, however, is better hireling/merc AI.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_431_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, and fixing the despawn bug for summons like golems, revives, and shadow warrior/master.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nice find! :</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>D. However, I wouldn't think that you will never find anything again, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I found a Shako off a random corpse spitter in Act IV Hell... and to my surprise and pleasure, it wasn't ethereal either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Needless to say, I was immensely pleased.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For the record, I had around 160 MF on my Trapsin at the time (without wearing my full MF kit).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I also found a Wizardspike from a random devilkin in the Forgotten Tower some weeks ago as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's always nice to find something good when you aren't looking for it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Come to think of it, most of the desirable items I've found thus far (a couple Lem runes, Wizardspike, Shako, Ribcracker, Rockstopper, Ali Baba, Gull, 3 pieces of the Disciple Set--nothing GG, but stuff I wanted/needed for my builds) were all obtained when I wasn't actively farming for any of them.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, when I actively tried to farm uniques or runes, I seldom got anything of use, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That makes me think that it all comes down to mentality/perspective.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If I tell myself that I'm looking for some El and Eld runes, I never find any... but I do start finding Shaels and Dols, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_432_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe I should actively start hunting for low runes and trash uniques, then!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I feel your pain, friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What makes things worse with the Council is that they heal one another very rapidly too.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So if you're babysitting your merc by teleporting him out of danger every time, you aren't going to doing any damage to the Council members whom you *can* kill on your own.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And if you're killing the Council, your merc is playing Pet-the-Hydra.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some people swear by Orb + Fireball.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have the respec tokens (or free respecs) to spare, it could be worth a try.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I personally think that the damage may be a bit mediocre overall compared to Orbwall, but if you can still clear quickly, it could be worthwhile.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What's interesting is that Meteorb felt good in LoD classic--I don't remember having too much difficulty aiming meteors in the original game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But here, meteor feels quite lackluster.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It could just be that the game runs at a higher framerate than LoD classic... and the indicator circle for meteor vanishes right after you cast it, whereas in the original LoD it would remain until impact.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_433_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But that's just my perception... and maybe it's just a matter of learning the timing correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I would definitely respec if I were you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sorcs get 2 life per vitality point invested, so your reassignment will mean 120 less hit points.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That may sound like a lot, but also consider the following: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Spirit gives you +22 vitality when equipped.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So that's 44 life back.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>We are down to -76 from your original allocation.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Waterwalks can give up to +65 life.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Now we are down to just -11 from your original total.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Not too bad, eh?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you can get your hands on a Shako, you're going to get +111 life... and +1 skills net gain over the Lore helm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, you would be giving up that 30 lightning resistance from the Lore, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I must ask, though: what's an Armageddon helm?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Are you referring to just a rare (yellow) helm?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't remember any unique or runeword that has "armageddon" in the name!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even without the Waterwalks or Shako, you'll only lose 76 life once you respec to equip the Spirit Monarch--and that is assuming no other modification in your kit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At level 74 in Hell, you can gain a few levels pretty quickly as you progress, so you can start pumping vitality again.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Levelling only seems to slow down when you are in the 80s, and it really grinds to a halt in the 90s.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_434_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for that Nightsmoke belt, I hope you have upped it to a mesh belt to get 4 rows.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Build(s) that can solo entirety of the game on /players 8?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was thinking today about what build(s) could solo the entire of the game on /players 8 from Act I Normal through Hell Baal under the following conditions: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You start on /players 8 from level 1, and do not change or lower the /players setting at any point 2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You progress through the game normally and complete every single quest on every difficulty (so no teleporting through half the act just to kill the act boss whilst skipping 95% of the monsters and other content) 3.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>SSF isn't a hard requirement, but the build cannot be defined by/dependent on super rare items or high runes to be viable, because if trading isn't an option, the chances of actually finding those HRs is pretty slim!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So no Tesladins, Werebear Sorcs, Riftsins, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only build that really comes to mind is the **Summon Necro/Fishymancer**.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Corpse explosion still hurts monsters badly even on /players 8 when combined with Amplify Damage.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And you can always have your merc kill a couple weak monsters in Act I to generate some victims for the ever-growing army of the undead, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And once you get the skeleton party going, it doesn't seem like it would be too bad... although it will be slow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for teleporting/telestomping, you can always use an item with teleport charges, although it would be a bit expensive (in terms of gold) to recharge them constantly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Anyone have any other suggestions for builds that can do this reliably? **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Orbwall Sorcs** and **Trapsins** can get past most immunities on Hell, but to really thrive on /players 8, I imagine that one would likely need Infinity to do so... and getting 2 Ber runes and an Ist offline is a rather tall order.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'd also imagine **Hammerdins** could work as well (even just using readily available gear like dual Spirit runewords, +2 skill ammy or circlets, and maybe the occasional +skill GC).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I know that many, many people have already accomplished this, but I'm just curious to see your opinions about which other builds besides **Summonmancers** are truly viable options for this particular "challenge."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_435_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm currently working on this with my Summonmancer, and would like to try it with other builds/characters.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_436_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Great job on completing that challenge!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_436_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That sounds like something I would have to try some time!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_436_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My personal (and far less daunting) challenge is to complete the game on /players 8 from Act I Normal through Hell Baal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_436_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only build I think could do it reliably is a Summonmancer, but I welcome any suggestions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_437_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Alkor wouldn't shank you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_437_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He'd just pour something nasty and corrosive into your soup whilst you weren't looking.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_437_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unless you are Necromancer, as he is really eager to learn about Necromantic potions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_437_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He'd only poison you once he finds out that you don't actually use anything besides the ocasional blue mana potion to raise your undead army, and that his books have been lying to him about Necromancers all this time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_438_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Well, I do enjoy playing a Summonmancer, but I tend to play the game with full clearing--or close to it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_438_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I wanted to see what other builds would be able to do the same, even relatively untwinked.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_439_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is an excellent answer; thank you!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_440_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was building a fury druid (werewolf), but I might respec to that build you describe since my fury druid is currently parked in NM with a free respec.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_440_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's not that I cannot progress with him, but mostly that I got sidetracked with other characters, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_441_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pretty much full clearing except for truly optional zones like The Hole, Swampy Pit, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_442_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That sounds like one hell of a challenge... and yes, you are right that the Maggot Lair is always a pain on a Summonmancer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_442_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Arcane Sanctuary is also a tedious slog.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_442_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo on Normal wasn't an issue for my Fishymancer, though--I didn't lose a single skeleton to him.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_442_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Decrepify will really slow him to a crawl.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_443_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Biggest issue I could see with Smiter is the lack of multi-target damage and dealing with groups.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_443_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, I will probably respec my Zealadin into more of a Smiter once I'm done with Hell to farm Ubers for torches, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_444_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've tried Act V Hell on P8 with my Trapsin, and whilst I didn't get curb stomped, it was taking too long to kill things.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_444_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't yet have Infinity on my Merc, and I haven't yet been fortunate enough to find +3 LS and +3 Traps claws.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_444_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apparently NM and Hell Anya can sell these, but I've never seen her have anything of the sort.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_444_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe I need to check more often, or pop in and out of Pindle's portal for 40 minutes, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_445_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Killing random shit is fun, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_445_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And sometimes can grant you some decent items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_445_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As far as I can recall, almost every item that made my jaw drop came from a random mob: Shako, my first Mal and Pul runes (which I used to make Oath for my Zealot), Gull, Wizardspike (which I still haven't found a use for), etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_445_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, to each his own.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_445_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The beauty of Diablo 2 is that you can play it however you like... to some degree.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_446_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've had something slightly similar (but nowhere as egregious) happen to me on PC in single player--the game crashed in Act I NM, and when I restarted, my Cube was gone from my inventory.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_446_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I had go to back to Normal Act II to get a new one, as I didn't feel like playing through all of Act I NM without a Horadric Cube.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_446_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Regarding the stuff you lost on your Sorc--was this in the shared or personal stash?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_446_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most of the stories I've heard of disappearing items involve the shared stash... Fortunately, I think what happened to you isn't the norm.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_446_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you were playing on PC, I'd suggest backing up your save files if you are worried about future crashes and lost items, but I don't know if you can do that on the console.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_447_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's definitely there for flavour.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_447_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a shame that the set doesn't give you the lifesteal fireball that the Vampires have, instead of just the normal Sorc fireball, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_448_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is some impressive attention to detail!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_448_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I love posts like this which point out little details I never noticed :D However, I have noticed that the Sorceress' idle posture in town seems to be always looking at her feet... or perhaps some other part of her body, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_448_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, and her stance changes notably between the current and legacy graphics (you can notice the difference most when you have a shield equipped).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Looks like we've got ourselves a badass here!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All jokes aside, any reason for all the unnecessary belligerence?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't speak for other people, but I personally would never downvote anyone for just expressing their opinion on a thread *I* created.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't expect everyone to agree with me.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Heck, if I didn't want people's opinions, I wouldn't have wasted the time I could have spent scratching my arse to create this thread!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, "fun" is subjective.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe you are the type to rage and smash gaming peripherals after your umpteenth death, but to me, if each death gets me a bit further, that's progress, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To each his own.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_449_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Good luck to you too, friendo... and may life treat you better so that you don't ooze with barely repressed rage in what should otherwise be a friendly discussion among people who share a common interest.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_450_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only thing better than this would be to simply allow TCP/IP play so that people can enjoy multiplayer with their favourite mods, and keep the regular [Battle.net](https://Battle.net) play as it is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_450_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is how it was with LoD classic, and everyone was (generally) happy with it, as I recall.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely lower MF with quicker kills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Quicker kills = more runs, which equals more chance of finding stuff you want.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'd be surprised at what you can get from random trash mobs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Slower kills means more time per run... and greater chance of you dying.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The best solution is to balance MF with combat efficacy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Find the maximum MF at which you can clear monsters efficiently, and maybe tweak that a bit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Having so much MF that it takes you ages to kill a particularly resilient unique pack is no bueno.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_451_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Hope [this](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Magic_find_diminishing_returns) helps with your maths and determining how much MF you should shoot for, then aim for +skills, FCR, and other things that will help keep you alive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_452_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What did the Countess drop?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_452_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if she's just giving you Els, Tirs, and Nefs, you can readily cube those up to a Tal with a bit of persistence.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_452_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you got three Iths during those runs, you have yourself a Tal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_452_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Of course, if you don't yet have a Horadric Cube (and no characters past Act I Normal), you'd need to wait until Act II to do that!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_453_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Don't feel bad, friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_453_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>My first Hell Countess kill in D2R, she dropped absolutely no runes or keys.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_453_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That was with my Trapsin, who seems to be cursed as far as runes go, since I never got anything better from the Countess with my Trapsin than a Lum and a couple keys.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_453_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, on my first Hell Countess kill with my Orbwall Sorc, she dropped a Lem and a Dol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_453_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, considering that those keys are rarer than rune drops, consider yourself fortunate.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_453_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just make sure to collect and stash at least 2 more keys of terror minimum whilst you are at it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_454_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This is the way.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_454_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, 317% MF with your main FCR loadout is still quite impressive.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_454_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Some would argue that it is more than good enough for MF purposes, but squeezing a bit more out when facing boss packs or for when landing killing blows on act bosses never hurts :D.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Why don't you like Corpse Explosion?!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>According to the original D2 devs, it's the best skill in the game.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I kid you not.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, using a crossbow to support your minions probably wouldn't work very well outside of Act I Normal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only marginally viable options for the long term I can think of would be the following: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Using an upped Pus Spitter unique crossbow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It has -60% requirements and +2 Necromancer skills.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Making a Faith runeword (Ohm Jah Lem Eld) in a 4 os Colossus crossbow, for the lvl 15 Fanaticism, +2 skills. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This** could work, since it also has Ignores Target Defence, which will effectively give you a 95% hit chance against all normal mobs (but not uniques and act bosses).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The AR bonuses from the Fanaticism will also help, as will the attack speed bonus from the aura and the damage bonus to you and your minions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, Faith is an expensive runeword to make, and any crossbow in which you'd want to make it will likely have very high strength and dexterity requirements, which means fewer points in vitality.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You are also foregoing a lot of +skills and potential resistance bonuses by using a 2h weapon vs. 1h and shield (or shrunken head).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never seen anyone use a Faith crossbow on a Necromancer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Might have to do with the Ohm and Jah runes, among other things.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you have a spare Ohm and Jah rune lying around, there are probably better things you can use or save them for on a Necro than a Faith crossbow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_455_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And even with a lot of attribute bonuses from endgame kit, you'd still end up putting more points into dex and strength than you would normally want to with a Necro.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_456_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's a bit of a joke, referencing the 404 error for pages not found on websites.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_457_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The breakfast of champions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_457_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've never cared much for Wheaties (or any breakfast cereal), but your post may actually convince me to go out and buy a box :D. All jokes aside, was this online or offline?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_457_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the latter, at which player settings?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_457_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And was any horking involved?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>[Item levels,](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Sockets) my friend.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want a 5 os flail, it must have an ilvl of at least 41+.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Generally, ilvl is tied to the [area level](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Area_Level) in which it drops.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, any white (non-magic, non-unique) flail that drops in NM Tower level 4  amp; 5, and from NM Jail 1 onward can have 5 os.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just to be safe, however, I'd only use flails that drop from the Catacombs onward.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For 4 os flails, you need an ilvl of between 26 and 40.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Thus, Act IV Normal, Normal Cows, and Normal Act V from Arreat Plateau to WSK level 2 would be the places to look, although Normal Cows is the safest bet.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>NB: By "safe," I don't mean that the area itself is necessarily safe to farm (although Normal difficulty generally isn't dangerous anywhere), but safe in the sense that an item dropped in those zones should have the ilvl to match what you are looking for without risking any mistakes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_458_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are running Cows for runeword bases, remember to remove your MF gear to minimize the chances of blues and yellows dropping instead of white items.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_459_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I hope that your vertigo isn't due to serious illness or head injury!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_459_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In any event, I hope that you get better soon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_460_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Very impressive results, I must say!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_460_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, investing in bone prison and wall seems like a good idea.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_460_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What scares me most as a Summon Necro (or when my Summonmancer reaches Hell) are cursed unique archer/quill rat packs (basically anything with ranged physical attacks), Gloams, and Extra Fast Death Lords in Act V. Bone Prison or wall will shut down all but the Gloams as an extra measure of safety.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_461_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely, I will have to invest some points in Dim Vision as well by the time I reach Hell.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_462_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I think that's a Glaive in her hands, not a sword, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_462_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But no, zons don't really have any abilities that work well with swords, other than critical strike, or whatever oskills you can get from runewords or uniques (e.g. Berserk or Zeal from Passion runeword).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What is "disgusting" about the artwork for the female characters?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Please tell me what "the problem" is that you claim is "very real."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And yes, Diablo 2 is from a different era.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is an elegant game from a more civilised time.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That was an era when people did not get offended about every innocuous thing instead of speaking out against **actual** injustices.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I miss the late 90s and early 2000s, when it was actually possible to look toward the future with bright-eyed hope.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_463_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All one can hope for is that things remain more or less the same as they are now, as opposed to getting worse.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oath grants Indestructible as one of the runeword mods, so ideally, you would want to use an ethereal base.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This means no recharging the skill charges, as ethereal items cannot be recharged or repaired.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, if you ever switch weapons, the summoned monsters will disappear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At least I know this is true with the Heart of Wolverine; I've never tried the Iron Golem so I'm not 100% sure about that one.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The main reason to make Oath is for the massive %ED and IAS.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>340% ED and 50% IAS on an ethereal superior base is no joke--and it doesn't require any runes higher than Mal.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are very lucky, you can get all the runes from Hell Countess.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, keep in mind that runewords made in superior items (that aren't indestructible) have significantly increased repair costs.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But... if both of your weapons are indestructible, you will save a lot of gold on repairs since weapons for melee characters are what take the most wear and tear.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But gold is easy to make anyway!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for which weapon you should switch out... that is tough.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you can up the Butcher's Pupil, it would be worth keeping, since Oath will definitely offer higher damage than either of those on average, I imagine.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Perhaps you could equip one at a time, and switch out the lower damage one for Oath.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Since you seem to be focusing on axes, I'd use a 4 os ethereal superior Berserker Axe, as that has the highest max damage for any 1h axe.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just keep in mind that it **will** have to drop with 4 os, since if you try to Larzuk a superior Berserker Axe, he will almost always put 6 sockets in it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are impatient, you can use an ethereal superior Small Crescent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That can only have 4 os maximum, so if you Larzuk it, you will get 4 sockets.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Oddly enough, the Berserker axe has a longer melee range than the Small Crescent, at least according to the Arreat Summit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_464_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That might also factor into your considerations as a WW barb.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_465_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nope, you'd only have those charges, and when they are gone, they are gone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_465_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, you don't make Oath for the charges.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_465_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's for the IAS and ED.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_465_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be honest, the only skill charges which I really find useful are: \- Lower Resist \- Life Tap \- Teleport Other than those three skills (2 only spawn on wands, the latter can spawn on staves, amulets, and 1 unique axe, Spellsteel), I don't find most other skill charges to be particularly noteworthy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_466_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I don't think any of the Primarchs were particularly egotistical for changing their legions' names.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_466_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only one you could accuse of egotism might be Horus, as no other legion was named after its Primarch.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_466_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>All of those changes made sense, because once the Primarch joined his legion, its culture and combat doctrines often changed drastically.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Both gunpowder (i.e. black powder) and smokeless powder have their own oxidizing agent.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The first rockets were fueled by gunpowder.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Soviets even had a space station with a 23mm autocannon which they successfully test-fired in low Earth orbit.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>So yes, regular firearms would function in space.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There are some reasons, though, why a conventional firearm wouldn't be an ideal weapon in the vacuum of space.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most are easily remedied, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You may have some moving parts cold-weld together in the airless atmosphere, and oil-based lubricants may turn into sticky sludge.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, this is easily overcome with proper dry lubricants.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Recoil from larger-calibre weapons could push you backward if you are floating in space.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Again, easily fixable by having your suit provide a small propulsion boost (from a gas generator) to counteract any backward push from your weapon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That, or only using firearms in places that have some sort of gravitational pull (Luna would be fine).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ejected cartridge casings could pose a foreign object danger.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Easily solved by using revolvers, or could be an impetus to invest in caseless ammo.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The main reason why you don't see conventional firearms used in space settings in sci-fi is really just the rule of cool, to be frank.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_467_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If a civilisation has the means to develop FTL capability and build kilometre-long space ships, it would look a bit drab for them to still be shooting at each other with ARs, Glocks, and AKs, don't you think?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_468_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even if the Grey Knights *didn't* have to purge all the survivors (due to Inquisitorial mandates), you definitely **don't** want the Grey Knights to show up to answer your distress call... because if the Grey Knights come, whatever you are fighting is far, far worse than even Tyranids.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are an atheist, then you shouldn't even believe in humans having a soul, or any sort of afterlife.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The existence of the soul cannot be scientifically proven in real life anyway.. but I personally prefer to see a universe where there is some justice.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I cannot abide the idea of a universe in which Oskar Dirlewanger and St. Francis of Assisi end up in the same exact place: as food for the worms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For this reason, I am not an atheist.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I do agree with you atheists (and incidentally, the Emperor) on the point that organised religion has done a lot of harm throughout history.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It would be a grand day if we could separate the "be good to your neighbour" and "strive for virtue, even if it isn't immediately rewarded (if at all)" parts of religions like Christianity from the "kill the unbeliever" parts that seem to crop up way too often over the course of human history, and are **still** problematic in many parts of the world.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_469_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, if one believes in an all-powerful deity, it's a bit of a stretch to believe that this deity would need ordinary humans to do his dirty work when it comes to unbelievers!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_470_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Human souls: right to the warp... where it's always Taco Tuesday, and your soul is just what Srx'tll'ar the Unclean (more commonly known as "Steve" to his cultists, who have trouble pronouncing his actual name, which wasn't coined with mortal tongues in mind) has been looking forward to use to season his Eldar skin-wrapped tortillas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_470_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those who were good little boys and girls presumably go to the Emperor, to fight by his side at the battle against Chaos at the end times.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_470_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ork souls: re-absorbed by Gork and Mork, presumably.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_470_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I doubt that Orks even have individual souls, although they do have a psychic consciousness and they definitely have individual personalities.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_471_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The biggest issue I have with some of the battles in 40K is that somehow, humanity has mostly forgotten how to rapidly assemble a subcritical mass of highly enriched U-235 to make a big bang.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_471_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Considering that many of the enemies of the Imperium of Man like Orks and Tyranids *love* to use swarm tactics and just charge pell-mell across large, open, plains, why is the Imperium still using only high explosives against them?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_471_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Considering that the Imperium has no qualms about using radiological weapons, you'd think that they'd be firing nuclear artillery shells and atomic rockets like crazy against a Tyranid or Ork horde, especially when it's on a planet that is nigh uninhabitable anyway.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_471_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's probably that the authors don't understand how powerful the blast effects of nuclear weapons are, or that they recognise that if the Imperium had the types of tactical and strategic warheads Earth has had since the mid-20th century, a lot of those battles wouldn't be possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_472_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The most amusing thing about the Scarus sector is that it was named after a Word Bearer shortly before the Horus Heresy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_472_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Apparently, the Imperium never thought to change the name, and no Imperial alive in M41 would even be able to make that connexion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I agree 100% that The Purge is one of the best of the Horus Heresy series.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It also provides some nice prequel material for the Word Bearers series as well!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, one thing that always intrigued me is **how** exactly phosphex works.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The BL writers really aren't consistent about it at all.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Is it just like some extra-nasty Willie Pete?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Then it shouldn't be able to burn underwater (it is described as being able to do this) **or** in the vacuum of space.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, just smothering a patch of burning phosphex should extinguish it... temporarily.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or is it more like chlorine trifluoride--which *doesn't* need oxygen to burn, as the fluorine provides the oxidizer?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>ClF3 seems like the closest real-life equivalent to phosphex; it will even set asbestos on fire, and is highly corrosive (In *Ignition*, John Drury Clark wryly remarks that the best way to deal with a chlorine trifluoride fire is to have a good pair of running shoes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He also describes a spill as burning through multiple concrete floors.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is hypergolic with most known materials... and the Germans were considering using it as an incendiary weapon against the Maginot Line in WW2.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_473_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Later experiments with ClF3 postulated its usage as liquid rocket fuel, but thankfully, we were able to find slightly less dangerous alternatives.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_474_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's probably Aura Enchanted monsters with Holy Freeze that are chilling you.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_474_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cannot be Frozen only applies to cold damage attacks (e.g. from Horror Mages and Cold Enchanted uniques).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_474_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It won't protect you from Duriel's aura, either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_474_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's generally a good idea to kill Aura Enchanted uniques ASAP, since they can provide some **very** nasty bonuses to their mates, like... \- Cursed, Extra Strong, Aura Enchanted (with Might or Fanatacism) Dark Archers = firing squad. \-</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_474_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Aura Enchanted Gloams with Conviction = ride the lightning \- Aura Enchanted Death Lords with Holy Freeze = don't bother running; you'll just die tired.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_475_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, nothing is stopping you from going back to NM to farm and/or level more.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_475_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, I'd highly suggest you read some guides on the game... those would have warned you about the ubiquitous elemental immunities in Hell!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_475_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The reason why your Blizzard doesn't seem to be hitting as hard is because even those enemies that aren't immune will often have significant elemental resistances--some points in Cold Mastery will really help with this! [</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_475_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Arreat Summit](http://classic.battle.net/diablo2exp/), [D2 Maxroll.gg](https://d2.maxroll.gg/category/resources), and the [Diablo Wiki](https://diablo2.diablowiki.net/Main_Page) are all great resources.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_475_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Diablo II may be an old game, but it has a surprising level of depth and many less-than-obvious mechanics that you need to be aware of before tackling Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For me, the real flaw of the Great Crusade wasn't what it did to the alien species.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Surely you cannot argue that the Orks, Drukhari, Slaugth, Megarachnids, or Nephilim had **any** interest whatsoever in coexisting peacefully with humanity.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Pretty much every other non-human species in 40K would happily wipe out humanity if given the chance. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Even the Eldar, who are generally the most "reasonable" of the bunch, wouldn't bat an eye at killing 1 billion humans to save 10 of their own kind.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Rather, it was how the new Imperium treated **other human civilisations** outside of Imperial rule. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Angron comments on this in *Betrayer...* and he is disgusted by it.)</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The other human worlds weren't given any choice about whether they wanted to be part of the Imperium, which often meant having their pristine worlds raped by the Mechanicum, sons snatched away to be turned into Astartes (or servitors if they failed), and their best and brightest men and women conscripted into the Imperial Army to be sent to die in some warzone thousands of light-years away just so the Astartes can swoop in and steal the limelight, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I do agree with you about the Emperor not being a particularly nice fellow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>War is hell, but I honestly cannot imagine what use a just ruler would have for sadistic maniacs like the Night Lords.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the Emperor needed assassins, infiltrators, or special operations, the Raven Guard and Alpha Legion could fill the role **much** better and with significantly less flayings of unarmed civilians.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, the Night Lords' methods of compliance *do not work*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They didn't work on Nostramo, and they certainly didn't keep on some of the worlds the Night Lords conquered, especially if the edgy bastards took their eye off the ball.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's interesting that none of the HH authors ever explored this concept, but what the Night Lords' methods would effectively result in is enemies who would fight to the last man.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Ironically, this is something that Honsou, the Iron Warriors Warsmith, understands clearly in M41 (and he criticises his rival Berossus for this).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Because nobody is is going to surrender to the sadistic bastards who just flayed his wife and kids alive and broadcast it on the 8 pm planetwide news network.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And against anyone who had technology capable of penetrating Astartes battleplate (and the Great Crusade did run into civilisations like that), the Night Lords would be in for a lot of unnecessary casualties.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you ask me, the Emperor's biggest mistake wasn't Angron.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It was not having the Space Wolves, Ultramarines, or Alpha Legion wipe out Konrad Curze and all traces of his blighted legion.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Whereas every other Astartes legion had some shreds of nobility and utility in battle, the Night Lords really had none whatsoever.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_476_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They were just murderers and sadists useful for picking on the weak, not soldiers who could break fortresses like their cousins in the other legions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And to be fair, nearly all of those xenos would do *exactly* the same thing to the Imperium if given the chance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Orks tried to, in fact, not long after the Horus Heresy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The real tragedy are the human civilisations that were doing fine on their own after Old Night, and who rejected the Imperum's offer to become vassals and give up their independence (and to some degree, their culture).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Those worlds just wanted to be left alone.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Granted, Big E had his reasons for those brutal conquests.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If those worlds were left alone, they'd eventually be subject to the predations of xenos and, worse yet, Chaos.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_477_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If the Great Crusade had worked (and Erebus had fallen down a reactor shaft, perhaps), then the Emperor would have found a way to shield all of mankind from the Warp... or at least that was his idea.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Were there any examples of "peaceful non-threat" Xenos?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I can't think of any off the top of my head.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I agree with you that it was not a golden age in any absolute sense, but even the term "golden age" itself is highly relative--even in the real world.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Just about any 'golden age' of any civilisation on this planet was still a time of rampant violence, poverty, disease, and oppression for no small number of people living in that time and place.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, Terra was more or less a shithole during the Great Crusade--several Astartes from nicer places like Macragge and Chogoris imply this at various points.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, compared to the state of the Imperium in M41, even before the 13th Black Crusade and Cicatrix Maledictum, the Great Crusade era *was* a golden age in the sense that humanity (at least those on worlds that accepted compliance peacefully) could look forward to the future with a sense of hope that it would be even better.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_478_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In M41, I don't think any human has much hope for the future besides holding onto what they have currently.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_479_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It's quite simple, actually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_479_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Humanity in the 28,000 years since Neil Armstrong's "giant step" essentially built around the site.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_479_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, the fact that it is an *eagle banner* (note that the American flag does *not* have an Eagle on it, and the original flag planted by Armstrong et al.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_479_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>was knocked over by exhaust wash and is likely bleached plain white by now) indicates that someone around the Emperor's time found the original site, and made it into a sort of memorial.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Emperor certainly wasn't a god.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>He did have some powers of foresight, but they were not infallible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That is something the Imperials (starting with Lorgar) got *horribly* wrong.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, with the exception of the Eldar--who again, are *not* nice and friendly any more than humanity is in 40k--pretty much most of the other Xenos were a threat.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Slaugth aren't friendly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Neither are Nephilim... who enjoy enslaving humans and turning them into their mindless servants.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There were, and are worse things than Orks in the 40k/30k galaxy.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There were even alien races who were wholly converted to the worship of Chaos, such as the Laer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maybe my ability to empathize (and my morality) ends at human beings, but to me, the greatest flaws of the fledgling Imperium were how it treated its human subjects, not what it did to some alien species who had no desire to coexist peacefully with mankind.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the Eldar, the existence of the newest Chaos god (Slaanesh) is entirely their fault, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Nevertheless, you can't claim that the Emperor did not have the best interests of humanity (as a whole) in mind, as he clearly knew the threat that Chaos presented.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The Emperor had two big issues: \- He was not good at explaining his plans and motives to his followers \- He was a utilitarian in the extreme sense In any event, I am enjoying this discussion, even if we do not agree on everything :).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_480_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I definitely agree with some of your points, though, especially the Emperor's arrogance.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_481_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>LOL... as soon as I saw the suggestion to use liquid fluroine as an oxydizer, my immediate thought was "oh hell no!"</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_481_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I was laughing by the time I got to the proposed FOOF/Dimethylmercury rocket motor, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_481_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Somehow, I can imagine an Ork Mekboy trying something like that.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_481_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And unfortunately for the Imperium, he'd probably get it to work, too!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_482_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I've had my cube go missing as well on two occasions.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_482_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It was preceded by a game crash.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_482_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Needless to say, it was a major pain in the arse.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_482_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>A recommendation for everyone: get the Halls of the Dead Level 2 WP on each difficulty (or at least on one).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_482_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That way, if you have your 404 cube issue, retrieving a new one wouldn't quite as tedious.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_482_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Without that waypoint, you would potentially need to run/teleport from Lut Gholein through the Rocky Waste to the Dry Hills *and then* locate the Halls of the Dead, or work your way back from whichever desert location waypoint you have (Lost City or Far Oasis).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_483_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>To be fair, the Nails that the World Eaters received were a different model--a reverse-engineered imitation of Angron's implants.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_483_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, a Primarch's brain works differently from that of a normal Legionary... and Angron's implants are shown to have replaced part of his frontal lobes and other neural tissue.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_483_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Removing them would have either killed Angron outright, or reduced him to a vegetable.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_483_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sure, there was a chance that the Emperor could figure out a workaround, especially if he put Arkham Land on the job, but, Big E had a strict timetable, and i guess he didn't want to take the risk of having a permanently incapacitated primarch</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_484_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is an interesting idea... and it has been explored already in literature.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_484_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Read *Crimson Tears* in the Soul Drinkers series.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_484_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;!A certain exiled Drukhari prince has a sort of "if you can't beat her, join her" attitude concerning Slaanesh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_484_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Namely, he doesn't plan on dying anytime soon, and whilst he doesn't exactly worship Slaanesh, he has no qualms about dedicating souls (humans, that is) to She-Who-Thirsts and also working alongside chaos cultists.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_484_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Karhedros' main complaint in life--other than being exiled from Comorragh is that no matter how many mon-keigh he slaughters and tortures, the Imperium doesn't give him any respect!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_484_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They treat him like a nuisance, a minor pirate at best, not a real threat like the way they'd react to even a bunch of Traitor Guardsmen like the Blood Pact. !</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Most* of the Iron Warriors don't actually worship Chaos the way that the Word Bearers or even some members of the Black Legion do.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They don't seem to actually perceive the powers in the Warp as gods like your average Word Bearer.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>However, Iron Warriors certainly don't shun the use of Chaos, nor do they punish or censure legionaries who take it a bit too far.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If Kroeger were a Night Lord in Talos' warband, they'd probably keep him chained up and only unleash him in battle.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, the Warsmith  gt;!(Barbaran Falk)!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>lt; has no issue with allowing Kroeger to walk around, even though he clearly is far from sane.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_485_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, the only really sane ones in that entire warband are Honsou and Forrix.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_486_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The darker palette from the "of Carnage" suffix does indeed make it look distinctive--almost like it is corroded.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_486_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I'm also mildly intrigued that you leave the empty spaces in your inventory on the right.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_486_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I tend to do the exact opposite--cube, charms, and tomes on the right side, and left side of the inventory free :) For me, that makes it a bit faster to pick up and drop items when my inventory is open.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For some builds, Spirit is good enough that you'll be using it well into Hell difficulty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I still haven't found anything better for my level 79 Orbwall Sorc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only superior options I can think of would be a good Death's Fathom, Oculus, or the ful Tal's set (I only have the belt thus far).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But in terms of uniques and sets, I feel that the following items are worth holding onto for the semi-long term: 1.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Magefist (unique light gauntlets).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+1 Fire skills and +20 FCR is great for many Sorc builds, and even some other caster builds as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Angelic Wings and Angelic Halo (Angelic Raiment set ammy and ring).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Massive AR bonus for melee builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Goblin Toe (unique light plated boots).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Until you get Gore Rider, Goblin Toe is a great source of Crushing Blow.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only downside to it is the lack of FRW.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Goldwrap (unique heavy belt).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Upgrade it if you want 4 rows and don't mind needing 88 strength.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It is a great addition to any MF set even into the endgame.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Gull (unique dagger).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>+100 MF is self-explanatory!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sander's Riprap (Sander's Folly set boots)--If you don't need resists or CB from your boots, having +40% FRW is always helpful.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You can replace these with Waterwalks or Sandstorm Trek down the line.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_487_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sander's Taboo (Sander's Folly set gloves)--Until you get Laying of Hands or some other gloves with decent IAS, these can work well for melee builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Biggest tip I can offer is **do not neglect elemental resistances:** ***especially Lightning and Fire***.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Try to keep these maxed whenever possible.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Cold and poison are more easily dealt with and you can get by without maximum cold and poison, usually.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Maximum resistance is 75%, although certain skills (e.g. Paladin's Resist Fire, Cold, and Lightning auras) and items can raise this cap.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, a good way to navigate the maps in Act I is to follow the paths (in the outdoor zones).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>These will usually lead you to where you need to go.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Finally, make sure to locate the waypoint in each zone that has one--although certain waypoints like the Jail Lvl 2 aren't really worth getting.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_488_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This will save you *a lot* of running when you revisit areas.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>You'll be fine throughout Normal and at least the first 1/3 of NM even playing entirely SSF (solo self found) even as a Barbarian.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Where you *might* run into trouble is in late NM and definitely Hell difficulties.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Besides, if you ever hit a wall or get bored of your Barbarian, nothing is stopping you from rolling another class.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In fact, if you keep finding a lot of good items for another class, that might be a good motivation to try that class!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In Normal, though, you will likely hit two notable walls (both easily surmountable, however): \- The Act II boss (hint--chug a few thawing potions before hand, equip a fast, high-damaging weapon, and bring as many rejuvenation potions, i.e. the purple ones, as you can just in case) \- The Act IV boss (hint--he loves fire and lightning, so make sure your fire and lightning resists are close to max.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also, hit and run is your friend here) Finally, when it comes to items, the following things are worth holding onto if you find them \- Crushflange unique mace \- Goblin Toe unique light plated boots \- grey flails with 2 sockets... along with an Amn and Tir rune What do all these have in common?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Crushing blow, which, when it procs, will allow you to instantly shave off up to 25% of the target's remaining life (the amount removed will depend on the target type).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_489_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Make sure to get a source of crushing blow as a way to take down bosses fast!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_490_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>One doesn't need to be insane in order to be an evil, ruthless bastard like Honsou is.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_490_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>After all, Honsou's actions are generally quite rational, even though they are shockingly depraved.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_490_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As for the Daemonculaba, those horrific creations had a very rational purpose: to create new Iron Warriors to help fill out the warband.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_490_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>In terms of sanity, it's arguable that Honsou certainly has his faculties in check far more than his erstwhile comrades like Kroeger and Berossus.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_490_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Although it's also arguable that Toramino is also quite sane, and Soltarn Vull Bron is still around even after the Horus Heresy, if I recall correctly.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_490_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Still, we never do learn what happened to Toramino after the events of *Dead Sky, Black Sun*.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>**Answer to Question 2**: your Merc has some nice gear... but no life leech whatsoever!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you want him to stay alive longer, consider replacing that Rockstopper with a helm that provides life leech, such as Vampire Gaze, Andariel's Visage (add a Ral rune to offset that nasty -30% fire resist!),</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>or even Wormskull and Undead Crown.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Also get used to teleporting around to pull your merc out of trouble.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>If you are not a Sorc, you'll want to keep an item with Teleport charges--this can be a Staff of Teleport, the unique bearded axe Spellsteel, Naj's Puzzler, or just an amulet with teleport charges.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Or Enigma... which you might have already, since you already have an Infinity on your Merc, eheh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Your merc is useful in Hell (and before) largely for two reasons: aura support, and for killing things that are immune to your primary damage sources.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>As a Zealadin in Hell, I don't *really* need my Merc since anything I cannot kill, he wouldn't be able to deal with either!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But I try to keep him alive since his Blessed Aim aura helps my AR; he provides additional damage, and besides, Waheed is a nice guy, lol.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>By contrast, my Summonmancer, Trapsin, and Orbwall Sorc don't tend to do quite as well without their Mercs, heh. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Answer to Question 3**: Open wounds (available as an affix on certain uniques and runewords, e.g. Malice) also has the same effect.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And unlike poison, nothing is immune or resistant to it.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>There is, of course, the "Prevent Monster Heal," but this doesn't apply to super unique monsters, which includes the Ubers (in Uber Tristram), Act Bosses, etc.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Moreover, Smite can inflict open wounds... but it won't inflict poison damage from your charms.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_14</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And since Smite has no AR (and always hits), this can make Open Wounds a better option for preventing monster heal in some cases. **</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_15</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Answer to Question 4**: Pretty much every weapon type has at least *one* useful or desirable item in its class.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_16</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>When you say Tulwar, I immediately think of the Blade of Ali Baba, which is a great item for MF characters!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_17</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Buriza do-Kyanon is a crossbow... and a good weapon for an Amazon.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_18</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Druids get rather swift attack speeds with many 2h axes as well.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_19</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The *only* weapon type which I think is somewhat lacking in usefulness are daggers overall, and even then, there are some great daggers like Gull (for MF) and Wizardspike (for FCR and resistances).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_20</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Generally, you aren't going to be running around shanking things with a dagger, though!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_21</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>What is a good weapon for you will depend on your build, the item's properties, and its affixes.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_22</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>For example, Spirit is a great weapon for many caster builds.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_491_23</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>It isn't such a great choice for a Frenzy Barbarian, though, even if you made it in a Phase Blade--the affixes from this runeword (other than the 55% FHR and maybe the 7% life leech) don't benefit melee characters very much.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Definitely.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Sanity is... relative.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That said, I'm not sure you could call some Inquisitors (like Kryptman) fully sane, either.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>At least not in the sense of normal, well-adjusted people you'd want to live next door to.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Unfortunately, as far as Iron Warriors go, Honsou is arguably among the more reasonable of that bad lot.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_5</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Read *The Siege of Castellax* to see what is considered normal among Iron Warriors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_6</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;!Stuff like rendering the bodies of dead slaves down into protein paste to feed to the surviving slaves, and dropping tactical nukes on their own captured workforce to prevent them from falling into Ork hands, that's just a normal Thursday for the Iron Warriors.!</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_7</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>lt; One could even argue that in some ways, the Iron Warriors are *more* evil than the Word Bearers.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_8</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The latter definitely do some horrific things, but the Word Bearers somehow, in their own twisted way, believe that what they are doing is just and holy, to serve the true "gods" of Chaos. (</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_9</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>And not serving the Ruinous Powers would result in mankind going the same way as the Eldar, at least the Word Bearers believe).</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_10</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>But the Iron Warriors?</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_11</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They don't believe in any "higher" cause.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_12</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>I doubt they even have any illusions that they are still the "good guys."</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_492_13</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>They just do those atrocities in the name of expedience.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_493_0</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>Corpse starch is just that--a meme that got out of hand, heh.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_493_1</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>The only Imperial faction that would do anything close to the level Soylent Green that the Iron Warriors engage in is the Adeptus Mechanicus, and even then, they are just being eco-friendly by feeding the organic remains of broken down servitors to other servitors.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_493_2</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>That isn't to say that the Mechanicus is **anywhere** near ethical, though.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_493_3</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT> gt;!On Hydra Cordatus, they were deliberately inducing cancerous tumours in the Guardsmen stationed there to ensure that no one serving on that planet would outlive his or her tour of duty.</TEXT>
        </DOC>
        <DOC>
            	<DOCNO>s_1771_493_4</DOCNO>
            	<TEXT>This was all to keep the secret repository of Imperial Fists gene seed classified. !</TEXT>
        </DOC>
